{"title_page": "Exene Cervenka", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer, artist, and poet|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name = Exene Cervenka\n| background = solo_singer\n| image = Exene.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Exene Cervenka at [[The Chestnut Cabaret]] in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] on July 30, 1986\n| birth_name = Christene Lee Cervenka\n| alias = Exene, Exene Cervenkov\u00e1<br>Christine Notmyrealname\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1956|02|01}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago]], Illinois, U.S.\n| origin = [[Los Angeles]], California\n| death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place = \n| genre = {{flatlist|\n*[[Punk rock|Punk]]\n*[[folk music|folk]]\n*[[Rock music|rock]]}}\n| occupation = Singer-songwriter, poet, musician, [[visual artist]]\n| instrument = {{flatlist|\n*Vocals\n*guitar}}\n| years_active = 1978\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n*[[Bloodshot Records|Bloodshot]]\n*[[Rhino Records|Rhino]]\n*[[Kill Rock Stars]]\n*[[Nitro Records|Nitro]]\n*[[2.13.61]]\n*[[Rykodisc]]\n*Freeway}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n*[[X (American band)|X]]\n*[[The Knitters]]\n*[[John Doe (musician)|John Doe]]\n*[[Auntie Christ]]\n*The Original Sinners}}\n| website = {{URL|exenecervenka.net}}\n| children = [[Henry Mortensen]]\n}}\n'''Exene Cervenka''' (born '''Christene Lee Cervenka'''; February 1, 1956) is an American singer, artist, and poet.  She is best known for her work as a singer in the California [[punk rock]] band [[X (American band)|X]].<ref name=AllMusic-bio>{{cite web|last=Prato|first=Greg|title=Exene Cervenka: Biography |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/exene-cervenka-mn0000160993/biography|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=February 2, 2014}}</ref> Her surname is pronounced as \"''czer-vehn-kuh''\".\n\n== Music career ==\n \n[[File:Exene Cervenka 2010.jpg|thumb|Cervenka at SXSW 2010]]\n \t\nThe 21-year-old Cervenka met 23-year-old musician [[John Doe (musician)|John Doe]] at a poetry workshop at the [[Beyond Baroque Literary Arts Center|Beyond Baroque Foundation]] in [[Venice, California]].<ref name=VVoice-Interview-2008 /> Cervenka started working there.<ref name=Exene-BlogTalk-2013>{{cite web|title=Exene Cervenka \u2013 Singer, songwriter, poet, artist|url=http://www.blogtalkradio.com/storytellers/2013/07/03/exene-cervenka--singer-songwriter-poet-artist|work=Storytellers|publisher=Blog Talk Radio|accessdate=February 2, 2014|format=audio interview|date=July 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBilly Zoom and John Doe founded X in 1977.<ref name=\"rockerzine.com\">{{cite web|author=Keith Valcourt |url=http://www.rockerzine.com/index.php/2011/03/exene-cervenka-high-priestess-of-punk/ |title=Exene Cervenka: High Priestess Of Punk |website=Rockerzine.com |date=2011-03-30 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> Doe asked Cervenka to join soon after. They released their debut album, ''[[Los Angeles (X album)|Los Angeles]],'' in 1980 and, over the next six years, five more albums.\n \t\n[[Dave Alvin]] taught Cervenka how to play the guitar.<ref name=SunBreak-2010>{{cite web|last=Kay|first=Tony|title=More Fun in the New World: Exene Cervenka of X, Interviewed|url=http://www.thesunbreak.com/2010/04/20/more-fun-in-the-new-world-exene-cervenka-of-x-interviewed|work=[[The SunBreak]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100424201848/http://www.thesunbreak.com/2010/04/20/more-fun-in-the-new-world-exene-cervenka-of-x-interviewed|archivedate=April 24, 2010|date=April 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\t\n=== Collaborations ===\n\t\nIn 1982, Cervenka published ''Adulterers Anonymous'', her first in a series of four books in collaboration with artist [[Lydia Lunch]]. She and Lunch also released a spoken word album, ''Rude Hieroglyphics'', in 1996 and toured in support of the project.<ref name=NYT-2RockQueens-1982>{{cite news|last=Palmer|first=Robert|title=The Pop Life; 2 Rock Queens Turn to Literature|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/11/03/arts/the-pop-life-2-rock-queens-turn-to-literature.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=November 3, 1982}}</ref>\n \nFrom 1996 to 1999, [[John Roecker]] and Cervenka co-owned Los Angeles store \"You've Got Bad Taste.\" The store specialized in kitsch and various \"off-color\" novelties.<ref name=NYT-YGGT-closed-1999>{{cite news|title=Business: Diary; Who Says 'Nobody Ever Went Broke . . . '?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/21/business/business-diary-who-says-nobody-ever-went-broke.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=March 21, 1999}}</ref><ref name=LAWkly-Roek-2006>{{cite news|last=Lecaro|first=Lina|title=Punk Puppet Apocalypse|url=http://www.laweekly.com/2006-03-02/news/punk-puppet-apocalypse/|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[LA Weekly]]|date=February 28, 2006}}</ref>\n\t\nIn 1999, as '''Exene \u010cervenkov\u00e1,''' she appeared in the cult video ''Decoupage 2000: Return of the Goddess,'' along with guests [[Karen Black]] and the band [[L7 (band)|L7]]. She gave a reading of her poem \"They Must Be Angels,\" and appeared in an interview skit with ''Decoupage 2000'' hostess Summer Caprice.<ref name=decoupage2000 />\n\n== Art career ==\nIn 2005, Cervenka's journals and mixed media collages were exhibited in a one-person exhibition titled ''America the Beautiful'' at the [[Santa Monica Museum of Art]]. The exhibit was curated by [[Kristine McKenna]] and Michael Duncan. An expanded version of the exhibition traveled to [[DCKT Contemporary]] in New York in January 2006.\n\n== Personal life ==\nCervenka was married to [[John Doe (musician)|John Doe]] from 1980 to 1985. She met her second husband [[Viggo Mortensen]] in 1986 on the set of the comedy ''[[Salvation! (1987 film)|Salvation!]]'', a parody of [[televangelism]]. Mortensen played her husband Jerome. They married on July 8, 1987. On January 28, 1988, Cervenka gave birth to a son, Henry Blake Mortensen. Mortensen and Cervenka lived in Idaho for three years.<ref name=VVoice-Interview-2008>{{cite news|last=Trucks|first=Rob|title=Interview: Exene Cervenka of X|url=http://blogs.villagevoice.com/music/2008/05/interview_exene.php|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[Village Voice]]|date=May 20, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203113106/http://blogs.villagevoice.com/music/2008/05/interview_exene.php|archivedate=February 3, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> They separated in 1992, and were divorced in 1997.<ref name=NYT-Tmag-Viggo-2011>{{cite news|last=Heller|first=Zoe|title=Viggo Talks and Talks|url=http://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/12/02/viggo-talks-and-talks/|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nCervenka married musician Jason Edge, who went on to play in her band, Original Sinners.<ref name=Swindle-2008>{{cite web|last=Yokoland|title=Exene Cervenka |url=http://swindlemagazine.com/issueicons/exene-cervenka/ |work=Swindle Magazine|accessdate=February 2, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080228172558/http://swindlemagazine.com/issueicons/exene-cervenka/|archivedate=February 28, 2008}}</ref> Edge and Cervenka are now divorced.<ref name=NashScene-SGone-2010>{{cite news|last=McCall|first=Michael|title=Somewhere Gone from Exene Cervenka|url=http://www.nashvillescene.com/nashville/somewhere-gone-from-exene-cervenka/Content?oid=1227039|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[Nashville Scene]]|date=February 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nCervenka moved from Los Angeles to [[Jefferson City, Missouri]]<ref name=VVoice-Interview-2008 /> for four years, and then returned to Southern California.<ref name=LATimes-KeepingUp-2009>{{cite news|last=Lewis|first=Randy|title=Keeping up with Exene Cervenka|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/06/entertainment/et-exene-cervenka6|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[L.A. Times]]|date=October 6, 2009}}</ref> She now lives in Orange County.<ref name=OCReg-2011>{{cite news|last=Fadroski|first=Kelli Skye|title=Exene tells it straight on X, illness and O.C.|url=http://www.ocregister.com/soundcheck/http-481809-ocregister-people.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[Orange County Register]]|date=June 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=Riverfront-2009>{{cite news|last=Zaleski|first=Annie|title=Somewhere Out There: Exene Cervenka's new solo record, Somewhere Gone, has strong roots in Missouri|url=http://www.riverfronttimes.com/2009-10-21/music/somewhere-out-there-exene-cervenka-new-solo-record-somewhere-gone-strong-roots-missouri/|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[Riverfront Times]]|date=October 21, 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nOn June 2, 2009, Cervenka released a statement revealing that she had been diagnosed with [[multiple sclerosis]].<ref name=Exene-BS-Statement2009>{{cite web|title=A Statement from Exene Cervenka|url=https://www.bloodshotrecords.com/news/statement-exene-cervenka|work=Bloodshot Records|accessdate=February 2, 2014|date=June 2, 2009}}</ref><ref name=CLoaf-DespiteMS->{{cite web|last=Radford |first=Chad |title=Despite her MS diagnosis, Exene Cervenka lives for the moment |url=http://clatl.com/gyrobase/despite_her_ms_diagnosis_exene_cervenka_lives_for_the_moment/Content?oid=1341934 |work=[[Creative Loafing]] |publisher=Creative Loafing Atlanta |accessdate=February 2, 2014 |date=February 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140218231713/http://clatl.com/gyrobase/despite_her_ms_diagnosis_exene_cervenka_lives_for_the_moment/Content?oid=1341934 |archivedate=February 18, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref> Well before this diagnosis, she and X have actively supported [[Sweet Relief Fund|Sweet Relief]], a charity that aids uninsured artists. Sweet Relief was begun by musician [[Victoria Williams]] when she herself was diagnosed with MS.<ref name=ExeneStatement-2009>{{cite web|last=Cervenka|first=Exene|title=A Statement from Exene Cervenka |url=http://www.exenecervenka.com/exenemessage.html |work=ExeneCervenka.com |accessdate=February 2, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730043658/http://www.exenecervenka.com/exenemessage.html|archivedate=July 30, 2010|date=June 2, 2009}}</ref> In 2011, Cervenka said she may have been misdiagnosed.<ref name=OCReg-2011 /><ref name=LAWkly-Returns-2006>{{cite news|last=Ohanesian|first=Liz|title=Exene Cervenka Returns to Southern California|url=http://www.laweekly.com/westcoastsound/2009/10/06/exene-cervenka-returns-to-southern-california|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[LA Weekly]]|date=October 6, 2006}}</ref> However, Cervenka had to cancel a Spring 2011 tour due to problems associated with her MS.<ref name=Bloodshot-Tour-2011>{{cite web|title=Exene Cervenka Cancels Tour|url=https://www.bloodshotrecords.com/news/exene-cervenka-cancels-tour|work=Bloodshot Records|accessdate=February 2, 2014|date=April 4, 2011}}</ref> During a July 2015 interview, John Doe said that the multiple sclerosis diagnosis was a misdiagnosis, that Cervenka, after consulting with various doctors who were not able to diagnose her, is healthy.<ref name=Diffuser-Doe-2015>{{cite news|last1=Stafford|first1=James|title=In Conversation With X's John Doe|url=http://diffuser.fm/in-conversation-with-x-john-doe/|accessdate=30 July 2015|work=[[Diffuser.fm]]|date=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Conspiracy theories ===\nCervenka, as a self-styled \"conspiracy therapist,\" has provoked controversy on social media and on YouTube, under the name \"Christine Notmyrealname,\" by advancing conspiracy theories including the view that the [[2014 Isla Vista killings|Isla Vista shootings]] were a hoax designed to bring about stricter gun control laws. After the backlash, she has issued an apology on her Facebook and Twitter accounts and her conspiracy related YouTube videos are no longer available for viewing.<ref name=Radio-SBHoax-2014>{{cite web|title='80s Punk Star Exene Cervenka Claims Santa Barbara Shooting Was a Hoax|url=http://radio.com/2014/05/28/80s-punk-star-exene-cervenka-claims-santa-barbara-shooting-was-a-hoax/|website=Radio.com|accessdate=June 5, 2014|date=May 28, 2014}}</ref><ref name=IBT-SB-2014>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Eric|title=X Singer Exene Cervenka's Santa Barbara Shooting Conspiracy Theory Is One of Many|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/x-singer-exene-cervenkas-santa-barbara-shooting-conspiracy-theory-one-many-1592880|website=[[International Business Times]]|accessdate=June 5, 2014|date=June 1, 2014}}</ref><ref name=MercNews-SBHoax-2014>{{cite news|last1=Hicks|first1=Tony|title=Punk legend Exene Cervenka calls Santa Barbara shooting 'hoax'|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/entertainment/ci_25859992/punk-legend-exene-cervenka-calls-santa-barbara-shooting|accessdate=June 5, 2014|work=[[Contra Costa Times]]|date=May 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== X ===\n\n==== Singles, soundtracks, compilations, etc. ====\n* 1978: ''Adult Books/We're Desperate'' 7\" ([[Dangerhouse Records]])\n* 1979: ''Yes L.A.'' compilation (Dangerhouse Records)\n* 1980: ''[[The Decline of Western Civilization]]'' soundtrack (Spheeris Films/[[Slash Records]]): \"Beyond and Back,\" \"Johnny Hit and Run Paulene,\" \"Nausea,\" \"Unheard Music,\" \"We're Desperate\"\n* 1980: ''No Questions Asked'' by Flesh Eaters (Slash Records)\n* 1982: ''[[Urgh! A Music War]]'' soundtrack ([[A&M Records]])\n\n==== Albums ====\n* 1980: ''[[Los Angeles (X album)|Los Angeles]]'' (Slash Records)\n* 1981: ''[[Wild Gift]]'' (Slash Records)<ref name=NYTimes-XGrow-1982>{{cite news|last=Palmer|first=Robert|title=Pop Life; New Album Shows X Has Grown|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/23/arts/pop-life-new-album-shows-x-has-grown.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 23, 1982}}</ref>\n* 1982: ''[[Under the Big Black Sun]]'' ([[Elektra Records]])\n* 1983: ''[[More Fun in the New World]]'' (Elektra Records)\n* 1985: ''[[Ain't Love Grand!]]'' (Elektra Records)\n* 1987: ''[[See How We Are]]'' (Elektra Records/[[Asylum Records]])\n* 1988: ''[[Live at the Whisky a Go-Go (X album)|Live at the Whisky a Go-Go]]'' (Elektra/Asylum Records)\n* 1993: ''[[Hey Zeus!]]'' ([[Big Life Records]])\n* 1995: ''[[Unclogged]]'' (Infidelity Recordings/Sunset Boulevard)<ref name=NYT-DoeExeneCountry-1995>{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|title=Pop Review; John Doe and Exene Go a Little Bit Country|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/20/arts/pop-review-john-doe-and-exene-go-a-little-bit-country.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 20, 1995}}</ref>\n* 1997: ''[[Beyond and Back: The X Anthology]]'' (Elektra Records)\n* 2004: ''[[The Best: Make the Music Go Bang!]]'' (Elektra Records/[[Rhino Records]])\n* 2005: ''X \u2013 Live in Los Angeles'' ([[Shout! Factory]])\n\n=== The Knitters ===\n* 1985: ''[[Poor Little Critter on the Road]]'' (Slash Records/Rhino Records)\n* 2005: ''[[The Modern Sounds of the Knitters]]'' (Zo\u00eb Records)\n\n=== Solo ===\n* 1989: ''Old Wives' Tales'' (Rhino Records)<ref name=NYTimes-HalfX-1989>{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|title=Reviews/Music; Half of X Equals Cervenka|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/10/29/arts/reviews-music-half-of-x-equals-cervenka.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 29, 1989}}</ref>\n* 1990: ''Running Sacred'' (RNA (Rhino New Artists))\n* 1994: ''Exene Cervenka'' (Wordcore Volume 7) 7\" ([[Kill Rock Stars]])\n* 1995: ''Surface To Air Serpents'' (213CD/[[Thirsty Ear Recordings]])\n* 2009: ''Somewhere Gone'' ([[Bloodshot Records]])<ref name=HoustonPress-2010>{{cite news|last=Gray|first=Chris|title=Inquiring Minds: Exene Cervenka on Losing a Friend, Weeping Willows, Albums as Collage and Her Good Buddy Biscuit|url=http://blogs.houstonpress.com/rocks/2010/01/rocks_off_where_did_this.php|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=Houston Press|date=January 27, 2010}}</ref>\n* 2011: ''The Excitement of Maybe'' (Bloodshot Records)<ref name=AMP-2011>{{cite web|last=Steffens|first=Charlie|title=An Interview with Exene Cervenka|url=http://charliesteffens.com/an-interview-with-exene-cervenka/|work=[[AMP (magazine)|AMP]]|accessdate=February 2, 2014|date=March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203181246/http://charliesteffens.com/an-interview-with-exene-cervenka/|archivedate=February 3, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==== Bands ====\n* 1997: ''Life Could Be A Dream'' as [[Auntie Christ]] ([[Lookout Records]])\n* 2002: ''Original Sinners'' as Original Sinners ([[Nitro Records]])\n* 2006: ''Sev7en'' as Exene Cervenka and the Original Sinners (Nitro Records)\n\n==== Other ====\n* 1985: Wanda Coleman, Exene Cervenka: ''Twin Sisters'' LP (Freeway). Poetry performance recorded at [[McCabe's Guitar Shop]], Santa Monica, CA on February 1, 1985.\n* 1995: Lydia Lunch & Exene Cervenka: ''Rude Hieroglyphics'' ([[Rykodisc]]). Recorded live at the Sapphire Supper Club, Orlando, FL on March 20, 1995.\n* 1999: ''Decoupage 2000: Return of the Goddess.'' Read poem \"They Must Be Angels\" and appeared in an interview skit.<ref name=decoupage2000>{{cite web |url=http://www.decoupagetv.com/tomorrow.html |title=Decoupage 2000 |publisher=Decoupagetv.com |accessdate=January 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709005346/http://www.decoupagetv.com/tomorrow.html |archivedate=July 9, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* 2012: John Doe & Exene Cervenka: ''Singing and Playing'' (Moonlight Graham Records). Recorded at Way Station April 2\u20133, 2010.<ref name=KCET-ExeneRulesGraham-2012>{{cite web|last=Bose|first=Lilledeshan|title=How Exene Cervenka Came to Rule Over the Boy's Club|url=http://www.kcet.org/arts/artbound/counties/orange/moonlight-graham.html|work=[[KCET]]|publisher=KCETLink|accessdate=February 2, 2014|date=May 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Additional musical contributions ===\n* 1994: Applegate, Christina, and Elizabeth Pena. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/32411773 Across the Moon.]'' Los Angeles, CA: Hemdale Home Video, 1994. {{ISBN|978-1-569-20068-1}} Music composed by Christopher Tyng & Exene Cervenka\n* 1996: ''Honor: A Benefit for the Honor the Earth Campaign'' ([[Daemon Records]]). \"The Future is a War\" by Exene Cervenka\n* 1997: ''[[G.I. Jane]]'' original soundtrack ([[Hollywood Records]]). \"The Future is a War\" by Auntie Christ\n* 1999: ''One Man's Meat'' by [[Viggo Mortensen]] (Lightning Creek). Features Exene Cervenka on vocals, guitar\n* 2000: ''[[Stoned Immaculate: The Music of The Doors]]'' (Elektra Records). \"Children of Night\" by [[Perry Farrell]] and Exene\n* 2001: ''Punk-o-rama 2001, Vol. 6'' ([[Epitaph Records]]). \"We're Desperate\" by Pennywise with Exene\n* 2002: ''Rise Above: 24 Black Flag Songs to Benefit the West Memphis Three'' ([[Sanctuary Records Group|Sanctuary]]). \"Wasted\" by Exene Cervenka\n* 2009: ''[[The People Speak (film)|The People Speak]]'' original soundtrack ([[Verve Records]]). \"See How We Are\" by Exene Cervenka & John Doe\n* 2011: ''Kings and Queens'' by [[Blackie and the Rodeo Kings]] ([[Dramatico]]). \"Made of Love\" featuring Exene Cervenka\n*2018 \"Queen For A Day\" by [[Skating Polly]] featuring and also written by Exene Cervenka\n\n=== Video ===\n* ''[[The Decline of Western Civilization]]'' (1981)\n* ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/466135850 Urgh! A Music War]'' (1982)\n* ''[[X: The Unheard Music]]'' (1985/1987, video; 1986/1987/2004, DVD; re-released 2011 Silver Anniversary Edition)<ref name=NYT-UnheardMusic-1986>{{cite news|last=Maslin|first=Janet|title=Film: 'Unheard Music'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/21/movies/film-unheard-music.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 21, 1986}}</ref>\n* ''[[X - Live in Los Angeles]]'' (2005) \u2013 [[Shout! Factory]]: Concert by X in Los Angeles recorded live on November 26 and 27, 2004 {{ISBN|978-0-738-93185-2}}\n\n== Works or publications ==\n* Lunch, Lydia, and Exene Cervenka. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/8669443 Adulterers Anonymous.]'' New York: Grove Press, 1982. {{ISBN|978-0-394-62412-9}}\n* ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/849679557 The 1984 Calendar of Olympic Games, Music & Orwellian Dates.]'' 1984, n.d.. Produced by M. Hyatt, Exene Cervenka and 53 mail artists from around the world.\n* ''[http://www.baddaymovie.com/ Bad Day: A Short Film by Modi Frank and Exene Cervenka.]'' (1986)<ref name=BadDay-PDF>{{cite web|title=Kevin Costner in a \"Lost\" Western Movie Found and Released Exclusively Online|url=http://www.baddaymovie.com/BadDayMediaRelease08-01-10.pdf|work=Bad Day Movie|accessdate=February 2, 2014}}</ref><ref name=HuffPo-BadDay-Costner-2010>{{cite news|last=Derrick|first=Lisa|title=Bad Day: Kevin Costner's Secret Movie Released Online|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/lisa-derrick/bad-day-kevin-costers-sec_b_652740.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[Huffington Post]]|date=July 20, 2010}}</ref>\n* Mohr, Bill, and Sheree Levin. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/12924592 Poetry Loves Poetry: An Anthology of Los Angeles Poets.]'' Santa Monica, CA: Momentum Press, 1985. {{ISBN|978-0-936-05450-6}}<ref name=LAT-PoetryLovesPoetry-1986>{{cite news|last=Bartruff|first=James|title=Fiction : Poetry Loves Poetry, edited by Bill Mohr; photographs by Sheree Levin.|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-08-17/books/bk-16474_1_bill-mohr|accessdate=February 1, 2014|newspaper=[[L.A. Times]]|date=August 17, 1986}}</ref>\n* Jarecke, Kenneth, and Exene Cervenka. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/28606930 Just Another War.]'' Joliet, Mont: Bedrock Press, 1992. {{ISBN|978-0-963-47840-5}}<ref name=ShavedNeck2002>{{cite web|title=Exene Cervenka Interview|url=http://www.shavedneck.com/ExeneCervenkaInterviewKZSU.htm|work=Shaved Neck|accessdate=February 2, 2014|date=June 26, 2002}}</ref>\n* Cervenka, Exene. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/30623984 Virtual Unreality.]'' Los Angeles: 2.13.61 Publications, 1993. {{ISBN|978-1-880-98515-1}}\n* Cervenka, Exene. \"Consumption.\" ''[[Details Magazine]],'' July 1993. (poem)\n* Cervenka, Exene. \"Acres of Defeat.\" ''[[Raygun Magazine]],'' Dec./Jan 1993. (article)\n* Cervenka, Exene. \"Midnight Black.\" ''[[L.A. Weekly]]'' Magazine, Best of L.A. Issue, 1993. (poem)\n* Lake, Bambi, and Alvin Orloff. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/34618232 The Unsinkable Bambi Lake: A Fairy Tale Containing the Dish on Cockettes, Punks, and Angels.]'' San Francisco: Manic D Press, 1996. {{ISBN|978-0-916-39742-5}} Introduction by Exene Cervenka\n* Snowden, Don, and Gary Leonard. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/36916508 Make the Music Go Bang!: The Early L.A. Punk Scene.]'' New York: St. Martin's Griffin, 1997. {{ISBN|978-0-312-16912-1}} \"Halos Above Our Horns\" by Exene Cervenkova. (essay)\n* Rollins, Henry. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/41257257 The Best of 2.13.61 Publications.]'' Los Angeles: 2.13.61 Publications, 1998. {{ISBN|978-1-880-98562-5}} (excerpts from \"Virtual Unreality\")\n* Maybe, Ellyn, and Exene Cervenka. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/39609378 The Cowardice of Amnesia.]'' Los Angeles: 2.13.61 Publications, 1998. {{ISBN|978-1-880-98558-8}}\n* Hyatt, Michael, and Exene Cervenka. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/781450801 Lucky 13 Postcards.]'' Los Angeles, Calif: s.n., 2000.\n* Cervenka, Exene. ''A Beer on Every Page.'' 2002.\n* Jocoy, Jim, Thurston Moore, and Exene Cervenka. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/49648198 We're Desperate: The Punk Photography of Jim Jocoy : SF/LA 78\u201380.]'' New York, NY: PowerHouse Books, 2002. {{ISBN|978-1-576-87156-0}} \"Slivery Moon\" (essay)\n* Kihn, Greg. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/52155535 Carved in Rock: Short Stories by Musicians.]'' New York: Thunder's Mouth Press, 2003. {{ISBN|978-1-560-25453-9}} features short story \"Perfect World from Virtual Unreality\" by Exene Cervenka\n* Cervenka, Exene, and Viggo Mortensen. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/123481820 Magical Meteorite Songwriting Device: Collages.]'' Santa Monica, CA: Perceval Press, 2006. {{ISBN|978-0-976-30092-2}}<ref name=NYT-Viggo-Pub-2006>{{cite news|last=Maslin|first=Janet|title=Viggo Mortensen's Unusual Role: Indie Publishing Mogul|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/01/movies/01viggo.html?fta=y|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 1, 2006}}</ref>\n\n=== Exhibitions ===\n\n==== One-person exhibitions ====\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20140204014022/https://smmoa.org/programs-and-exhibitions/exene-cervenka-america-the-beautiful/ America the Beautiful.]'' [[Santa Monica Museum of Art]] (September 17 \u2013 November 26, 2005)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20140226164700/http://www.dcktcontemporary.com/artists/1734/collections/134 America the Beautiful.]'' [[DCKT Contemporary]] (January 7 \u2013 February 11, 2006)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20140203114431/http://www.western-project.com/2007/12/09/exene-cervenka-a-fifth-of-tomorrow-collages-and-journals/ A Fifth of Tomorrow.]'' Collages and journals. Western Project (June 9 \u2013 July 14, 2007)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20140226170950/http://www.dcktcontemporary.com/artists/1734/collections/112 Sleep in Spite of Thunder.]'' DCKT Contemporary (May 23 \u2013 July 18, 2008)\n\n==== Two-person exhibitions ====\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20140203140038/http://www.western-project.com/2009/12/09/exene-cervenka-and-wayne-white-were-not-the-jet-set-2009/ Exene Cervenka and Wayne White: We're Not The Jet Set.]'' Paintings, collages and sculptures. Western Project (July 25 \u2013 September 5, 2009)\n\n==== Group exhibitions ====\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20100428023030/http://www.markmooregallery.com/exhibitions/1998-12-05_hollywood-satan/ Hollywood Satan.]'' Mark Moore Gallery, Santa Monica, CA (December 5\u201325, 1998)\n* ''[http://www.track16.com/exhibitions/punk/punk.html Forming: The Early Days of L.A. Punk.]'' Track 16 Gallery, Santa Monica, CA (April 10 \u2013 June 15, 1999)\n* ''[http://www.track16.com/exhibitions/capital/capital.html Capital Art: On the Culture of Punishment.]'' Track 16 Gallery, Santa Monica, CA (February 3 \u2013 March 31, 2001)\n* ''Cruel And Unusual: A Benefit For The West Memphis Three.'' sixspace, Los Angeles, CA (2003)\n* ''[http://claremontmuseum.org/vexing-female-voices-from-east-la-punk/ Vexing: Female Voices from East L.A. Punk.]'' Claremont Museum of Art, Claremont, CA (May 18 \u2013 August 31, 2008); Museo de las Artes, Universidad de Guadalajara, Guadalajara, Mexico (2008\u20132009)\n* Yard Dog, Austin, TX (2009)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20111020135033/http://www.cafam.org/CelestialAsh.html Celestial Ash: Assemblages from Los Angeles.]'' Craft and Folk Art Museum, Los Angeles, CA (April 11 \u2013 September 13, 2009)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20140203122400/http://www.western-project.com/2009/11/07/western-project-the-first-six-years-group-show-2009/ Western Project: The First Six Years.]'' Western Project, Culver City, CA (November 7 \u2013 December 30, 2009)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20140203150529/http://www.western-project.com/2010/08/14/tanya-batura-exene-cervenka-amir-h-fallah-will-yackulic-2010/ Tanya Batura / Exene Cervenka / Amir H. Fallah / Will Yackulic.]'' Western Project, Culver City, CA (August 14 \u2013 September 11, 2010)\n* ''[http://www.nolongerempty.org/nc/home/what-we-do/exhibitions/exhibition/never-can-say-goodbye/ Never Can Say Goodbye, No Longer Empty.]'' at former Tower Records Store, West 4th Street & Broadway, New York, NY (2010)\n* ''Girls Just Want to Have Funds.'' P.P.O.W Gallery, New York, NY (2010)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20140226155322/http://www.dcktcontemporary.com/exhibitions/1491 DCKT @ Miami Project.]'' Midtown Art District (December 3\u20138, 2013)\n\n==== Exhibition catalogs ====\n* Bessy, Claude, and Edward Colver. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/44466013 Forming: The Early Days of L.A. Punk.]'' Santa Monica, CA: Smart Art Press, 2000. {{ISBN|978-1-889-19544-5}} Track 16 Gallery (April 10 \u2013 June 5, 1999). Cervenka was co-editor, essay: \"Forming: the Early Days of L.A. Punk\"\n* Botey, Mariana, and Pilar Perez. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/46805033 Capitalart: On the Culture of Punishment.]'' Santa Monica, CA: Smart Art Press, 2001. {{ISBN|978-1-889-19546-9}} Track 16 Gallery (February 3 \u2013 March 31, 2001)\n* Cervenka, Exene. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/62379355 Exene Cervenka: America the Beautiful.]'' Santa Monica, CA: Smart Art Press, 2005.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of female rock singers]]\n* [[X (American band)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0148923}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140208032224/http://www.dcktcontemporary.com/artists/1734  Exene Cervenka] at [[DCKT Contemporary]]\n\n{{X (U.S. band)|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cervenka, Exene}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:American female singers]]\n[[Category:American folk singers]]\n[[Category:American punk rock singers]]\n[[Category:American spoken word poets]]\n[[Category:Bloodshot Records artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Female punk rock singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Florida]]\n[[Category:People with multiple sclerosis]]\n[[Category:Singers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:The Knitters members]]\n[[Category:X (American band) members]]\n[[Category:People from Mokena, Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer, artist, and poet|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name = Exene Cervenka\n| background = solo_singer\n| image = Exene.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Exene Cervenka at [[The Chestnut Cabaret]] in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] on July 30, 1986\n| birth_name = Christene Lee Cervenka\n| alias = Exene, Exene Cervenkov\u00e1<br>Christine Notmyrealname\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1956|02|01}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago]], Illinois, U.S.\n| origin = [[Los Angeles]], California\n| death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place = \n| genre = {{flatlist|\n*[[Punk rock|Punk]]\n*[[folk music|folk]]\n*[[Rock music|rock]]}}\n| occupation = Singer-songwriter, poet, musician, [[visual artist]]\n| instrument = {{flatlist|\n*Vocals\n*guitar}}\n| years_active = 1978\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n*[[Bloodshot Records|Bloodshot]]\n*[[Rhino Records|Rhino]]\n*[[Kill Rock Stars]]\n*[[Nitro Records|Nitro]]\n*[[2.13.61]]\n*[[Rykodisc]]\n*Freeway}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n*[[X (American band)|X]]\n*[[The Knitters]]\n*[[John Doe (musician)|John Doe]]\n*[[Auntie Christ]]\n*The Original Sinners}}\n| website = {{URL|exenecervenka.net}}\n}}\n'''Exene Cervenka''' (born '''Christene Lee Cervenka'''; February 1, 1956) is an American singer, artist, and poet.  She is best known for her work as a singer in the California [[punk rock]] band [[X (American band)|X]].<ref name=AllMusic-bio>{{cite web|last=Prato|first=Greg|title=Exene Cervenka: Biography |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/exene-cervenka-mn0000160993/biography|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=February 2, 2014}}</ref> Her surname is pronounced as \"''czer-vehn-kuh''\".\n\n== Music career ==\n \n[[File:Exene Cervenka 2010.jpg|thumb|Cervenka at SXSW 2010]]\n \t\nThe 21-year-old Cervenka met 23-year-old musician [[John Doe (musician)|John Doe]] at a poetry workshop at the [[Beyond Baroque Literary Arts Center|Beyond Baroque Foundation]] in [[Venice, California]].<ref name=VVoice-Interview-2008 /> Cervenka started working there.<ref name=Exene-BlogTalk-2013>{{cite web|title=Exene Cervenka \u2013 Singer, songwriter, poet, artist|url=http://www.blogtalkradio.com/storytellers/2013/07/03/exene-cervenka--singer-songwriter-poet-artist|work=Storytellers|publisher=Blog Talk Radio|accessdate=February 2, 2014|format=audio interview|date=July 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBilly Zoom and John Doe founded X in 1977.<ref name=\"rockerzine.com\">{{cite web|author=Keith Valcourt |url=http://www.rockerzine.com/index.php/2011/03/exene-cervenka-high-priestess-of-punk/ |title=Exene Cervenka: High Priestess Of Punk |website=Rockerzine.com |date=2011-03-30 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> Doe asked Cervenka to join soon after. They released their debut album, ''[[Los Angeles (X album)|Los Angeles]],'' in 1980 and, over the next six years, five more albums.\n \t\n[[Dave Alvin]] taught Cervenka how to play the guitar.<ref name=SunBreak-2010>{{cite web|last=Kay|first=Tony|title=More Fun in the New World: Exene Cervenka of X, Interviewed|url=http://www.thesunbreak.com/2010/04/20/more-fun-in-the-new-world-exene-cervenka-of-x-interviewed|work=[[The SunBreak]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100424201848/http://www.thesunbreak.com/2010/04/20/more-fun-in-the-new-world-exene-cervenka-of-x-interviewed|archivedate=April 24, 2010|date=April 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\t\n=== Collaborations ===\n\t\nIn 1982, Cervenka published ''Adulterers Anonymous'', her first in a series of four books in collaboration with artist [[Lydia Lunch]]. She and Lunch also released a spoken word album, ''Rude Hieroglyphics'', in 1996 and toured in support of the project.<ref name=NYT-2RockQueens-1982>{{cite news|last=Palmer|first=Robert|title=The Pop Life; 2 Rock Queens Turn to Literature|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/11/03/arts/the-pop-life-2-rock-queens-turn-to-literature.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=November 3, 1982}}</ref>\n \nFrom 1996 to 1999, [[John Roecker]] and Cervenka co-owned Los Angeles store \"You've Got Bad Taste.\" The store specialized in kitsch and various \"off-color\" novelties.<ref name=NYT-YGGT-closed-1999>{{cite news|title=Business: Diary; Who Says 'Nobody Ever Went Broke . . . '?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/21/business/business-diary-who-says-nobody-ever-went-broke.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=March 21, 1999}}</ref><ref name=LAWkly-Roek-2006>{{cite news|last=Lecaro|first=Lina|title=Punk Puppet Apocalypse|url=http://www.laweekly.com/2006-03-02/news/punk-puppet-apocalypse/|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[LA Weekly]]|date=February 28, 2006}}</ref>\n\t\nIn 1999, as '''Exene \u010cervenkov\u00e1,''' she appeared in the cult video ''Decoupage 2000: Return of the Goddess,'' along with guests [[Karen Black]] and the band [[L7 (band)|L7]]. She gave a reading of her poem \"They Must Be Angels,\" and appeared in an interview skit with ''Decoupage 2000'' hostess Summer Caprice.<ref name=decoupage2000 />\n\n== Art career ==\nIn 2005, Cervenka's journals and mixed media collages were exhibited in a one-person exhibition titled ''America the Beautiful'' at the [[Santa Monica Museum of Art]]. The exhibit was curated by [[Kristine McKenna]] and Michael Duncan. An expanded version of the exhibition traveled to [[DCKT Contemporary]] in New York in January 2006.\n\n== Personal life ==\nCervenka was married to [[John Doe (musician)|John Doe]] from 1980 to 1985. She met her second husband [[Viggo Mortensen]] in 1986 on the set of the comedy ''[[Salvation! (1987 film)|Salvation!]]'', a parody of [[televangelism]]. Mortensen played her husband Jerome. They married on July 8, 1987. On January 28, 1988, Cervenka gave birth to a son, Henry Blake Mortensen. Mortensen and Cervenka lived in Idaho for three years.<ref name=VVoice-Interview-2008>{{cite news|last=Trucks|first=Rob|title=Interview: Exene Cervenka of X|url=http://blogs.villagevoice.com/music/2008/05/interview_exene.php|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[Village Voice]]|date=May 20, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203113106/http://blogs.villagevoice.com/music/2008/05/interview_exene.php|archivedate=February 3, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> They separated in 1992, and were divorced in 1997.<ref name=NYT-Tmag-Viggo-2011>{{cite news|last=Heller|first=Zoe|title=Viggo Talks and Talks|url=http://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/12/02/viggo-talks-and-talks/|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nCervenka married musician Jason Edge, who went on to play in her band, Original Sinners.<ref name=Swindle-2008>{{cite web|last=Yokoland|title=Exene Cervenka |url=http://swindlemagazine.com/issueicons/exene-cervenka/ |work=Swindle Magazine|accessdate=February 2, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080228172558/http://swindlemagazine.com/issueicons/exene-cervenka/|archivedate=February 28, 2008}}</ref> Edge and Cervenka are now divorced.<ref name=NashScene-SGone-2010>{{cite news|last=McCall|first=Michael|title=Somewhere Gone from Exene Cervenka|url=http://www.nashvillescene.com/nashville/somewhere-gone-from-exene-cervenka/Content?oid=1227039|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[Nashville Scene]]|date=February 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nCervenka moved from Los Angeles to [[Jefferson City, Missouri]]<ref name=VVoice-Interview-2008 /> for four years, and then returned to Southern California.<ref name=LATimes-KeepingUp-2009>{{cite news|last=Lewis|first=Randy|title=Keeping up with Exene Cervenka|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/06/entertainment/et-exene-cervenka6|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[L.A. Times]]|date=October 6, 2009}}</ref> She now lives in Orange County.<ref name=OCReg-2011>{{cite news|last=Fadroski|first=Kelli Skye|title=Exene tells it straight on X, illness and O.C.|url=http://www.ocregister.com/soundcheck/http-481809-ocregister-people.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[Orange County Register]]|date=June 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=Riverfront-2009>{{cite news|last=Zaleski|first=Annie|title=Somewhere Out There: Exene Cervenka's new solo record, Somewhere Gone, has strong roots in Missouri|url=http://www.riverfronttimes.com/2009-10-21/music/somewhere-out-there-exene-cervenka-new-solo-record-somewhere-gone-strong-roots-missouri/|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[Riverfront Times]]|date=October 21, 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nOn June 2, 2009, Cervenka released a statement revealing that she had been diagnosed with [[multiple sclerosis]].<ref name=Exene-BS-Statement2009>{{cite web|title=A Statement from Exene Cervenka|url=https://www.bloodshotrecords.com/news/statement-exene-cervenka|work=Bloodshot Records|accessdate=February 2, 2014|date=June 2, 2009}}</ref><ref name=CLoaf-DespiteMS->{{cite web|last=Radford |first=Chad |title=Despite her MS diagnosis, Exene Cervenka lives for the moment |url=http://clatl.com/gyrobase/despite_her_ms_diagnosis_exene_cervenka_lives_for_the_moment/Content?oid=1341934 |work=[[Creative Loafing]] |publisher=Creative Loafing Atlanta |accessdate=February 2, 2014 |date=February 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140218231713/http://clatl.com/gyrobase/despite_her_ms_diagnosis_exene_cervenka_lives_for_the_moment/Content?oid=1341934 |archivedate=February 18, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref> Well before this diagnosis, she and X have actively supported [[Sweet Relief Fund|Sweet Relief]], a charity that aids uninsured artists. Sweet Relief was begun by musician [[Victoria Williams]] when she herself was diagnosed with MS.<ref name=ExeneStatement-2009>{{cite web|last=Cervenka|first=Exene|title=A Statement from Exene Cervenka |url=http://www.exenecervenka.com/exenemessage.html |work=ExeneCervenka.com |accessdate=February 2, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730043658/http://www.exenecervenka.com/exenemessage.html|archivedate=July 30, 2010|date=June 2, 2009}}</ref> In 2011, Cervenka said she may have been misdiagnosed.<ref name=OCReg-2011 /><ref name=LAWkly-Returns-2006>{{cite news|last=Ohanesian|first=Liz|title=Exene Cervenka Returns to Southern California|url=http://www.laweekly.com/westcoastsound/2009/10/06/exene-cervenka-returns-to-southern-california|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[LA Weekly]]|date=October 6, 2006}}</ref> However, Cervenka had to cancel a Spring 2011 tour due to problems associated with her MS.<ref name=Bloodshot-Tour-2011>{{cite web|title=Exene Cervenka Cancels Tour|url=https://www.bloodshotrecords.com/news/exene-cervenka-cancels-tour|work=Bloodshot Records|accessdate=February 2, 2014|date=April 4, 2011}}</ref> During a July 2015 interview, John Doe said that the multiple sclerosis diagnosis was a misdiagnosis, that Cervenka, after consulting with various doctors who were not able to diagnose her, is healthy.<ref name=Diffuser-Doe-2015>{{cite news|last1=Stafford|first1=James|title=In Conversation With X's John Doe|url=http://diffuser.fm/in-conversation-with-x-john-doe/|accessdate=30 July 2015|work=[[Diffuser.fm]]|date=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Conspiracy theories ===\nCervenka, as a self-styled \"conspiracy therapist,\" has provoked controversy on social media and on YouTube, under the name \"Christine Notmyrealname,\" by advancing conspiracy theories including the view that the [[2014 Isla Vista killings|Isla Vista shootings]] were a hoax designed to bring about stricter gun control laws. After the backlash, she has issued an apology on her Facebook and Twitter accounts and her conspiracy related YouTube videos are no longer available for viewing.<ref name=Radio-SBHoax-2014>{{cite web|title='80s Punk Star Exene Cervenka Claims Santa Barbara Shooting Was a Hoax|url=http://radio.com/2014/05/28/80s-punk-star-exene-cervenka-claims-santa-barbara-shooting-was-a-hoax/|website=Radio.com|accessdate=June 5, 2014|date=May 28, 2014}}</ref><ref name=IBT-SB-2014>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Eric|title=X Singer Exene Cervenka's Santa Barbara Shooting Conspiracy Theory Is One of Many|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/x-singer-exene-cervenkas-santa-barbara-shooting-conspiracy-theory-one-many-1592880|website=[[International Business Times]]|accessdate=June 5, 2014|date=June 1, 2014}}</ref><ref name=MercNews-SBHoax-2014>{{cite news|last1=Hicks|first1=Tony|title=Punk legend Exene Cervenka calls Santa Barbara shooting 'hoax'|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/entertainment/ci_25859992/punk-legend-exene-cervenka-calls-santa-barbara-shooting|accessdate=June 5, 2014|work=[[Contra Costa Times]]|date=May 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== X ===\n\n==== Singles, soundtracks, compilations, etc. ====\n* 1978: ''Adult Books/We're Desperate'' 7\" ([[Dangerhouse Records]])\n* 1979: ''Yes L.A.'' compilation (Dangerhouse Records)\n* 1980: ''[[The Decline of Western Civilization]]'' soundtrack (Spheeris Films/[[Slash Records]]): \"Beyond and Back,\" \"Johnny Hit and Run Paulene,\" \"Nausea,\" \"Unheard Music,\" \"We're Desperate\"\n* 1980: ''No Questions Asked'' by Flesh Eaters (Slash Records)\n* 1982: ''[[Urgh! A Music War]]'' soundtrack ([[A&M Records]])\n\n==== Albums ====\n* 1980: ''[[Los Angeles (X album)|Los Angeles]]'' (Slash Records)\n* 1981: ''[[Wild Gift]]'' (Slash Records)<ref name=NYTimes-XGrow-1982>{{cite news|last=Palmer|first=Robert|title=Pop Life; New Album Shows X Has Grown|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/23/arts/pop-life-new-album-shows-x-has-grown.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 23, 1982}}</ref>\n* 1982: ''[[Under the Big Black Sun]]'' ([[Elektra Records]])\n* 1983: ''[[More Fun in the New World]]'' (Elektra Records)\n* 1985: ''[[Ain't Love Grand!]]'' (Elektra Records)\n* 1987: ''[[See How We Are]]'' (Elektra Records/[[Asylum Records]])\n* 1988: ''[[Live at the Whisky a Go-Go (X album)|Live at the Whisky a Go-Go]]'' (Elektra/Asylum Records)\n* 1993: ''[[Hey Zeus!]]'' ([[Big Life Records]])\n* 1995: ''[[Unclogged]]'' (Infidelity Recordings/Sunset Boulevard)<ref name=NYT-DoeExeneCountry-1995>{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|title=Pop Review; John Doe and Exene Go a Little Bit Country|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/20/arts/pop-review-john-doe-and-exene-go-a-little-bit-country.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 20, 1995}}</ref>\n* 1997: ''[[Beyond and Back: The X Anthology]]'' (Elektra Records)\n* 2004: ''[[The Best: Make the Music Go Bang!]]'' (Elektra Records/[[Rhino Records]])\n* 2005: ''X \u2013 Live in Los Angeles'' ([[Shout! Factory]])\n\n=== The Knitters ===\n* 1985: ''[[Poor Little Critter on the Road]]'' (Slash Records/Rhino Records)\n* 2005: ''[[The Modern Sounds of the Knitters]]'' (Zo\u00eb Records)\n\n=== Solo ===\n* 1989: ''Old Wives' Tales'' (Rhino Records)<ref name=NYTimes-HalfX-1989>{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|title=Reviews/Music; Half of X Equals Cervenka|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/10/29/arts/reviews-music-half-of-x-equals-cervenka.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 29, 1989}}</ref>\n* 1990: ''Running Sacred'' (RNA (Rhino New Artists))\n* 1994: ''Exene Cervenka'' (Wordcore Volume 7) 7\" ([[Kill Rock Stars]])\n* 1995: ''Surface To Air Serpents'' (213CD/[[Thirsty Ear Recordings]])\n* 2009: ''Somewhere Gone'' ([[Bloodshot Records]])<ref name=HoustonPress-2010>{{cite news|last=Gray|first=Chris|title=Inquiring Minds: Exene Cervenka on Losing a Friend, Weeping Willows, Albums as Collage and Her Good Buddy Biscuit|url=http://blogs.houstonpress.com/rocks/2010/01/rocks_off_where_did_this.php|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=Houston Press|date=January 27, 2010}}</ref>\n* 2011: ''The Excitement of Maybe'' (Bloodshot Records)<ref name=AMP-2011>{{cite web|last=Steffens|first=Charlie|title=An Interview with Exene Cervenka|url=http://charliesteffens.com/an-interview-with-exene-cervenka/|work=[[AMP (magazine)|AMP]]|accessdate=February 2, 2014|date=March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203181246/http://charliesteffens.com/an-interview-with-exene-cervenka/|archivedate=February 3, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==== Bands ====\n* 1997: ''Life Could Be A Dream'' as [[Auntie Christ]] ([[Lookout Records]])\n* 2002: ''Original Sinners'' as Original Sinners ([[Nitro Records]])\n* 2006: ''Sev7en'' as Exene Cervenka and the Original Sinners (Nitro Records)\n\n==== Other ====\n* 1985: Wanda Coleman, Exene Cervenka: ''Twin Sisters'' LP (Freeway). Poetry performance recorded at [[McCabe's Guitar Shop]], Santa Monica, CA on February 1, 1985.\n* 1995: Lydia Lunch & Exene Cervenka: ''Rude Hieroglyphics'' ([[Rykodisc]]). Recorded live at the Sapphire Supper Club, Orlando, FL on March 20, 1995.\n* 1999: ''Decoupage 2000: Return of the Goddess.'' Read poem \"They Must Be Angels\" and appeared in an interview skit.<ref name=decoupage2000>{{cite web |url=http://www.decoupagetv.com/tomorrow.html |title=Decoupage 2000 |publisher=Decoupagetv.com |accessdate=January 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709005346/http://www.decoupagetv.com/tomorrow.html |archivedate=July 9, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* 2012: John Doe & Exene Cervenka: ''Singing and Playing'' (Moonlight Graham Records). Recorded at Way Station April 2\u20133, 2010.<ref name=KCET-ExeneRulesGraham-2012>{{cite web|last=Bose|first=Lilledeshan|title=How Exene Cervenka Came to Rule Over the Boy's Club|url=http://www.kcet.org/arts/artbound/counties/orange/moonlight-graham.html|work=[[KCET]]|publisher=KCETLink|accessdate=February 2, 2014|date=May 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Additional musical contributions ===\n* 1994: Applegate, Christina, and Elizabeth Pena. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/32411773 Across the Moon.]'' Los Angeles, CA: Hemdale Home Video, 1994. {{ISBN|978-1-569-20068-1}} Music composed by Christopher Tyng & Exene Cervenka\n* 1996: ''Honor: A Benefit for the Honor the Earth Campaign'' ([[Daemon Records]]). \"The Future is a War\" by Exene Cervenka\n* 1997: ''[[G.I. Jane]]'' original soundtrack ([[Hollywood Records]]). \"The Future is a War\" by Auntie Christ\n* 1999: ''One Man's Meat'' by [[Viggo Mortensen]] (Lightning Creek). Features Exene Cervenka on vocals, guitar\n* 2000: ''[[Stoned Immaculate: The Music of The Doors]]'' (Elektra Records). \"Children of Night\" by [[Perry Farrell]] and Exene\n* 2001: ''Punk-o-rama 2001, Vol. 6'' ([[Epitaph Records]]). \"We're Desperate\" by Pennywise with Exene\n* 2002: ''Rise Above: 24 Black Flag Songs to Benefit the West Memphis Three'' ([[Sanctuary Records Group|Sanctuary]]). \"Wasted\" by Exene Cervenka\n* 2009: ''[[The People Speak (film)|The People Speak]]'' original soundtrack ([[Verve Records]]). \"See How We Are\" by Exene Cervenka & John Doe\n* 2011: ''Kings and Queens'' by [[Blackie and the Rodeo Kings]] ([[Dramatico]]). \"Made of Love\" featuring Exene Cervenka\n*2018 \"Queen For A Day\" by [[Skating Polly]] featuring and also written by Exene Cervenka\n\n=== Video ===\n* ''[[The Decline of Western Civilization]]'' (1981)\n* ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/466135850 Urgh! A Music War]'' (1982)\n* ''[[X: The Unheard Music]]'' (1985/1987, video; 1986/1987/2004, DVD; re-released 2011 Silver Anniversary Edition)<ref name=NYT-UnheardMusic-1986>{{cite news|last=Maslin|first=Janet|title=Film: 'Unheard Music'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/21/movies/film-unheard-music.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 21, 1986}}</ref>\n* ''[[X - Live in Los Angeles]]'' (2005) \u2013 [[Shout! Factory]]: Concert by X in Los Angeles recorded live on November 26 and 27, 2004 {{ISBN|978-0-738-93185-2}}\n\n== Works or publications ==\n* Lunch, Lydia, and Exene Cervenka. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/8669443 Adulterers Anonymous.]'' New York: Grove Press, 1982. {{ISBN|978-0-394-62412-9}}\n* ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/849679557 The 1984 Calendar of Olympic Games, Music & Orwellian Dates.]'' 1984, n.d.. Produced by M. Hyatt, Exene Cervenka and 53 mail artists from around the world.\n* ''[http://www.baddaymovie.com/ Bad Day: A Short Film by Modi Frank and Exene Cervenka.]'' (1986)<ref name=BadDay-PDF>{{cite web|title=Kevin Costner in a \"Lost\" Western Movie Found and Released Exclusively Online|url=http://www.baddaymovie.com/BadDayMediaRelease08-01-10.pdf|work=Bad Day Movie|accessdate=February 2, 2014}}</ref><ref name=HuffPo-BadDay-Costner-2010>{{cite news|last=Derrick|first=Lisa|title=Bad Day: Kevin Costner's Secret Movie Released Online|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/lisa-derrick/bad-day-kevin-costers-sec_b_652740.html|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=[[Huffington Post]]|date=July 20, 2010}}</ref>\n* Mohr, Bill, and Sheree Levin. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/12924592 Poetry Loves Poetry: An Anthology of Los Angeles Poets.]'' Santa Monica, CA: Momentum Press, 1985. {{ISBN|978-0-936-05450-6}}<ref name=LAT-PoetryLovesPoetry-1986>{{cite news|last=Bartruff|first=James|title=Fiction : Poetry Loves Poetry, edited by Bill Mohr; photographs by Sheree Levin.|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-08-17/books/bk-16474_1_bill-mohr|accessdate=February 1, 2014|newspaper=[[L.A. Times]]|date=August 17, 1986}}</ref>\n* Jarecke, Kenneth, and Exene Cervenka. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/28606930 Just Another War.]'' Joliet, Mont: Bedrock Press, 1992. {{ISBN|978-0-963-47840-5}}<ref name=ShavedNeck2002>{{cite web|title=Exene Cervenka Interview|url=http://www.shavedneck.com/ExeneCervenkaInterviewKZSU.htm|work=Shaved Neck|accessdate=February 2, 2014|date=June 26, 2002}}</ref>\n* Cervenka, Exene. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/30623984 Virtual Unreality.]'' Los Angeles: 2.13.61 Publications, 1993. {{ISBN|978-1-880-98515-1}}\n* Cervenka, Exene. \"Consumption.\" ''[[Details Magazine]],'' July 1993. (poem)\n* Cervenka, Exene. \"Acres of Defeat.\" ''[[Raygun Magazine]],'' Dec./Jan 1993. (article)\n* Cervenka, Exene. \"Midnight Black.\" ''[[L.A. Weekly]]'' Magazine, Best of L.A. Issue, 1993. (poem)\n* Lake, Bambi, and Alvin Orloff. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/34618232 The Unsinkable Bambi Lake: A Fairy Tale Containing the Dish on Cockettes, Punks, and Angels.]'' San Francisco: Manic D Press, 1996. {{ISBN|978-0-916-39742-5}} Introduction by Exene Cervenka\n* Snowden, Don, and Gary Leonard. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/36916508 Make the Music Go Bang!: The Early L.A. Punk Scene.]'' New York: St. Martin's Griffin, 1997. {{ISBN|978-0-312-16912-1}} \"Halos Above Our Horns\" by Exene Cervenkova. (essay)\n* Rollins, Henry. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/41257257 The Best of 2.13.61 Publications.]'' Los Angeles: 2.13.61 Publications, 1998. {{ISBN|978-1-880-98562-5}} (excerpts from \"Virtual Unreality\")\n* Maybe, Ellyn, and Exene Cervenka. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/39609378 The Cowardice of Amnesia.]'' Los Angeles: 2.13.61 Publications, 1998. {{ISBN|978-1-880-98558-8}}\n* Hyatt, Michael, and Exene Cervenka. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/781450801 Lucky 13 Postcards.]'' Los Angeles, Calif: s.n., 2000.\n* Cervenka, Exene. ''A Beer on Every Page.'' 2002.\n* Jocoy, Jim, Thurston Moore, and Exene Cervenka. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/49648198 We're Desperate: The Punk Photography of Jim Jocoy : SF/LA 78\u201380.]'' New York, NY: PowerHouse Books, 2002. {{ISBN|978-1-576-87156-0}} \"Slivery Moon\" (essay)\n* Kihn, Greg. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/52155535 Carved in Rock: Short Stories by Musicians.]'' New York: Thunder's Mouth Press, 2003. {{ISBN|978-1-560-25453-9}} features short story \"Perfect World from Virtual Unreality\" by Exene Cervenka\n* Cervenka, Exene, and Viggo Mortensen. ''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/123481820 Magical Meteorite Songwriting Device: Collages.]'' Santa Monica, CA: Perceval Press, 2006. {{ISBN|978-0-976-30092-2}}<ref name=NYT-Viggo-Pub-2006>{{cite news|last=Maslin|first=Janet|title=Viggo Mortensen's Unusual Role: Indie Publishing Mogul|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/01/movies/01viggo.html?fta=y|accessdate=February 2, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 1, 2006}}</ref>\n\n=== Exhibitions ===\n\n==== One-person exhibitions ====\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20140204014022/https://smmoa.org/programs-and-exhibitions/exene-cervenka-america-the-beautiful/ America the Beautiful.]'' [[Santa Monica Museum of Art]] (September 17 \u2013 November 26, 2005)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20140226164700/http://www.dcktcontemporary.com/artists/1734/collections/134 America the Beautiful.]'' [[DCKT Contemporary]] (January 7 \u2013 February 11, 2006)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20140203114431/http://www.western-project.com/2007/12/09/exene-cervenka-a-fifth-of-tomorrow-collages-and-journals/ A Fifth of Tomorrow.]'' Collages and journals. Western Project (June 9 \u2013 July 14, 2007)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20140226170950/http://www.dcktcontemporary.com/artists/1734/collections/112 Sleep in Spite of Thunder.]'' DCKT Contemporary (May 23 \u2013 July 18, 2008)\n\n==== Two-person exhibitions ====\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20140203140038/http://www.western-project.com/2009/12/09/exene-cervenka-and-wayne-white-were-not-the-jet-set-2009/ Exene Cervenka and Wayne White: We're Not The Jet Set.]'' Paintings, collages and sculptures. Western Project (July 25 \u2013 September 5, 2009)\n\n==== Group exhibitions ====\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20100428023030/http://www.markmooregallery.com/exhibitions/1998-12-05_hollywood-satan/ Hollywood Satan.]'' Mark Moore Gallery, Santa Monica, CA (December 5\u201325, 1998)\n* ''[http://www.track16.com/exhibitions/punk/punk.html Forming: The Early Days of L.A. Punk.]'' Track 16 Gallery, Santa Monica, CA (April 10 \u2013 June 15, 1999)\n* ''[http://www.track16.com/exhibitions/capital/capital.html Capital Art: On the Culture of Punishment.]'' Track 16 Gallery, Santa Monica, CA (February 3 \u2013 March 31, 2001)\n* ''Cruel And Unusual: A Benefit For The West Memphis Three.'' sixspace, Los Angeles, CA (2003)\n* ''[http://claremontmuseum.org/vexing-female-voices-from-east-la-punk/ Vexing: Female Voices from East L.A. Punk.]'' Claremont Museum of Art, Claremont, CA (May 18 \u2013 August 31, 2008); Museo de las Artes, Universidad de Guadalajara, Guadalajara, Mexico (2008\u20132009)\n* Yard Dog, Austin, TX (2009)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20111020135033/http://www.cafam.org/CelestialAsh.html Celestial Ash: Assemblages from Los Angeles.]'' Craft and Folk Art Museum, Los Angeles, CA (April 11 \