{"title_page": "Altman Lighting Co.", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| logo                = \n| name                = Altman Lighting\n| type                = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| foundation          = 1953\n| location            = [[Yonkers|Yonkers, New York]], United States\n| industry            = Stage, Event, and Architectural Lighting\n| products            = \n| homepage            = http://www.altmanltg.com/\n}}\n\n'''Altman Lighting''', established in 1953, is one of the leading manufacturers of [[theatrical lighting]] instruments. They are located in Yonkers, New York and have been a family run business since the 1950s. Altman specializes in theatrical lighting and follow spots as well as a series of architectural fixtures.\n\n==History==\nThe Altman Lighting Company was established in 1953 by Charles and Alice Altman. Charles became well known for providing equipment to schools and small theatres that could not afford it. In 1963, Altman lighting founded Altman rentals under the leadership of Ronald; Charles and Alice's son. One of Altman's first and most notable inventions was the [[Parabolic aluminized reflector light|PAR]] 64 which they introduced in 1966 for a [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] concert tour.<ref name= \"ref2\"/><ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite news \n  | last = Archer\n  | first = Rick\n  | title = PROFILE: Altman Lighting Inc.\n  | date = April 26, 2004\n  | url = http://www.allbusiness.com/company-activities-management/company-structures-ownership/10629301-1.html\n  | accessdate = April 15, 2009 }}</ref> \nBy the 1980s, Altman had become the dominant [[stage lighting]] company in America and in 1988 Charlie and Alice were awarded the Lifetime Achievement Foot Candle Award for their extraordinary achievement in stage lighting.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Altman Theatrical Lighting Catalog\n |url          = http://www.altmanltg.com/altman_theatrical_catalog.pdf\n |format       = PDF\n |accessdate   = April 16, 2009\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110707120725/http://www.altmanltg.com/altman_theatrical_catalog.pdf\n |archive-date = 2011-07-07\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> \nIn 1990 Alice Altman died, and the company was handed over to Robert Altman in 1992. That same year, Altman released a full line of TV and Film products. Charles Altman died in 1995 and His son Robert, now oversees daily operations.<ref name=\"ref1\"/>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1988, Charles and Alice Altman won the Lifetime Achievement Foot Candle Award for their achievement in stage lighting and in 1993<ref name= \"ref2\"/> Charles Altman won the Wally Russell award for \"outstanding contribution to the entertainment industry\".<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = The WALLY Awards\n |publisher    = The Wally Russell Foundation\n |url          = http://www.wallyfund.org/activities.html\n |accessdate   = April 15, 2009\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090720135517/http://www.wallyfund.org/activities.html\n |archive-date = 2009-07-20\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\nIn 1997 Altman received the Theatre Crafts International Award, which honors new and innovative technical achievement for their focusing [[Striplight|cyc light]]. The next year, Altman won the EDDY award, which recognizes \"outstanding contribution to the field of entertainment technology\", for the Star [[Parabolic aluminized reflector light|PAR]] luminaire.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | title = The EDDY Awards\n  | publisher = Penton Media, Inc.\n  | date = December 7, 2006\n  | url = http://livedesignonline.com/eddys/eddy_awards/index2.html\n  | accessdate = April 16, 2009\n  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090425160037/http://livedesignonline.com/eddys/eddy_awards/index2.html\n  | archivedate = 25 April 2009\n  | url-status = dead\n  | df = dmy-all\n  }}\n</ref>\nIn 2004, Altman received the Star Magazine Technology and Business award for their ability to implement technology to solve critical business challenges. Then in 2005, Altman won the Lightfair international Award for Smart Track, a system they had introduced the year before.<ref name= \"ref2\"/>  In 2013 the Phoenix LED was awarded the PLASA Members Choice Award in the equipment category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lightingandsoundamerica.com/news/story.asp?ID=MX6W0P|title=PLASA Announces Winners of 2013 Members' Choice Product Awards - Lighting&Sound America Online News|last=America|first=PLASA Media Inc-Lighting & Sound|website=Lighting&Sound America Online  News|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> In 2015 the Pegasus LED fresnel line also earned the PLASA Members Choice Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eventtechnology.org/altman-lighting/|title=Altman Lighting|website=Event Technology Portal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Electronics companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Stage lighting]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies established in 1953]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1953]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| logo                = \n| name                = Altman Lighting\n| type                = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| foundation          = 1953\n| location            = [[Yonkers|Yonkers, New York]], United States\n| industry            = Stage, Event, and Architectural Lighting\n| products            = \n| homepage            = http://www.altmanltg.com/\n}}\n\n'''Altman''' '''Lighting''', established in 1953, is one of the leading manufacturers of [[theatrical lighting]] instruments. They are located in Yonkers, New York and have been a family run business since the 1950s. Altman specializes in theatrical lighting and follow spots as well as a series of architectural fixtures.\n\n==History==\nThe Altman Lighting Company was established in 1953 by Charles and Alice Altman. Charles became well known for providing equipment to schools and small theatres that could not afford it. In 1963, Altman lighting founded Altman rentals under the leadership of Ronald; Charles and Alice's son. One of Altman's first and most notable inventions was the [[Parabolic aluminized reflector light|PAR]] 64 which they introduced in 1966 for a [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] concert tour.<ref name= \"ref2\"/><ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite news \n  | last = Archer\n  | first = Rick\n  | title = PROFILE: Altman Lighting Inc.\n  | date = April 26, 2004\n  | url = http://www.allbusiness.com/company-activities-management/company-structures-ownership/10629301-1.html\n  | accessdate = April 15, 2009 }}</ref> \nBy the 1980s, Altman had become the dominant [[stage lighting]] company in America and in 1988 Charlie and Alice were awarded the Lifetime Achievement Foot Candle Award for their extraordinary achievement in stage lighting.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Altman Theatrical Lighting Catalog\n |url          = http://www.altmanltg.com/altman_theatrical_catalog.pdf\n |format       = PDF\n |accessdate   = April 16, 2009\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110707120725/http://www.altmanltg.com/altman_theatrical_catalog.pdf\n |archive-date = 2011-07-07\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> \nIn 1990 Alice Altman died, and the company was handed over to Robert Altman in 1992. That same year, Altman released a full line of TV and Film products. Charles Altman died in 1995 and His son Robert, now oversees daily operations.<ref name=\"ref1\"/>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1988, Charles and Alice Altman won the Lifetime Achievement Foot Candle Award for their achievement in stage lighting and in 1993<ref name= \"ref2\"/> Charles Altman won the Wally Russell award for \"outstanding contribution to the entertainment industry\".<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = The WALLY Awards\n |publisher    = The Wally Russell Foundation\n |url          = http://www.wallyfund.org/activities.html\n |accessdate   = April 15, 2009\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090720135517/http://www.wallyfund.org/activities.html\n |archive-date = 2009-07-20\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\nIn 1997 Altman received the Theatre Crafts International Award, which honors new and innovative technical achievement for their focusing [[Striplight|cyc light]]. The next year, Altman won the EDDY award, which recognizes \"outstanding contribution to the field of entertainment technology\", for the Star [[Parabolic aluminized reflector light|PAR]] luminaire.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | title = The EDDY Awards\n  | publisher = Penton Media, Inc.\n  | date = December 7, 2006\n  | url = http://livedesignonline.com/eddys/eddy_awards/index2.html\n  | accessdate = April 16, 2009\n  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090425160037/http://livedesignonline.com/eddys/eddy_awards/index2.html\n  | archivedate = 25 April 2009\n  | url-status = dead\n  | df = dmy-all\n  }}\n</ref>\nIn 2004, Altman received the Star Magazine Technology and Business award for their ability to implement technology to solve critical business challenges. Then in 2005, Altman won the Lightfair international Award for Smart Track, a system they had introduced the year before.<ref name= \"ref2\"/>  In 2013 the Phoenix LED was awarded the PLASA Members Choice Award in the equipment category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lightingandsoundamerica.com/news/story.asp?ID=MX6W0P|title=PLASA Announces Winners of 2013 Members' Choice Product Awards - Lighting&Sound America Online News|last=America|first=PLASA Media Inc-Lighting & Sound|website=Lighting&Sound America Online  News|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> In 2015 the Pegasus LED fresnel line also earned the PLASA Members Choice Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eventtechnology.org/altman-lighting/|title=Altman Lighting|website=Event Technology Portal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n[[