& Charles|year=1965}}\n* {{cite book |last=Thomas |first=Cliff |author-link=Cliff Thomas |title=The Narrow Gauge in Britain and Ireland |year=2002 |publisher=Atlantic Publishing |isbn=1-902827-05-8 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/narrowgaugeinbri0000thom }}\n* {{cite magazine |author=Woodcock, G. George |date=September 1938 |title=The Tal-y-llyn Railway |magazine=Railway Magazine |volume=83 |issue=495 |pages=197\u2013200}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Talyllyn Railway}}\n* [http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/ Talyllyn Railway website]\n* [http://www.ngrm.org.uk/ Narrow Gauge Railway Museum]\n* [https://archive.org/details/railway_with_a_heart_of_gold_1965 Railway with a Heart of Gold], a slightly tongue-in-cheek documentary about the railway, filmed in the early 1950s by American filmmaker Carson Davidson.\n\n{{Talyllyn Railway}}\n{{Heritage railways in Wales}}\n{{Historical Welsh railway companies}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n[[Category:Talyllyn Railway| Talyllyn Railway]]\n[[Category:2 ft 3 in gauge railways in Wales]]\n[[Category:Narrow gauge railways in Snowdonia]]\n[[Category:Heritage railways in Snowdonia]]\n[[Category:Winners of the Queen's Award for Voluntary Service]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:1866 establishments in Wales]]\n[[Category:Railway inclines in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Voice of Clam", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIn popular culture:c/e", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talyllyn_Railway"}
{"title_page": "Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez", "text_new": "{{short description|Interim President of Bolivia since 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{spanish name|[[\u00c1\u00f1ez]]|[[Ch\u00e1vez (surname)|Ch\u00e1vez]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez\n| image               = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez.jpg\n| caption             = \u00c1\u00f1ez in 2016\n| order = 66th \n| office              = President of Bolivia\n| term_start          = 12 November 2019\n| term_end            = \n| vicepresident       = <!-- ''None'' -->\n| predecessor         = [[Evo Morales]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[President pro tempore of the Community of Latin American and Caribbean States|President pro tempore of CELAC]]\n| term_start1         = 12 November 2019\n| term_end1           = 8 January 2020{{Efn|CELAC ''pro tempore'' presidency is assigned to countries and it automatically passes to the next president after elections. After the [[2019 Bolivian political crisis]], Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez would become ''pro tempore'' president of CELAC. However, Mexico called for a new CELAC summit on its own. Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez denounced that the summit should be called for by Bolivia. As the result of this dispute, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez did not attend to the CELAC summit and did not formally pass the ''pro tempore'' presidency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elimparcial.com/mundo/Bolivia-no-asistira-al-cambio-de-presidencia-de-la-Celac-por-roces-con-Mexico-20191223-0073.html|title=Bolivia no asistir\u00e1 al cambio de presidencia de la Celac por roces con M\u00e9xico|work=El Imparcial|date=23 December 2019|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/es/mundo/bolivia-rechaza-que-m%C3%A9xico-convocara-a-reuni%C3%B3n-de-la-celac-sin-consultarle-previamente/1682226|title=Bolivia rechaza que M\u00e9xico convocara a reuni\u00f3n de la Celac sin consultarle previamente|work=Anadolu Agency|first=Sant\u0131ago|last=Serna Duque|date=24 December 2020|access-date=11 April 2020|language=es}}</ref>}}\n| predecessor1        = [[Evo Morales]]\n| successor1          = [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]]\n| office2             = [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly|Senator]] for [[Beni Department|Beni]]\n| term_start2         = 22 January 2010\n| term_end2           = 12 November 2019\n| office3             = [[Bolivian Constituent Assembly of 2006\u201307|Member of the Constituent Assembly]]\n| term_start3         = 6 August 2006\n| term_end3           = 6 August 2007\n| birth_name          = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1967|8|13}}\n| birth_place         = [[San Joaqu\u00edn, Bolivia|San Joaqu\u00edn]], [[Beni Department|Beni]], Bolivia\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| spouse              = Tadeo Ribera Bruckner (1990-?), H\u00e9ctor Hernando Hincapi\u00e9 Carvajal (?-present)\n| party               = [[Democrat Social Movement]] [[Juntos (Bolivian political party)|Juntos]]\n| signature           = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez signature.svg\n}}\n\n'''Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez'''<ref>{{citation |title=Entrevista Jeanine A\u00f1ez Chavez |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v185AWdeDE0 |language=en |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> ({{IPA-es|\u025f\u029da\u02c8nine \u02c8a\u0272es}}; born 13 August 1967)<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://web.senado.gob.bo/senadoras-es/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-ch%C3%A1vez |title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |date=16 October 2015 |website=C\u00e1mara de Senadores |language=es |accessdate=11 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111145518/https://web.senado.gob.bo/senadoras-es/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-ch%C3%A1vez |archivedate=11 November 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> is a Bolivian politician and lawyer currently serving as the Interim [[President of Bolivia]] since November 2019, after the [[Evo Morales government resignation|resignation of the government of Evo Morales]]. Her interim term will end when [[2020 Bolivian general election|new elections]] take place on an as yet undetermined date in 2020.\n\nShe was previously an opposition [[Senate of Bolivia|senator]] from the northeastern [[Departments of Bolivia|department]] of [[Beni, Bolivia|Beni]], belonging to the center-right [[Democrat Social Movement]]. Her political position has been described by journalists as [[right-wing]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization |first=Dan |last=Collyns |date=14 November 2019 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/jeanine-anez-declares-bolivia-interim-president-191112233635201.html |title=Jeanine Anez declares herself Bolivia interim president |date=12 November 2019 |website=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> and anti-[[Evo Morales|Morales]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cronista.com/internacionales/Bolivia-quien-es-Jeanine-Anez-Chavez-la-mujer-que-puede-quedar-al-mando-de-la-transicion-20191110-0019.html |title=Bolivia: qui\u00e9n es Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, la mujer que puede quedar al mando de la transici\u00f3n |date=11 November 2019 |website=El Cronista |trans-title=Bolivia: who is Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, the woman who can be in charge of the transition |access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/after-morales-resignation-a-question-for-bolivia-was-this-the-democratic-will-or-a-coup/2019/11/11/ff36ce9a-040c-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html |title=After Morales' resignation, a question for Bolivia: Was this the democratic will, or a coup? |last=Faiola |first=Anthony |date= |website=[[The Washington Post]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111194058/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/after-morales-resignation-a-question-for-bolivia-was-this-the-democratic-will-or-a-coup/2019/11/11/ff36ce9a-040c-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html|archive-date=2019-11-11|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50399640 |title=Bolivian senator assumes interim presidency |last= |first= |date=13 November 2019 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |access-date=13 November 2019 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nJeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez was born in the small Amazonian town of [[San Joaqu\u00edn, Bolivia|San Joaqu\u00edn]] in the [[Department of Beni]], Bolivia, on 13 August 1967. She was the youngest of seven children born to two teachers.<ref name=biografias>{{cite web|url=http://library.fes.de/pdf-files/bueros/bolivien/10697.pdf|language=es|title=BIOGRAF\u00cdAS Historias de Vida en la Asamblea Legislativa Plurinacional|year=2013|page=416\u2013418}}</ref> Her background has been described as poor [[mestiza]] and lower-middle-class.<ref name=\"\u201ceconomist\u201d\">{{cite news|author=|title= Bolivia after the ouster of Evo Morales, a leftist strongman|url= https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/03/07/bolivia-after-the-ouster-of-evo-morales-a-leftist-strongman|work=[[The Economist]]|date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=CIDOB>{{cite web|url=https://www.cidob.org/biografias_lideres_politicos/america_del_sur/bolivia/jeanine_anez_chavez|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |website=www.cidob.org|language=es|date=13 December 2019}}</ref> During this time, San Joaqu\u00edn lacked proper roads, was dependent on diesel generators for power and had a water supply that was rationed. Recalling her childhood, she says \"We grew up with many limitations, with many needs but nevertheless I had a beautiful childhood, very free.\" <ref name=biografias></ref>\n\nShe attended the local school, a girls school that her mother would later become director of. At age seventeen, she achieved her baccalaureate and left San Joaqu\u00edn to pursue an education in La Paz, first at the Bolivian Institute and then at the Abraham Lincoln Institute. At this time, she studied to become a secretary.<ref name=biografias></ref> She continued to [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]] where she took further studies as a secretary, including computing and some English. <ref name=biografias></ref> After getting married at aged 23, she moved to [[Trinidad, Bolivia]], where she enrolled at the Autonomous University of the Beni Jos\u00e9 Ballivi\u00e1n and obtained a graduate degree in law and legal sciences.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=biografias></ref>\n\n==Career==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez passed the bar in 1991.<ref name=\":2\" /> She was formerly a media presenter<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/mundo/perfil-de-jeanine-anez-nueva-presidenta-interina-de-bolivia-432904 |title=\u00bfQui\u00e9n es Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez, la nueva presidenta interina de Bolivia? |first=Casa Editorial El |last=Tiempo |date=13 November 2019 |location=Colombia |language=es |website=[[ElTiempo.com]]}}</ref> and director at Totalvisi\u00f3n.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Constituent Assembly (2006\u20132008)===\nBetween 2006 and 2008, she served as a constituent assemblywoman for the drafting of the new constitutional charter, also working as part of the Judiciary.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Senate (2010\u20132019)===\nIn 2010, she was elected to the [[Bolivian Senate|Senate]] as a member of the party [[Plan Progress for Bolivia \u2013 National Convergence|Plan Progress for Bolivia-National Convergence]] (P.P.B - C.N), representing the Department of Beni in the National Assembly.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/spip.php?page=parlamentario&id_parlamentario=159 |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |date= |access-date=21 April 2014 |publisher=vicepresidencia.gob.bo |language=es |format= |quote= }}</ref> She ran for governor of Beni in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Jeanine-Anez-precandidata-gobernacion-Beni_0_1697830274.html |title=La senadora Jeanine A\u00f1ez surge como primera precandidata opositora a la gobernaci\u00f3n de Beni; el MSM apunta a una tercera opci\u00f3n |last=Corz |first=Carlos |date=1 October 2012 |website=La Raz\u00f3n |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she spoke out against the approval of a finance bill by the Morales' government for the construction of the Villa Tunari-San Ignacio de Moxos highway. She claimed that it was not approved with due consideration for the native peoples and institutions of the region saying that \"indigenous people's right was violated\", a sentiment echoed by leader of the natives of the Isiboro S\u00e9cure National Park Indigenous Territory (TIPNIS), Adolfo Moye who said it was enacted \"without considering the serious impact on the ecosystem and natural reserves of the region.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20110511/senadora-cuestiona-financiamiento-carretera-cochabamba-beni|title=Senator questions financing of Cochabamba-Beni highway|language=es|date=11 May 2011|website=www.losttiempos.com|}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, A\u00f1ez and fellow party legislator Adri\u00e1n Oliva presented a report to the Human Rights Commission of the Chamber of Deputies of Uruguay in an effort to publicise human rights violations in Bolivia. According to the UN refugee office, UNHCR, there were around 600 Bolivian exiles or refugees, a hundred political prisoners and at least 15 cases of torture at this time. The UN High Commissioner for Human Rights stated that there was a \"crisis in the administration of justice\" in Bolivia. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20120523/presentan-informe-uruguay|website=www.lostiempos.com|date=23 May 2012|language=es|title=Report presented in Uruguay}}</ref> Also in 2012, A\u00f1ez was selected as a Bolivian representative to the Amazonian Parliament. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20120316/senado-designo-representantes-parlamentos-internacionales|website=www.lostiempos.com|date=16 March 2012|language=es|title=Senate designates representatives to international parliaments.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, there were a series of nationwide strikes and protests against the MAS government concerning the reduction of seats in the Chamber of Deputies for the areas of [[Department of Beni|Beni]], [[Potos\u00ed department|Potos\u00ed]] and [[Department of Chuquisaca|Chuquisaca]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2013/10/2/beni-potosi-inician-paro-contra-escanos-2058.html|date=2 October 2013|title=Beni and Potosi begin strike against seats}}</ref>As Senator of Beni, Jeanine A\u00f1ez joined picket lines and was among six legistlators and a dozen indigenous representatives of [[CONAMAQ]] that went on hunger strike in protest to the legistlation being passed by the MAS majority in both chambers. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2013/10/4/conflicto-escanos-agrava-tres-piquetes-huelguistas-2255.html|title=Conflict over seats worsens, there are three pickets of strikers|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=4 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2013/10/4/opositores-bolivianos-inician-huelga-hambre-contra-reduccion-escanos-2289.html|title=Bolivian opposition members start hunger strike against reduction of seats|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=4 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, \u00c1\u00f1ez made complaints about the lack of financial transparency from the government. Requests for reports as part of opposition legislators ability to audit the activities of the state were delayed and in 499 out of 1979 cases for the 2013-14 period received no response. The authorities, according to the regulations of the Chamber of Deputies, were permitted 10 business days to respond to a request for a report, and in the Senate, 15 days. If the request for a written report is not answered, an injunction can be issued to give a time limit of 48 hours. \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that in many cases, these injunctions were ignored and there was a \"denial of information\". Many of the projects had multi-million budgets with several interested parties for whom access is even more restricted.  \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that in many cases which do receive replies \"they are responses without response\". Responses included two sheets of photocopies, material unrelated to the request or boxes full of documents which do \"not intend to clarify the doubts, but to hinder the work of the legislators.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2014/2/9/denuncian-trabas-acceso-informacion-para-fiscalizar-13544.html|title=They denounce obstacles in access to information for auditing|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=8 February 2014}}</ref> In 2019-2020, many of these cases are under investigation. <ref name=corruption>{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/america-latina/2019/12/22/bolivia-se-suman-denuncias-por-corrupcion-fraude-y-malos-manejos-de-empresas-publicas-durante-los-anos-de-evo-morales/|title=Bolivia: Allegations of corruption, fraud and mismanagement of public companies during the years of Evo Morales accumulate|language=es|website=Infobae|date=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she was one of three Senators to make a complaint against Gisela L\u00f3pez, then  Minister for Public Works. This involved the management of the state-owned Bolivia TV and undocumented expenditure of more than $40 million. The case had already been the target of more than 30 obstructed complaints by a former minister. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/52748_piden-informe-a-lopez-sobre-millonario-desembolso|website=www.eldeber.com.bo|date=14 April 2018|language=es|title=Report requested from Lopez over multi-million disbursement}}</ref> In 2019, this would become the centre of the Neurona case in which L\u00f3pez and 22 others \"are suspected of the alleged crimes of improper use of influence, negotiations incompatible with the exercise of public functions, breach of duties, contracts harmful to the State and uneconomic conduct\". <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/158496_gobierno-acusa-a-exministra-lopez-por-corrupcion-e-inicia-una-querella|date=2 December 2019|title=Government accuse exminister Lopez of corruption and begin lawsuit|language=es|website=www.eldeber.com.bo}}</ref> Also in 2018, she presented a bill to the Senate to combat \"[[revenge porn|sexual blackmail]]\" stating \"Social networks lend themselves to everything, we have seen that the viralization of intimate videos has become an extortion mechanism , and on some occasions it is to blackmail psychologically and economically, so the intention is to penalize and specifically typify it\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/64136_sexo-chantaje-el-proyecto-de-ley-que-quiere-penalizar-difusion-de-videos-intimos|title=Sexual blackmail: The bill that wants to penalise the spread of intimate videos|date=25 October 2018|language=es|website=www.eldeber.com.bo}}</ref> In the wake of her becoming president, anti-\u00c1\u00f1ez posters spread a pornographic video with her as the alleged protagonist on social media which she denied and called a \"vile attack\". <ref name=porno>{{cite web|url=https://politico.mx/minuta-politica/internacional/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-rechaza-supuesto-video-sexual-es-un-ataque-vil/|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez denies supposed sexual video|date=20 November 2019|language=es|website=www.politico.mx}}</ref>\n\nBy 2019, she was elected as the second vice president of the Senate, and her alternate was Franklin Valdivia Leigue.<ref name=\":0\" /> This role placed her fifth in the [[President of Bolivia#Current line of succession|line of succession to the presidency]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Before the presidential elections in 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez had questioned the reliability of opinion polls, based on unclear methods and inconsistent results.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/8/19/piden-informe-escrito-al-tse-por-la-encuestadora-viaciencia-228016.html |title=Piden informe escrito al TSE por la encuestadora ViaCiencia |last= |first= |date= |website=Diario Pagina Siete |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===<span id=\"Interim president of Bolivia (2019\u2013present)\"></span>Interim President of Bolivia (2019\u2013present)===\n\n====Initial protest period====\n\nOn 10 November, Morales and his vice president, [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]], [[Evo Morales government resignation|resigned from office]] after pressure from political opponents and civic groups and losing support from former political allies, the police and the [[Armed Forces of Bolivia|military]];<ref name=\"Londo\u00f1o\">Ernesto Londo\u00f1o, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/evo-morales-bolivia.html Bolivian Leader Evo Morales Steps Down], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (10 November 2019).</ref>. This was followed by the resignation of [[Adriana Salvatierra Arriaza]], the president of the [[Bolivian Senate]], who was next in the constitutional line of succession<ref name=\"GuerreroAndone\">Kay Guerrero & Dakin Andone, [https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/10/americas/bolivia-new-election-audit/index.html Bolivian President Evo Morales steps down following accusations of election fraud], CNN (10 November 2019).</ref>\u2014leading to a situation where all constitutional successors were exhausted. The role of acting President of the Senate would normally fall to the vice-president of the Senate, Rub\u00e9n Medinaceli, but since he also had resigned, the position fell to A\u00f1ez as second vice-president of the Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/76278_salvatierra-asume-pide-que-haya-mas-inclusion-de-mujeres-y-jovenes|title=Salvatierra sworn in; Calls for more inclusion of women and young people|website=El Deber|date=18 January 2019|language=es|author=Jes\u00fas Alanoca Paco}}</ref> Thus A\u00f1ez became the highest-ranking official in the line of succession to the presidency of Bolivia and stated an acceptance to fill the role if needed. The succession was not automatic, however, as the Legislative Assembly would need to hold emergency meetings to accept the abdications of the President and Vice-President and determine who was next in line due to the lack of constitutional guidance.<ref name=\"vicepresidente1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-50370125 |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez en proceso de ratificaci\u00f3n tras renuncia del Presidente, Vicepresidente, Presidente del Senado y Presidente de la C\u00e1mara de Diputados de Bolivia |editor=BBC News Mundo |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez could not attend an emergency assembly until the day after Morales' resignation, as she was in Beni and there were no Sunday flights from there to the capital of [[La Paz]].<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nOn 11 November, A\u00f1ez arrived at [[El Alto International Airport|La Paz-El Alto airport]] and was taken in a military helicopter to a nearby Air Force base. From there, she traveled to the Bolivian Senate. At 4pm, an emergency vote took place to formally accept the resignations of the previous day. <ref name=\"Huff-Post\">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.fr/entry/apres-la-demission-devo-morales-les-insoumis-denoncent-un-coup-detat_fr_5dc91fa7e4b00927b236112e |title=Apr\u00e8s la d\u00e9mission d'Evo Morales, les insoumis d\u00e9noncent un \"coup d'\u00c9tat\" |date=11 November 2019 |website=Le Huffington Post}}</ref> Morales' MAS party, which still held a majority in the upper chamber, boycotted this vote. Constitutional experts Paul Coca and Israel Alanoca stated that, while the normal quorum would have been desirable for purpose of quelling accusations of a coup d'etat, there was no specific regulation to deal with the resignation of leaders and an emergency vote on the grounds of human rights concerns and establishing social peace would be legally valid.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/11/si-no-hay-quorum-en-la-alp-se-puede-apelar-al-voto-de-urgencia-237110.html|title=If there is no quorum in the ALP, an emergency vote can be applied|language=es|date=11 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn the evening of 12 November, per article 169 of the [[Constitution of Bolivia]], \u00c1\u00f1ez was declared acting [[president of Bolivia]] in front of a session of the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldeber.com.bo/156411_anez-asume-la-presidencia-de-bolivia-ante-vacancia-y-aplicando-la-sucesion-constitucional|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez asume la Presidencia de Bolivia ante vacancia y aplicando la sucesi\u00f3n constitucional|trans-title=\u00c1\u00f1ez assumes the Presidency of Bolivia due to vacancy and applying the constitutional succession|website=El Deber|language=es|access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> This vote was also boycotted by MAS, who dubbed the vote \"illegal\". <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/12/anez-asume-la-presidencia-para-pacificar-el-pais-237195.html|title=Anez assumes the presidency to pacify the country|language=es|date=12 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/12/evo-morales-arrives-mexico-bolivia-power-vacuum |title=Bolivia: Jeanine A\u00f1ez claims presidency after ousting of Evo Morales |location=La Paz |first1=Jo |last1=Tuckman |first2=Dan |last2=Collyns |date=13 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 November 2019 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 }}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/13/americas/bolivia-political-unrest-intl-hnk/index.html |title=Bolivian senator declares herself acting president -- but she may be on shaky ground |first1=Joshua |last1=Berlinger |first2=Gustavo |last2=Vald\u00e9s |website=CNN |access-date=13 November 2019 }}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez obtained the favorable vote of the remaining parties, a third part of the parliament. <ref>{{cite news |title=La senadora Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez se proclama presidenta de Bolivia sin qu\u00f3rum en el Parlamento |url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/11/12/america/1573566340_453048.html |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=13 November 2019 |accessdate=13 November 2019|issn=1134-6582|language=es|first=Francesco|last=Manetto}}</ref> The move was later upheld by the [[Plurinational Constitutional Court]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/156414_tcp-avala-sucesion-constitucional-en-la-presidencia|title=TCP avala sucesi\u00f3n constitucional en la Presidencia |trans-title=TCP uphelds constitutional succession in the Presidency |website=El Deber |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019 }}</ref> \n\nOn 13 November Salvatierra contended that her resignation was not valid since it had not been accepted by the Senate, and therefore, \u00c1\u00f1ez should not be able to assume the Presidency via becoming President of the Senate.<ref name=\"dispute\">{{cite news |title=Presidenta de Senado boliviano denuncia presi\u00f3n a dirigentes |url=https://www.telesurtv.net/news/bolivia-presidenta-senado-denuncia-presion-dirigentes-20191113-0021.html |accessdate=14 November 2019 |work=www.telesurtv.net |agency=teleSUR |date=13 November 2019 |language=es}}</ref> This prompted a further session on the Senate on 14 November, this time with the involvement of MAS, that reaffirmed Salvatierra's resignation more formally and elected M\u00f3nica Eva Copa from the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]] as the new president.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atb.com.bo/pol%C3%ADtica/eva-copa-es-la-nueva-presidenta-del-senado|language=es|title=Eva Copa is the new president of the Senate|date=15 November 2019|website=www.atb.com.bo}}</ref>\n\nAmid a pledge to \"rebuild democracy\", A\u00f1ez unveiled her new [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]]. Her senior ministers included prominent businesspeople from [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]]. The first eleven members of her cabinet did not include any members of the [[indigenous peoples in Bolivia]], which ''[[The Guardian]]'' described as a sign that she did \"not intend to reach across the country's deep political and ethnic divide\". Later appointments of the remaining positions would include two indigenous members. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Anez-completa-gabinete-ministra-Alto_0_3257674272.html|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez posesiona cinco nuevos ministros; Yujra besa la wiphala y va por di\u00e1logo con El Alto - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/ministros-posesion-bolivia-anez_0_3260074003.html|title=A\u00f1ez posesiona a Carlos Huallpa en Miner\u00eda y a Virginia Patty Torres en Educaci\u00f3n - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref> While Morales's first cabinet was majority indigenous (14 out of 16 positions), this number steadily decreased since 2009 and by 2017 contained only three indigenous members. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2006/01/23/actualidad/1137970802_850215.html|title=Morales toma juramento a los 16 ministros que integran el \"nuevo Gabinete del pueblo\"|work=El Pais|language=es|accessdate=13 April 2020|date=23 January 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/especial01/2017/1/22/gabinete-tuvo-rostros-indigenas-pero-pocos-ministros-poder-124588.html|title=Gabinete tuvo rostros ind\u00edgenas, pero pocos ministros con poder - Diario Pagina Siete|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Decree 4078 and repercussions ====\n\nOn 15 November, amid [[2019 Bolivian protests|continuing protests]], violence and [[2019 shortages in Bolivia|shortages]] in several main cities, A\u00f1ez issued Decree 4078 to enlist the police and army to pacify the country. Article 3 of the decree reads \"The personnel of the Armed Forces who participate in operations to restore internal order and public stability will be exempt from criminal liability when, in compliance with their constitutional functions, they acted in legitimate defense or state of necessity, in observance of the principles of legality, absolute necessity and proportionality.\u201d <ref name=HRO>{{cite web|url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/11/17/america/1574014107_965320.html|website=El Pais|language=es|date=17 November 2019|title=Alarm in Bolivia for impunity for the military who repress the protests|author=Francesco Manetto}}</ref> The same day, there was a confrontation close to [[Sacaba]] with pro-Morales supporters, mainly coca growers, while they were attempting to cross a bridge on which a police cordon has been set up. 9 people were killed and 17 injured, 11 of which showing wounds from projectiles. <ref name=sacaba>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/17/gobierno-niega-uso-de-armas-en-sacaba-suman-los-muertos-237622.html|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=17 November 2019|title=Government deny use of arms in Sacaba. The dead increase.}}</ref> Protesters say that they were fired upon without warning while the police report states that 201 people were involved in \"violent acts\" and 10 men were arrested for the \"crimes of armed uprising, possession and carrying of firearms, and manufacture and trade of explosive and suffocating substances\". Several human rights groups, including the [[Inter-American Commission on Human Rights|IACHR]], [[Amnesty International]], [[Human Rights Watch]] and the UN Human Rights Commission, called for the immediate revocation of Decree 4078.<ref name=HRO></ref> Amnesty International described it as a \"carte blanche\" for human rights abuses. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2019/11/bolivia-derogar-norma-impunidad-fuerzas-armadas/|date=18 November 2019|title=Bolivia: Jeanine A\u00f1ez must immediately repeal decree giving impunity to Armed Forces personnel|author=Amnesty International}}</ref> Government sources claimed that the bullets were not of the type used by the police while army garrison commander Alfredo Cu\u00e9llar stated that they were under no orders to shoot and would not be authorised to use lethal force in those circumstances. <ref name=sacaba></ref>.\n\nOn 28 November, the controversial decree was repealed by President A\u00f1ez, but not before a further massacre occurred in the [[Senkata]] district of [[El Alto]] in which another 9 people were killed and more injured.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/29/anez-abroga-polemico-decreto-luego-de-la-pacificacion-del-pais-238933.html|language=es|title=A\u00f1ez abrogates controversial decree in order to pacify country|date=29 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=IACHR></ref> The Senkata gas refinery plant had been attacked in previous days and a military escort was provided for a convoy of fuel trucks needed to relieve shortages in the cities of El Alto and LA Paz. While en route, a violent clash occurred.<ref name=IACHR></ref>The official government response was, again, that they had not fired shots and that they had been under attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20191121/fiscalia-confirma-ocho-fallecidos-por-enfrentamientos-en-senkata|title=Prosecutors office confirm 8 deaths due to clash in Senkata|date=21 November 2019|website=El Alteno|language=es}}</ref> Concerning the deaths, President \u00c1\u00f1ez said \"We deeply regret the deaths of our brothers in El Alto, it hurts us because we are a government of peace\" and called for dialogue to listen to the demands of the protesters. In addition, she asked international organizations and the church to accompany this process in order to stop the violence. \"Let's unite to reconcile, to build the Bolivia for which we are all fighting and so that one Bolivian is never above the other,\" said \u00c1\u00f1ez.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/157419_la-presidenta-jeanine-anez-lamenta-las-muertes-de-el-alto-y-pide-dialogo-para-pacificar-el-pais|website=El Deber|date=December 2019|language=es|title=President Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez mourns the deaths of El Alto and calls for dialogue to pacify the country}}</ref>\n\nOn invitation by the state, the IACHR conducted an investigation into the deaths and injuries that occurred during this period of violence. On 10 December they published their preliminary observations, based on interviews conducted with eyewitnesses. The stated that \"it is appropriate to describe these events as massacres, given the number of people who lost their lives in the same way and at the same time and place, and because the acts in question were committed against a specific group of people. Furthermore, the patterns of injuries that have been recorded point strongly to extrajudicial killing practices.\"<ref name=IACHR>{{cite web|url=http://www.oas.org/en/iachr/media_center/PReleases/2019/321.asp|date=10 December 2019|website=www.oas.org|title=IACHR Preliminary Findings}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/12/10/cidh-califica-hechos-de-sacaba-senakta-de-masacre-pide-investigacion-internacional-240095.html|date=10 December 2019|language=es|title=IACHR calls acts at Sacaba and Senkata massacres and asks for international investigation|website=P\u00e1gina Siete}}</ref> In ongoing talks with families of victims, proposed compensation relating to Decree 4100 includes 100000 Bolivianos ($15000) for families of those killed and from 12500 to 50000 Bolivianos for those injured, the amount depending on severity. By request of the families, the amount is to be given in humanitarian aid (including 12 months of food) rather than a single payment. It also allows the victims to seek help from international organisations. A final agreement has not been reached as there is general mistrust in the government to follow through on their promises. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2020/2/6/victimas-de-senkata-gobierno-negocian-acuerdo-de-seis-puntos-245777.html|date=6 February 2020|title=Victims of Senkata and government negotiate agreement on 6 points.|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete}}</ref>\n\nAfter taking office, the governments of [[Canada]], [[Brazil]], the [[European Union]], [[Russia]] and the [[United States]] recognized \u00c1\u00f1ez as the acting president of Bolivia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Canada will 'support' Bolivian opposition government |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/bolivia-canada-anez-government-1.5360138 |work=CBC News |date=14 November 2019}}</ref>{{when|date=December 2019}}<!-- the timing of this recognition should be included in the prose -->\n\n====Later activity====\n\nEarly on, \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that Morales would not be permitted to run in an upcoming election for a fourth term, should he return to Bolivia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-bolivias-interim-leader-says-evo-morales-cant-run-in-new-election/ |title=Bolivia's interim leader says Evo Morales can't run in new election |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bolivia-interim-president-bars-morales-from-new-elections/a-51259511 |title=Bolivia: Interim president bars Morales from new elections |date=15 November 2019  |website=www.dw.com |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> This was verified by the Constitutional Court, who reversed their decision to overturn the [[2016 Bolivian constitutional referendum]] which permitted all public figures to have an unlimited number of terms. This also prevented the vice-president from running for a fourth term. The decision was further ratified on 23 November when a bill was first approved by the Senate and then later in the day by the lower house, both of which are dominated by Morales' Movement Toward Socialism party.<ref name=bills>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bolivian-election-lawmakers-approve-new-elections-with-rules-barring-ex-president-evo-morales-from-running/|title=Bolivian lawmakers approve new election rules barring ex-President Morales from running|date=23 November 2019|website=cbsnews}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 November, \u00c1\u00f1ez rejected a bill presented by Morales' party that would have prevented the ousted president, and all others in his party, from being tried for alleged crimes committed during the exercise of their functions to date. \"With respect to approving this bill in favor of those who have committed crimes and who now seek impunity, my decision is clear and firm: I will not promulgate this law,\" \u00c1\u00f1ez said. The bill did not have full support within MAS with one member of the Chamber of Deputies stating \"I ask the president [Morales] to reflect and really listen to the Bolivian people,\" and claimed that for years the \"oppressed wing\" of MAS suffered discrimination from within the party.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/12/28/ortiz-pide-morales-reflexionar-pensar-en-el-pueblo-241794.html|title=Ortiz asks Morales to reflect and think about the people.|date=28 December 2019|language=es|website=www.paginasiete.bo}}</ref>\n\nSince then, the \u00c1\u00f1ez government has led numerous investigations and charges of corruption against members of previous administration and those linked to them. The majority involve embezzlement or misappropriation of state owned companies and awarding of state contracts where there was a conflict of interest. These include Entel, a state communications company that saw losses of $250 million and was described as the \"petty cash\" of MAS, the Neurona case, the Bolivian Highway Administrator that saw $310 million dollars disappear into uncompleted or unobserved projects, investments in state owned petroleum projects that were not developed and the multimillion diversion of money from the Indigenous Fund. All of the previous cases involved government ministers and several were subject to complaints from members of the opposition in the past.<ref name=corrupcion></ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/ciudad/20171021/opositores-afirman-que-el-mas-se-dana-en-corrupcion|website=www.elalteno.com|language=es|date=22 October 2017|title=Opposition agree that MAS damages itself through corruption}}</ref> Corruption watchdogs have observed that corruption was common under the MAS government and continues to be a problem in the interim government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20190130/informe-de-corrupcion-pone-al-pais-nivel-de-un-regimen-autoritario|website=www.elalteno.com|language=es|title=Corruption report puts the country at the level of an authoritarian regime|date=30 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=casos>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20200108/gobierno-investiga-592-exautoridades-de-la-gestion-de-morales-y-familiares-por|website=www.elalteno.com.bo|date=8 January 2020|language=es|title=Government investigates 592 ex-authorities of the Morales era}}</ref> The level of prosecutions have led to accusations of political persecution from human rights groups.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/2/29/cuatro-organismos-internacionales-se-pronunciaron-advirtiendo-violacion-derechos-en-bolivia-248178.html|website=www.paginasiete.bo|title=Four human rights organisations spoke out against human rights violations in Bolivia|language=es|date=29 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=casos></ref> Similar observations were also made during the Morales era.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2016/country-chapters/bolivia|website=www.hrw.org|title=2016 Human Rights Report (Bolivia)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2019/country-chapters/bolivia|website=www.hrw.org|title=2019 Human Rights Report (Bolivia)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/andes-to-the-amazon/2017/apr/08/top-bolivian-ngo-faces-forced-eviction|website=www.guardian.com|title=Top Bolivian NGO faces forced eviction|date=8 April 2018}}</ref> In response to prosecutions, the government claim that \"It must be remembered that the current Judicial Branch, be it the Supreme Court of Justice, the Constitutional Court, the Council of the Magistracy, all have been appointed by MAS and in other cases have been preselected by MAS.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/3/8/reportaje-de-washington-post-ve-ola-de-persecucion-en-bolivia-248951.html|title=Washington Post see wave of persecution in Bolivia.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/04/29/bolivia-dozens-judges-arbitrarily-dismissed|website=www.hrw.org|title=Bolivia: Dozens of judges arbitrarily dismissed|date=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Straits Times]], the new interim government of president Jeanine A\u00f1ez has \"denounced foreign influence in the country since taking power, naming Colombians, Peruvians, Cubans and Venezuelans at different times... blaming foreigners for provoking violent clashes during post-election violence.\"<ref name=GAT>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/americas/bolivia-unveils-anti-terror-unit-to-fight-threatening-foreign-groups |title=Bolivia unveils anti-terror unit to fight 'threatening' foreign groups |date=4 December 2019 |website=The Straits Times}}</ref> Bolivia has had long-standing problems with foreign groups involved in organised crime, largely the drug trade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20171025/denuncian-presencia-de-narcotraficantes-colombianos-peruanos-y-brasilenos-en-el|title=They denounce presence of Colombian, Peruvian and Brazilian drug traffickers in Beni|language=es|date=25 October 2017|website=www.elalteno.com.bo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20180523/policia-desbarata-banda-de-colombianos-vinculada-al-prestamo-gota-gota|date=23 May 2018|title=Police disrupt Colombian gang linked to the 'drop by drop' loan|language=es|website=www.elalteno.com.bo}}</ref> Police arrested an Argentine national and fugitive since 2017, 44-year-old Facundo Morales Schoenfeld, in the eastern province of Santa Cruz. He was previously a member of the [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia]] (FARC) and was participating among the protesters in [[Yapacan\u00ed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eltiempo.com/justicia/conflicto-y-narcotrafico/en-bolivia-fue-capturado-alias-camilo-exguerrillero-de-las-farc-433296|website=www.eltiempo.com|language=es|date=14 November 2019|title=Who is the 'Argentine', ex-Farc captured after protests in Bolivia?}}</ref> Around the same time, four Cubans were discovered in El Alto with 90000 Bs ($13000) contained in two backpacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/156665_la-policia-investiga-y-detiene-a-nueve-subditos-extranjeros|date=15 November 2019|title=Police investigate and detain 9 foreign subjects|language=es}}</ref> Venezuelan migrants, many fleeing the current unrest in their country, had been subject to accusations of \"political activity\" and involvement in criminal activities under the Morales government, with human rights groups expressing concern about persecution of Venezuelans in Bolivia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20190403/canciller-advierte-que-venezolanos-no-pueden-hacer-politica-en-el-pais|title=Chancellor warns that Venezuelans cannot do politics in Bolivia|language=es|date=4 March 2019|website=www.elalteno.com.bo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Amnesty International demands that Bolivia stop the persecution and expulsion of Venezuelans|language=es|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20190328/amnistia-internacional-exige-bolivia-que-pare-la-persecucion-y-expulsion-de|website=www.elalteno.com.bo}}</ref> While police and interim government ministers have cited involvement of armed and politically aligned Venezuelans in pro-Morales protests<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/21/hay-16-carreteras-bloqueadas-amenazan-con-cerrar-aeropuerto-238015.html|title=16 roads are blocked and threaten to close airport|language=es|date=21 November 2019|website=www.paginasiete.bo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/16/detienen-venezolanos-con-armas-en-beni-continuan-los-ataques-terroristas-237545.html|title=9 Venezuelans detained with weapons in Beni and terrorist attacks continue|language=es|date=16 November 2019}}</ref>, they have also granted amnesty to Venezuelan refugees, extended permanence and transit of Venezualan citizens and approved a resolution to help Venezuelan children and adolescents. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/2/12/el-gobierno-otorgo-refugio-54-venezolanos-246424.html|title=The government granted refuge to 54 Venezuelans|date=12 February 2020|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/2/3/bolivia-legalizara-permanencia-transito-de-ciudadanos-venezolanos-245466.html|title=Bolivia will legalise permanence and transit of Venezuelan citizenz|date=3 February 2020|language=es|website=www.paginasiete.bo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2020/1/30/aprueban-resolucion-que-favorece-ninos-venezolanos-245030.html|title=Resolution approved which favours Venezuelan children}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 November, 700 Cuban doctors were expelled from Bolivia. The Cuban doctor program had been a subject of controversy in Bolivia in previous years with the Bolivian medical workers union (FESIMRAS) complaining that Cubans needed only a simple photocopy to practice medicine whereas the requirements for Bolivians were much more stringent and many medical professionals were unemployed.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2019/5/23/medicos-cubanos-pueden-ejercer-en-bolivia-solo-con-fotocopia-simple-denuncia-fesimras-218913.html|title=Cuban doctors can practice in Bolivia with only a simple photocopy, FESIMRAS denounce|language=es|date=23 May 2019|website=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20190316/denuncian-que-el-estado-gasta-bs-14-mil-al-mes-por-cada-medico-cubano|title=They denounce that the state wastes 14000 Bs per month on each Cuban doctor.|date=16 March 2019|website=www.elalteno.com.bo|language=es}}</ref><ref name=Larrea></ref>The interim government stated that the Cuban embassy was paid $147 million over the course of 13 years for the Cuban doctors program and the president of the Medical College of La Paz, Luis Larrea, claimed that there was \"indiscriminate use of state assets, the waste of state money deposited in private accounts to, supposedly, pay Cubans, when these resources should be in a fiscal account,\" and that the Bolivian doctor felt \"belittled\".<ref name=Larrea>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20200123/anez-destapa-la-corrupcion-del-mas-y-dice-labor-cumplida|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez uncovers the corruption of the MAS and says \"work accomplished\"|language=es|website=www.elalteno.com.bo|date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2019/12/9/larrea-dice-que-el-gobierno-de-morales-despilfarro-dinero-menosprecio-al-medico-boliviano-239903.html|title=Larrea says the Morales government wasted money and belittled the Bolivian doctor|language=es|date=9 December 2019|website=www.elalteno.com.bo}}</ref> There have also been suggestions that only 205 out of 702 were doctors with the remaining working as drivers, technicians and in other areas that had nothing to do with medicine \"but were assigned salaries of 1,032, dollars\" as if they were doctors and that documents for these workers were falsified.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20191129/de-los-702-cubanos-solo-205-eran-medicos-pero-ganaban-buen-sueldo|title=Of the 702 Cubans, only 205 were doctors but they earned good salaries|language=es|website=www.elalteno.com.bo|date=29 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://eldeber.com.bo/162196_gobierno-de-evo-gasto-us-147-millones-en-medicos-cubanos|title=Evo's govenmnet wasted $147 million on Cuban doctors|date=January 2020</ref> The former head of the Cuban doctors program in Bolvia, Carlos de la Rocha, is facing charges of breach of duties, destruction of documents and theft, among other crimes. De la Rocha maintains his innocence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/161953_aprehenden-a-exfuncionario-responsable-del-programa-de-medicos-cubanos-en-bolivia|title=Former official responsible for the Cuban doctors program in Bolivia apprehended|language=es|date=January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/1/7/de-la-rocha-asegura-ser-inocente-que-manejo-todo-transparentemente-242714.html|title=De la Rocha claims to be innocent and that he handled everything transparently|language=es|website=www.paginasiete.bo|date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe interim government and President have explicitly signaled an attempt to disassociate themselves with countries that were political allies of Morales and \"anti imperialist ideology\". Chancellor [[Karen Longaric]] stated \"The relationship with Venezuela, Nicaragua and Cuba was aimed at consolidating an ideological current that had a geopolitical project. Bolivia did not benefit at all. It has always contributed more than it received and we are a developing country that cannot afford to make contributions or invest outside the country and sustaining other economies\" and that \"Bolivia did not want to participate in the association agreements with the EU, unlike Peru, Ecuador and Colombia, which did and that benefited, for example, with the elimination of visas to travel to Europe. Bolivia at the time moved away demonizing free trade agreements and treaties.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/1/6/gobierno-da-un-giro-las-relaciones-diplomaticas-bolivianas-con-decisiones-242520.html|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es|date=6 January 2020|title=Government reverses Bolivian diplomatic relations with 4 decisions}}</ref> This direction was further highlighted in the closure and replacement of the General [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Torres]] Anti-Imperialist Command School<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-37114191|website=www.bbc.com|date=18 August 2016|title=Bolivia opens 'anti-imperialist' school to counter US}}</ref><ref name=anti-imp>{{cite web|website=www.lostiempos.com|language=es|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20200116/sustituyen-escuela-antiimperialista-heroes-nancahuazu|title=The anti-imperialist school is replaced by H\u00e9roes de \u00d1ancahuaz\u00fa}}</ref>, an institution that made many military and political opponents uneasy as it was viewed as an attempt to align the military to a political ideology more sympathetic to that of Morales' MAS party. A ministry of defense press release stated that \"The core of the teaching focuses on anti-imperialist content with different components for the benefit of sergeants, second lieutenants, lieutenants, captains and above\". Taking and passing these courses was compulsory in order to achieve promotion to all ranks for captain and below.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindef.gob.bo/mindef/node/3257|title=Anti-imperialist School reinterprets history through the logic of the South|website=www.mindef.gob.bo|date=29 November 2018|language=es}}</ref><ref name=anti-imp></ref> In 2016, its opening was attended by the ministers of Defense of Nicaragua, Martha Ruiz Sevilla, and of Venezuela, the controversial [[Vladimir Padrino L\u00f3pez]].<ref>{{cite web|website=www.theguardian.com|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/aug/17/bolivia-anti-imperialist-military-school-evo-morales-us|title=Bolivia opens 'anti-imperialist' military school to counter US foreign policies|date=16 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=anti-imp></ref> The interim government had previously made it no longer compulsory to shout the phrase \"Patria o muerte\" (\"Fatherland or death\") during military activities. The phrase, popularised by [[Fidel Castro]] in a 1960 speech, was integrated into the military in 2010 by Morales, replacing the traditional \"subordinaci\u00f3n y constancia, viva Bolivia hacia el mar\" (\"subordination and constancy, long live Bolivia towards the sea\").<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/america-latina/2019/12/05/el-grito-de-patria-o-muerte-fue-eliminado-de-los-actos-militares-en-bolivia/|title=The cry of \"fatherland or death\" has been eliminated from military acts in Bolivia.|date=5 December 2019|language=es|website=www.infobae.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 December, the formation of a new anti-terrorist group, Grupo Anti-Terrorista (GAT), was announced to combat terrorist groups and narcotics traffickers.<ref name=GAT></ref> \n\nOn 10 December, \u00c1\u00f1ez created a committee to facilitate the return of an estimated 1300 political exiles created during the government of former President Evo Morales. She stated that \"The committee will not help people who are prosecuted for crimes against humanity or for drug trafficking.\" These exiles would include Manfred Reyes Villa, Mario Coss\u00edo, Branko Marinkovic and Elsner Larraz\u00e1bal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20191205/gobierno-crea-comite-para-el-retorno-de-los-perseguidos-politicos|title=Government creates committee for the return of persecuted politicians|date=10 December 2019|website=www.elalteno.com.bo|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/america-latina/2019/12/04/un-comite-investigara-las-denuncias-de-persecucion-politica-durante-los-anos-de-gobierno-de-evo-morales/|title=A committee will investigate allegations of political persecution during the years of Evo Morales' government|date=10 December 2019|language=es|website=www.infobae.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20160528/periodistas-politicos-denuncian-persecucion|website=Los Tiempos|date=28 May 2016|language=es|title=Journalists and politicians denounce persecution}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 December 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez sent a bill to the Plurinational Legislative Assembly in which it would be mandatory for candidates to take part in debates. She stated of electoral debate that \"it is an obligation. Democracy thrives on freedom and the freedom to be responsible requires information\". During the almost 14 years that Morales ruled Bolivia, he never agreed to debate with any candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20191231/anez-envia-alp-proyecto-ley-que-plantea-debate-obligatorio-candidatos|website=www.lostiempos.com|language=es|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez submits a bill to assembly that raises mandatory debate between candidates}}</ref> This bill was rejected by the opposition ruled Assembly and \u00c1\u00f1ez appealed to them to reconsider on the grounds of \"making democracy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20200117/anez-apela-alp-aprobar-ley-debate-obligatorio-rumbo-elecciones|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez appeals to ALP to approve bill on obligatory electoral debates|date=13 January 2020|language=es|website=www.lostiempos.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 January 2020, the government decided to ratify the 22 January public holiday created by Morales to celebrate the founding of the [[Plurinational State of Bolivia]] via the 2009 constitution. On this day, the President of Bolivia normally addresses the nation, but doubt had been expressed whether this holiday would go ahead due to its strong political connection with Morales and MAS. In a public statement, however, minister for the Presidency [[Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], said \"January 22 is a holiday by presidential decree, we are going to respect that decree and our president is evaluating if she is going to make a report about the pillars of this government, which are transition, pacification and management.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/1/7/gobierno-ratifica-feriado-del-22-de-enero-anez-evalua-informe-de-gestion-242710.html | title=Government ratifies 22 January holiday and A\u00f1ez considers management address|language=es}}</ref> In this speech, she thanked the indigenous people of Bolivia for \"having accompanied the process with wisdom and firm decision\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theworldnews.net/bo-news/somos-un-pueblo-que-no-se-rinde|website=www.theworldnews.net|title=Plurinational State Day Presidential Speech|date=23 January 2020|language=es}}</ref>\n\nSince early March 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez has implemented numerous controls concerning the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bolivia|coronavirus pandemic]] including closing all borders, prohibiting all international and interdepartmental flights, a strict nationwide curfew and restricting driving to those transporting foods and supplies and those carrying out essential services. This crisis has also resulted in the postponement of the upcoming [[2020 Bolivian general election]], the delay having been agreed upon by all parties involved.\n\nOn 21 April 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez and her cabinet pledged to donate 50% of their monthly salary towards a fund to help those affected by the coronavirus pandemic and encouraged other parliamentarians to do the same. The President's monthly salary is currently Bs 24,251 ($3,520); that of a Minister of State of Bs 21,556 ($3,130); and that of a Vice Minister of Bs 20,210 ($2,930). The initial sum is Bs 250,000 ($36,290) per month. There is also an account managed by the ministry of health that anyone can donate to.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.la-razon.com/nacional/2020/04/21/anez-y-ministros-aportan-50-de-sus-sueldos-a-un-fondo-para-afectados-por-la-cuarentena/|website=www.la-razon.com|date=21 April 2020|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez and ministers donate 50% of earnings to fund for those affected by coronavirus|language=es}}</ref>\n\n===2020 Presidential Candidacy===\n\nOn 5 December, \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that she would not be a candidate or support any candidate in the upcoming presidential election.<ref>[https://rpp.pe/mundo/latinoamerica/bolivia-jeanine-anez-no-postulara-a-la-presidencia-segun-el-gobierno-interino-noticia-1233337 Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez no postular\u00e1 a la Presidencia de Bolivia, seg\u00fan el Gobierno interino.] Publicado el 5 de diciembre de 2019. Consultado el 8 de diciembre de 2019.</ref> This was further reiterated on 15 January 2020 by Minister for the Presidency [[:w:es:Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez|Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], who said that \"[\u00c1\u00f1ez] will not be a candidate. The President has stated on several occasions, she will not be a candidate, this is a government of peace, transition, and management because you can not stop the state apparatus.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/jeanine-anez-presidencia-gobierno-elecciones-bolivia_0_3294870527.html| language=es|title=Government clarifies that Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez will not be a candidate for the Presidency}}</ref>\n\nDespite her previous statements, \u00c1\u00f1ez announced her candidacy on 24 January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atb.com.bo/pol\u00edtica/jeanine-\u00e1\u00f1ez-confirma-candidatura-presidencial-para-las-elecciones-generales|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez confirma candidatura presidencial para las elecciones generales|date=24 January 2020|access-date=24 January 2020|website=ATBDigital|language=es-ES}}</ref> A survey reported in the Bolivian newspaper ''[[Los Tiempos]]'' indicated that, while 43% of respondents considered her to have done a \"good or very good\" job as interim president (compared to 27% bad or very bad), only 24% of respondents believed that she should stand as a candidate in the upcoming elections. In the same poll, 63% of respondents agreed with the statement that \"as interim president, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez should call elections and not take advantage of her power to become a presidential candidate.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20200126/encuesta-aprueban-gestion-anez-pero-rechazan-candidatura| title=Survey approves of \u00c1\u00f1ez's term as president, but rejects her candidacy.|language=es|date=26 January 2020}}</ref> Her running mate who was previously critical of her decision to stand as a presidential candidate is [[Samuel Doria Medina]], a former presidential candidate and leader of the center-right [[National Unity Front]] party.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/03/05/bolivia-after-the-ouster-of-evo-morales-a-leftist-strongman| title=Bolivia after the ouster of Evo Morales, a leftist strongman|date= 7 March 2020}}</ref>. They are standing under the newly formed [[Juntos (Bolivian political party)|Juntos]] alliance. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Unidad-Nacional-Sole-Vicepresidencia-Juntos_0_3304469555.html|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez and Doria Medina seal alliance and become presidential running mates| language=es|date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nA\u00f1ez is described as a [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-idUSKBN1XM1NV |title=Bolivian Senate head assumes interim presidency; Morales' loyalists object |date=13 November 2019 |work=Reuters |access-date=15 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191113-bolivian-senator-declares-herself-president-morales-denounces-coup |title=Bolivian senator declares herself interim president, Morales slams 'coup' |date=13 November 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> [[Religious conservatism|religious conservative]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/bolivia-s-new-leader-religious-conservative-jeanine-ez-chavez-faces-n1082426 |title=Bolivia's new leader, religious conservative Jeanine A\u00f1ez Chavez, faces daunting challenges |website=NBC News |language=en |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/14/bolivia-interim-leader-recognises-guaido-legitimate-venezuelan/ |title=Bolivia interim leader recognises Guaido as legitimate Venezuelan leader as balance shifts |last=Staff |first=Our Foreign |date=14 November 2019 |work=The Telegraph |access-date=15 November 2019 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> and has been a critic of Evo Morales.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bolivia-senator-jeanine-anez-declares-herself-interim-president/a-51218963 |title=Bolivia: Senator Jeanine Anez declares herself interim president {{!}} DW {{!}} 12 November 2019 |last= |first= |date= |website=Deutsche Welle |language=en-GB |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Drugs===\n\u00c1\u00f1ez has spoken out against the proliferation of drug trafficking in South America.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2017/10/20/narcotrafico-anez-llama-canalla-romero-dice-sobrino-responsable-actos-156480.html |title=Narcotr\u00e1fico: A\u00f1ez llama \"canalla\" a Romero y dice que su sobrino es responsable de sus actos |last= |first= |date= |website=Diario Pagina Siete |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, her nephew was arrested in Brazil for smuggling 480 kilos of drugs. The security minister [[Carlos Romero (Bolivian politician)|Carlos Romero]] criticized \u00c1\u00f1ez and said that her position in the senate was \"rogue\" because of the relationship; \u00c1\u00f1ez responded by saying that she is not responsible for her nephew's actions, and criticized Romero because of his position in the government by saying that he is \"responsible for the growth of drug trafficking\". It was later revealed that another Bolivian arrested with drugs at the same time was the nephew of another politician, this time belonging to the MAS ruling party.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===Prison services===\nIn early 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez called for an investigation into prison wardens in Beni after speaking to victims of rape and abuse on the part of guards. She aimed to set a precedent to bring in new legislation that can be upheld.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eju.tv/2019/03/senadora-jeanine-anez-pide-al-gobierno-investigar-todas-carceletas-del-beni/ |title=Senadora Jeanine A\u00f1ez pide al Gobierno investigar todas carceletas del Beni |website=eju.tv |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nShe describes herself as a [[Christianity|Christian]] and held up a large Bible while declaring herself the interim president; this was described by ''The Guardian'' as an \"explicit rebuke\" of Morales, who has a strained [[Evo Morales and the Roman Catholic Church|history with the Catholic Church]] and has expressed support for indigenous religious traditions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191113-jeanine-anez-stand-in-president-vowing-to-pacify-bolivia |title=Jeanine Anez: stand-in president vowing to 'pacify' Bolivia |date=13 November 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/13/jeanine-anez-bolivia-president-promises-new-elections |title=Bolivia's interim president Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez promises new elections |last=Collyns |first=Dan |date=13 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 November 2019 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Under Morales, a new [[Constitution of Bolivia|Constitution]] was [[2009 Bolivian constitutional referendum|approved by referendum]] that gave Christianity equal status to other religions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-11/bolivia-faces-power-vacuum-and-more-chaos-after-morales-quits |title=Senator Brandishing Giant Bible Takes Over Bolivia Presidency |date=11 November 2019 |website=Bloomberg |language=en |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> A 2018 survey found that 70% of Bolivians identified as Catholic and 17.2% as Protestant of some form. 9.3% were non-religious.<ref>[https://www.statista.com/statistics/1066911/religious-affiliation-in-bolivia/ \u2022 Religion affiliations in Bolivia 2018 | Statista<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Political analyst Carlos Cordero states that \u201cShe is a believer, but she does not use her religiosity politically, she expresses it, she lives it.\u201d<ref>https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/12/30/las-quince-diferencias-en-el-estilo-de-gobernar-de-jeanine-anez-morales-241950.html</ref>\n\n===Venezuela===\n\u00c1\u00f1ez recognized [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]] as acting president of Venezuela in the [[2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis]], 24 hours after taking office.<ref name=\"Alberto\">{{cite web |url=https://albertonews.com/principales/ultima-hora-bolivia-reconoce-a-juan-guaido-como-presidente-e-de-venezuela/ |title=Bolivia reconoce a Juan Guaid\u00f3 como presidente (E) de Venezuela |date=13 November 2019 |website=Albertonews.com |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> Her interim government also severed diplomatic relations with Venezuela's Maduro government, giving its diplomats 72 hours to leave the country.<ref name=\"lapiensa\">{{cite web |url=https://latinoamericapiensa.com/la-politica-internacional-de-anez-anuncio-la-salida-de-bolivia-del-alba-de-la-unasur-y-rompio-relaciones-con-venezuela/21065/ |title=La pol\u00edtica internacional de A\u00f1ez: anunci\u00f3 la salida de Bolivia del Alba, de la Unasur y rompi\u00f3 relaciones con Venezuela |language=es |website=Latinomerica Piensa |date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-bolivia-election-venezuela/bolivas-interim-government-to-ask-venezuelan-diplomats-to-leave-the-country-idUKKBN1XP23U |title=Boliva's interim government to ask Venezuelan diplomats to leave the country |website=Reuters |date=15 November 2019}}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez has also called on Guaid\u00f3 to appoint the new Venezuelan Ambassador to Bolivia, \"who will be recognized immediately by our government.\"<ref name=\"Alberto\"/>\n\nA month later, her government announced Bolivia's entry into the [[Lima Group]], a regional bloc established in 2017 with the purpose of finding a way out of the [[Crisis in Venezuela|Venezuelan crisis]]. The Bolivian foreign ministry said in a statement that it hoped to \u201ccontribute to a peaceful, democratic and constitutional solution to the crisis in Venezuela, which must be guided by the Venezuelan people.\u201d<ref>{{cite web | last1=Sigal | first1=Lucila | title=Bolivia announces entry into Lima Group to resolve Venezuelan crisis | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-politics/bolivia-announces-entry-into-lima-group-to-resolve-venezuelan-crisis-idUSKBN1YQ0JM | date=22 December 2019 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> On the same month, the interim government announced that they would give refuge to 200 Venezuelans \"who have fled their country for reasons of political order, of political persecution promoted by the [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] government.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/es/bolivia-dar%C3%A1-refugio-a-200-venezolanos-que-huyeron-por-persecuci%C3%B3n-pol%C3%ADtica/a-51665845|title=Bolivia will shelter 200 Venezuelans who fled for \"political persecution\"|last=|first=|date=13 December 2019|work=[[Deutsch Welle]]|access-date=4 January 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n===Violence against women and children===\nDuring her second senatorial term, \u00c1\u00f1ez was associated with legislative works to combat feminicides and violence against women which has become a continuing theme for her politically.<ref name=CIDOB></ref>\n\nOn 6 February 2020, she invited the people of Bolivia to attend a march in Santa Cruz in support of the fight against violence against women and children, an issue increasingly highlighted by the Bolivian press. <ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/rascacielos/2020/3/8/feminicidios-en-bolivia-suenos-robados-248613.html|language=es|date=8 March 2020|title=Feminicides in Bolivia: Stolen Dreams}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/2/6/anez-pide-denunciar-la-violencia-contra-mujeres-ninos-en-una-marcha-245817.html|date=6 February 2020| title=A\u00f1ez asks to denounce violence against women and children in a march|language=es}}</ref>\n\nOn [[International Women's Day]], 8 March 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez announced a $100 million investment in the fight against violence against women, She declared 2020 as the  Year of the Fight Against Feminicide and Infanticide in Bolivia, saying \"I am the worst news for all those murderers of women, users of violence, abusers, stalkers and rapists, because I will not get tired of closing against these aggressors\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.la-razon.com/sociedad/mujer-bolivia-anez-presidenta-violencia-genero_0_3326667313.html| title=\u00c1\u00f1ez: 'I will give everything to end gender violence'|language=es|date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2020/3/10/violencia-anez-lanza-plan-con-una-inversion-de-us-100-millones-249125.html|title=Violence: A\u00f1ez launches plan with an investment of $ us 100 million|language=es|date=8 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Racism controversy==\nAround 41% of the population of Bolivia identifies itself as [[Indigenous peoples in Bolivia|indigenous]]<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/15/world/americas/morales-bolivia-Indigenous-racism.html |title=Ethnic Rifts in Bolivia Burst Into View With Fall of Evo Morales |date=15 November 2019 |agency=The New York Times}}</ref> and the population often encounters discrimination regarding their social status in Bolivia, mainly related to poverty and ethnic background.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/could-bolivias-current-politics-be-fueling-indigenous-discrimination |title=Could Bolivia's current politics be fueling indigenous discrimination? |last= |first= |date=25 November 2019 |website=[[PBS NewsHour]] |language=en-us |access-date=3 December 2019}}</ref> Following the 2006 election of Evo Morales, the first indigenous president of Bolivia, polarization between the indigenous peoples and others increased<ref name=\":5\" /> as Bolivia's political system shifted from left-right politics to indigenous-urbanist politics.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Faguet |first=Jean-Paul |date=June 2019 |title=Revolution from Below: Cleavage Displacement and the Collapse of Elite Politics in Bolivia |url= http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/100505/1/Revolution_from_Below_in_Bolivia_2_Theory_v4_Full.docx|journal=[[Politics & Society]] |volume=47 |issue=2 |pages=205\u2013250 |doi=10.1177/0032329219845944 |quote=Politics shifted from a conventional left-right axis of competition, unsuited to Bolivian society, to an ethnic/rural\u2013cosmopolitan/urban axis closely aligned with its major social cleavage.|via= }}</ref>\n\nShortly after her inauguration, opponents of \u00c1\u00f1ez circulated [[Twitter#Tweets|tweets]] dating back to 2013 <ref name=\"elcomercio\">{{cite news |url=https://elcomercio.pe/mundo/latinoamerica/jeanine-anez-estos-son-los-agresivos-tuits-contra-originarios-e-indigenas-que-borro-la-presidenta-interina-de-bolivia-noticia/ |title=Estos son los agresivos tuits contra \"originarios\" e \"ind\u00edgenas\" que borr\u00f3 Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez, la presidenta de Bolivia |date=15 November 2019 |agency=Redaccion El Comercio}}</ref>. These tweets, directed towards indigenous peoples, have been described as \"racist\" by ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref name=\"guardian\" /> \"anti-indigenous\" by [[Agence France-Press]],<ref name=\"afp\">{{cite news |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/these-are-anti-indigenous-tweets-bolivias-interim-president-deleted |title=These are the anti-indigenous tweets that Bolivia's interim president deleted |date=16 November 2019 |agency=Agence France-Presse (AFP)}}</ref> and \"provocative\" by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> On [[Twitter]], \u00c1\u00f1ez called the [[Aymara people]]'s [[Willkakuti|New Year celebration]] \"satanic\" and said that \"nobody can replace God\", and has implied that indigenous people were not genuine for wearing shoes.<ref name=\"afp\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> She would later state \"I\u2019ve seen a couple of tweets that I never wrote and that we already stated were false\" and that she never made \"ill-intentioned\" comments.<ref name=\":5\" /> In the opening days of her presidency, [[Mar\u00eda Galindo]], an outspoken critic of Morales and an anarcha-feminist and psychologist, described the government of \u00c1\u00f1ez as \"anti-indigenous.\"<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |newspaper=The Guardian |date=14 November 2019}}</ref> About \u00c1\u00f1ez, she would later state that \"her hatred of the Indian is of all hatreds the most painful, because it is a hatred of herself\", referring to \u00c1\u00f1ez' own mestizo background. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/opinion/maria-galindo/2019/12/18/jeanine-usurpadora-sustituta-subalterna-240715.html|title=Jeanine: Usurper, substitute, subordinate?|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|author=Mar\u00eda  Galindo|date=18 December 2019|language=es}}</ref>\n\nAs acting president, \u00c1\u00f1ez has kept [[wiphala]], the flag of indigenous Bolivian communities, as a co-official [[flag of Bolivia]], as it had been under Morales, declaring that she was committed to the fundamental task of \"highlighting the unity [of the] plural and diverse\" nation of Bolivia.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://eju.tv/2019/11/jeanine-anez-instruye-que-junto-a-la-sagrada-tricolor-se-mantenga-la-wiphala/ |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez instruye que junto a la sagrada tricolor se mantenga la wiphala |website=eju.tv |date=12 November 2019}}</ref> In addition to the whipala, the [[patuj\u00fa]] is displayed prominently.<ref>[https://www.eldeber.com.bo/156526_colocan-la-bandera-de-la-flor-del-patuju-junto-a-la-wiphala-y-la-tricolor-en-palacio-quemado Colocan la bandera de la Flor del Patuj\u00fa junto a la wiphala y la tricolor en Palacio Quemado | EL DEBER<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The patuj\u00fa is a symbol of the Eastern indigenous peoples of Bolivia and of [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]], Bolivia's largest city. This flag was also adopted by indigenous opposition to Morales during the [[Isiboro_S%C3%A9cure_National_Park_and_Indigenous_Territory|TIPNIS]] protests.<ref>[https://radiopatuju.blogspot.com/2012/05/imagenes-por-el-tipnis-no.html Radio Patuj\u00fa 95.2 FM: IM\u00c1GENES \"POR EL TIPNIS NO\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> On 26 November 2019, she was presented with and wore a red poncho (a traditional Andean garment worn by community leaders) by representatives of the indigenous community on the inauguration of [[Rafael Quispe]] as director of the Fund for Indigenous Development.<ref>[https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20191126/anez-viste-poncho-andino-obsequiado-comunarios A\u00f1ez viste poncho andino obsequiado por comunarios | Los Tiempos<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On 28 January 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez signed a proposed bill to provide cultural recognition to the seven different identities of the country's indigenous women. After signing she stated \"This bill is a demonstration of the value of the [[pollera]] woman as the main character in the fight for the equality of indigenous, rural, migrant and mestizo women\" and that \"the principle of equality must transcend laws and transform society and create more opportunities for indigenous and rural women.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bolivia.com/actualidad/nacionales/cholas-bolivianas-patrimonio-cultural-e-inmaterial-bolivia-jeanine-anez-258189|website=www.bolivia.com|language=es|date=28 January 2020|title=Government will seek to declare the Cholas cultural heritage of Bolivia}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez was married in Santa Cruz at the age of 23 to Tadeo Ribera Bruckner, a lawyer and a former mayor of [[Trinidad, Bolivia|Trinidad]], the capital of [[Beni Department|Beni]], representing the Uni\u00f3n C\u00edvica Solidaridad (UCS) party. They had two children together, Carolina (born 1990) and Jos\u00e9 Armando (born 1995). Ribera died in [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]] on 29 January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/164289_fallece-el-exesposo-de-la-presidenta-jeanine-anez|website=El Deber|title=Ex-husband of President Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez dies|date=29 January 2020|language=es}}</ref><ref name=biografias></ref>\n\n\u00c1\u00f1ez's second husband is H\u00e9ctor Hernando Hincapi\u00e9 Carvajal, a Colombian from [[Tolima Department|Tolima]]. He is a politician in the [[Colombian Conservative Party]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=RESULTADO CORPORACI\u00d3N |url=https://elecciones.caracol.com.co/candidatos/senado/partido-conservador-colombiano |website=Caracol Radio |accessdate=14 November 2019|date=26 October 2019}}</ref> Hincapi\u00e9 ran, unsuccessfully, for a seat in the Colombian Senate in 2018, and as a member of the Tolima regional assembly and House of Representatives in 2010 and 2014 respectively. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lafm.com.co/internacional/el-colombiano-que-se-robo-el-corazon-de-la-presidenta-e-de-bolivia|title=The Colombian that stole he heart of the President of Bolivia|language=es|website=www.lafm.com.co|date=13 November 2019}}</ref> Until recently, they travelled between Bolivia and Colombia to see one another, although this has become easier since failure to win a seat in 2018.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=https://www.opinion.com.bo/content/print/jeanine-anez-chavez-mujer-dirige-bolivia-afronta-desafios/20191122104634737958|website=www.opinion.com.bo|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, the woman who heads Bolivia and faces challenges|language=es|date=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links\n|wikt=no|commonscat=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez|n=no|q=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez|s=no|author=no|b=no|v=no\n|voy=no|d=Q16581287|m=no|mw=no|species=no|species_author=no\n}}\n*[http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/spip.php?page=parlamentario&id_parlamentario=159 Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez]\n*[https://www.cidob.org/biografias_lideres_politicos/america_del_sur/bolivia/jeanine_anez_chavez Biography by CIDOB] \n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Evo Morales]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Bolivia]]|order=Interim|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of Bolivia}}\n{{Heads of State of the South America}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anez, Jeanine}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Bolivian politicians]]\n[[Category:Bolivian Christians]]\n[[Category:Female heads of government]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:People from Beni Department]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Senate of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Women presidents]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Interim President of Bolivia since 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{spanish name|[[\u00c1\u00f1ez]]|[[Ch\u00e1vez (surname)|Ch\u00e1vez]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez\n| image               = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez.jpg\n| caption             = \u00c1\u00f1ez in 2016\n| order = 66th \n| office              = President of Bolivia\n| term_start          = 12 November 2019\n| term_end            = \n| vicepresident       = <!-- ''None'' -->\n| predecessor         = [[Evo Morales]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[President pro tempore of the Community of Latin American and Caribbean States|President pro tempore of CELAC]]\n| term_start1         = 12 November 2019\n| term_end1           = 8 January 2020{{Efn|CELAC ''pro tempore'' presidency is assigned to countries and it automatically passes to the next president after elections. After the [[2019 Bolivian political crisis]], Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez would become ''pro tempore'' president of CELAC. However, Mexico called for a new CELAC summit on its own. Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez denounced that the summit should be called for by Bolivia. As the result of this dispute, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez did not attend to the CELAC summit and did not formally pass the ''pro tempore'' presidency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elimparcial.com/mundo/Bolivia-no-asistira-al-cambio-de-presidencia-de-la-Celac-por-roces-con-Mexico-20191223-0073.html|title=Bolivia no asistir\u00e1 al cambio de presidencia de la Celac por roces con M\u00e9xico|work=El Imparcial|date=23 December 2019|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/es/mundo/bolivia-rechaza-que-m%C3%A9xico-convocara-a-reuni%C3%B3n-de-la-celac-sin-consultarle-previamente/1682226|title=Bolivia rechaza que M\u00e9xico convocara a reuni\u00f3n de la Celac sin consultarle previamente|work=Anadolu Agency|first=Sant\u0131ago|last=Serna Duque|date=24 December 2020|access-date=11 April 2020|language=es}}</ref>}}\n| predecessor1        = [[Evo Morales]]\n| successor1          = [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]]\n| office2             = [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly|Senator]] for [[Beni Department|Beni]]\n| term_start2         = 22 January 2010\n| term_end2           = 12 November 2019\n| office3             = [[Bolivian Constituent Assembly of 2006\u201307|Member of the Constituent Assembly]]\n| term_start3         = 6 August 2006\n| term_end3           = 6 August 2007\n| birth_name          = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1967|8|13}}\n| birth_place         = [[San Joaqu\u00edn, Bolivia|San Joaqu\u00edn]], [[Beni Department|Beni]], Bolivia\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| spouse              = Tadeo Ribera Bruckner (1990-?), H\u00e9ctor Hernando Hincapi\u00e9 Carvajal (?-present)\n| party               = [[Democrat Social Movement]] [[Juntos (Bolivian political party)|Juntos]]\n| signature           = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez signature.svg\n}}\n\n'''Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez'''<ref>{{citation |title=Entrevista Jeanine A\u00f1ez Chavez |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v185AWdeDE0 |language=en |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> ({{IPA-es|\u025f\u029da\u02c8nine \u02c8a\u0272es}}; born 13 August 1967)<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://web.senado.gob.bo/senadoras-es/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-ch%C3%A1vez |title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |date=16 October 2015 |website=C\u00e1mara de Senadores |language=es |accessdate=11 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111145518/https://web.senado.gob.bo/senadoras-es/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-ch%C3%A1vez |archivedate=11 November 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> is a Bolivian politician and lawyer currently serving as the Interim [[President of Bolivia]] since November 2019, after the [[Evo Morales government resignation|resignation of the government of Evo Morales]]. Her interim term will end when [[2020 Bolivian general election|new elections]] take place on an as yet undetermined date in 2020.\n\nShe was previously an opposition [[Senate of Bolivia|senator]] from the northeastern [[Departments of Bolivia|department]] of [[Beni, Bolivia|Beni]], belonging to the center-right [[Democrat Social Movement]]. Her political position has been described by journalists as [[right-wing]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization |first=Dan |last=Collyns |date=14 November 2019 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/jeanine-anez-declares-bolivia-interim-president-191112233635201.html |title=Jeanine Anez declares herself Bolivia interim president |date=12 November 2019 |website=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> and anti-[[Evo Morales|Morales]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cronista.com/internacionales/Bolivia-quien-es-Jeanine-Anez-Chavez-la-mujer-que-puede-quedar-al-mando-de-la-transicion-20191110-0019.html |title=Bolivia: qui\u00e9n es Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, la mujer que puede quedar al mando de la transici\u00f3n |date=11 November 2019 |website=El Cronista |trans-title=Bolivia: who is Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, the woman who can be in charge of the transition |access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/after-morales-resignation-a-question-for-bolivia-was-this-the-democratic-will-or-a-coup/2019/11/11/ff36ce9a-040c-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html |title=After Morales' resignation, a question for Bolivia: Was this the democratic will, or a coup? |last=Faiola |first=Anthony |date= |website=[[The Washington Post]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111194058/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/after-morales-resignation-a-question-for-bolivia-was-this-the-democratic-will-or-a-coup/2019/11/11/ff36ce9a-040c-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html|archive-date=2019-11-11|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50399640 |title=Bolivian senator assumes interim presidency |last= |first= |date=13 November 2019 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |access-date=13 November 2019 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nJeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez was born in the small Amazonian town of [[San Joaqu\u00edn, Bolivia|San Joaqu\u00edn]] in the [[Department of Beni]], Bolivia, on 13 August 1967. She was the youngest of seven children born to two teachers.<ref name=biografias>{{cite web|url=http://library.fes.de/pdf-files/bueros/bolivien/10697.pdf|language=es|title=BIOGRAF\u00cdAS Historias de Vida en la Asamblea Legislativa Plurinacional|year=2013|page=416\u2013418}}</ref> Her background has been described as poor [[mestiza]] and lower-middle-class.<ref name=\"\u201ceconomist\u201d\">{{cite news|author=|title= Bolivia after the ouster of Evo Morales, a leftist strongman|url= https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/03/07/bolivia-after-the-ouster-of-evo-morales-a-leftist-strongman|work=[[The Economist]]|date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=CIDOB>{{cite web|url=https://www.cidob.org/biografias_lideres_politicos/america_del_sur/bolivia/jeanine_anez_chavez|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |website=www.cidob.org|language=es|date=13 December 2019}}</ref> During this time, San Joaqu\u00edn lacked proper roads, was dependent on diesel generators for power and had a water supply that was rationed. Recalling her childhood, she says \"We grew up with many limitations, with many needs but nevertheless I had a beautiful childhood, very free.\" <ref name=biografias></ref>\n\nShe attended the local school, a girls school that her mother would later become director of. At age seventeen, she achieved her baccalaureate and left San Joaqu\u00edn to pursue an education in La Paz, first at the Bolivian Institute and then at the Abraham Lincoln Institute. At this time, she studied to become a secretary.<ref name=biografias></ref> She continued to [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]] where she took further studies as a secretary, including computing and some English. <ref name=biografias></ref> After getting married at aged 23, she moved to [[Trinidad, Bolivia]], where she enrolled at the Autonomous University of the Beni Jos\u00e9 Ballivi\u00e1n and obtained a graduate degree in law and legal sciences.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=biografias></ref>\n\n==Career==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez passed the bar in 1991.<ref name=\":2\" /> She was formerly a media presenter<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/mundo/perfil-de-jeanine-anez-nueva-presidenta-interina-de-bolivia-432904 |title=\u00bfQui\u00e9n es Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez, la nueva presidenta interina de Bolivia? |first=Casa Editorial El |last=Tiempo |date=13 November 2019 |location=Colombia |language=es |website=[[ElTiempo.com]]}}</ref> and director at Totalvisi\u00f3n.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Constituent Assembly (2006\u20132008)===\nBetween 2006 and 2008, she served as a constituent assemblywoman for the drafting of the new constitutional charter, also working as part of the Judiciary.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Senate (2010\u20132019)===\nIn 2010, she was elected to the [[Bolivian Senate|Senate]] as a member of the party [[Plan Progress for Bolivia \u2013 National Convergence|Plan Progress for Bolivia-National Convergence]] (P.P.B - C.N), representing the Department of Beni in the National Assembly.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/spip.php?page=parlamentario&id_parlamentario=159 |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |date= |access-date=21 April 2014 |publisher=vicepresidencia.gob.bo |language=es |format= |quote= }}</ref> She ran for governor of Beni in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Jeanine-Anez-precandidata-gobernacion-Beni_0_1697830274.html |title=La senadora Jeanine A\u00f1ez surge como primera precandidata opositora a la gobernaci\u00f3n de Beni; el MSM apunta a una tercera opci\u00f3n |last=Corz |first=Carlos |date=1 October 2012 |website=La Raz\u00f3n |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she spoke out against the approval of a finance bill by the Morales' government for the construction of the Villa Tunari-San Ignacio de Moxos highway. She claimed that it was not approved with due consideration for the native peoples and institutions of the region saying that \"indigenous people's right was violated\", a sentiment echoed by leader of the natives of the Isiboro S\u00e9cure National Park Indigenous Territory (TIPNIS), Adolfo Moye who said it was enacted \"without considering the serious impact on the ecosystem and natural reserves of the region.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20110511/senadora-cuestiona-financiamiento-carretera-cochabamba-beni|title=Senator questions financing of Cochabamba-Beni highway|language=es|date=11 May 2011|website=www.losttiempos.com|}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, A\u00f1ez and fellow party legislator Adri\u00e1n Oliva presented a report to the Human Rights Commission of the Chamber of Deputies of Uruguay in an effort to publicise human rights violations in Bolivia. According to the UN refugee office, UNHCR, there were around 600 Bolivian exiles or refugees, a hundred political prisoners and at least 15 cases of torture at this time. The UN High Commissioner for Human Rights stated that there was a \"crisis in the administration of justice\" in Bolivia. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20120523/presentan-informe-uruguay|website=www.lostiempos.com|date=23 May 2012|language=es|title=Report presented in Uruguay}}</ref> Also in 2012, A\u00f1ez was selected as a Bolivian representative to the Amazonian Parliament. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20120316/senado-designo-representantes-parlamentos-internacionales|website=www.lostiempos.com|date=16 March 2012|language=es|title=Senate designates representatives to international parliaments.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, there were a series of nationwide strikes and protests against the MAS government concerning the reduction of seats in the Chamber of Deputies for the areas of [[Department of Beni|Beni]], [[Potos\u00ed department|Potos\u00ed]] and [[Department of Chuquisaca|Chuquisaca]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2013/10/2/beni-potosi-inician-paro-contra-escanos-2058.html|date=2 October 2013|title=Beni and Potosi begin strike against seats}}</ref>As Senator of Beni, Jeanine A\u00f1ez joined picket lines and was among six legistlators and a dozen indigenous representatives of [[CONAMAQ]] that went on hunger strike in protest to the legistlation being passed by the MAS majority in both chambers. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2013/10/4/conflicto-escanos-agrava-tres-piquetes-huelguistas-2255.html|title=Conflict over seats worsens, there are three pickets of strikers|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=4 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2013/10/4/opositores-bolivianos-inician-huelga-hambre-contra-reduccion-escanos-2289.html|title=Bolivian opposition members start hunger strike against reduction of seats|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=4 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, \u00c1\u00f1ez made complaints about the lack of financial transparency from the government. Requests for reports as part of opposition legislators ability to audit the activities of the state were delayed and in 499 out of 1979 cases for the 2013-14 period received no response. The authorities, according to the regulations of the Chamber of Deputies, were permitted 10 business days to respond to a request for a report, and in the Senate, 15 days. If the request for a written report is not answered, an injunction can be issued to give a time limit of 48 hours. \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that in many cases, these injunctions were ignored and there was a \"denial of information\". Many of the projects had multi-million budgets with several interested parties for whom access is even more restricted.  \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that in many cases which do receive replies \"they are responses without response\". Responses included two sheets of photocopies, material unrelated to the request or boxes full of documents which do \"not intend to clarify the doubts, but to hinder the work of the legislators.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2014/2/9/denuncian-trabas-acceso-informacion-para-fiscalizar-13544.html|title=They denounce obstacles in access to information for auditing|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=8 February 2014}}</ref> In 2019-2020, many of these cases are under investigation. <ref name=corruption>{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/america-latina/2019/12/22/bolivia-se-suman-denuncias-por-corrupcion-fraude-y-malos-manejos-de-empresas-publicas-durante-los-anos-de-evo-morales/|title=Bolivia: Allegations of corruption, fraud and mismanagement of public companies during the years of Evo Morales accumulate|language=es|website=Infobae|date=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she was one of three Senators to make a complaint against Gisela L\u00f3pez, then  Minister for Public Works. This involved the management of the state-owned Bolivia TV and undocumented expenditure of more than $40 million. The case had already been the target of more than 30 obstructed complaints by a former minister. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/52748_piden-informe-a-lopez-sobre-millonario-desembolso|website=www.eldeber.com.bo|date=14 April 2018|language=es|title=Report requested from Lopez over multi-million disbursement}}</ref> In 2019, this would become the centre of the Neurona case in which L\u00f3pez and 22 others \"are suspected of the alleged crimes of improper use of influence, negotiations incompatible with the exercise of public functions, breach of duties, contracts harmful to the State and uneconomic conduct\". <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/158496_gobierno-acusa-a-exministra-lopez-por-corrupcion-e-inicia-una-querella|date=2 December 2019|title=Government accuse exminister Lopez of corruption and begin lawsuit|language=es|website=www.eldeber.com.bo}}</ref> Also in 2018, she presented a bill to the Senate to combat \"[[revenge porn|sexual blackmail]]\" stating \"Social networks lend themselves to everything, we have seen that the viralization of intimate videos has become an extortion mechanism , and on some occasions it is to blackmail psychologically and economically, so the intention is to penalize and specifically typify it\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/64136_sexo-chantaje-el-proyecto-de-ley-que-quiere-penalizar-difusion-de-videos-intimos|title=Sexual blackmail: The bill that wants to penalise the spread of intimate videos|date=25 October 2018|language=es|website=www.eldeber.com.bo}}</ref> In the wake of her becoming president, anti-\u00c1\u00f1ez posters spread a pornographic video with her as the alleged protagonist on social media which she denied and called a \"vile attack\". <ref name=porno>{{cite web|url=https://politico.mx/minuta-politica/internacional/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-rechaza-supuesto-video-sexual-es-un-ataque-vil/|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez denies supposed sexual video|date=20 November 2019|language=es|website=www.politico.mx}}</ref>\n\nBy 2019, she was elected as the second vice president of the Senate, and her alternate was Franklin Valdivia Leigue.<ref name=\":0\" /> This role placed her fifth in the [[President of Bolivia#Current line of succession|line of succession to the presidency]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Before the presidential elections in 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez had questioned the reliability of opinion polls, based on unclear methods and inconsistent results.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/8/19/piden-informe-escrito-al-tse-por-la-encuestadora-viaciencia-228016.html |title=Piden informe escrito al TSE por la encuestadora ViaCiencia |last= |first= |date= |website=Diario Pagina Siete |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===<span id=\"Interim president of Bolivia (2019\u2013present)\"></span>Interim President of Bolivia (2019\u2013present)===\n\n====Initial protest period====\n\nOn 10 November, Morales and his vice president, [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]], [[Evo Morales government resignation|resigned from office]] after pressure from political opponents and civic groups and losing support from former political allies, the police and the [[Armed Forces of Bolivia|military]];<ref name=\"Londo\u00f1o\">Ernesto Londo\u00f1o, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/evo-morales-bolivia.html Bolivian Leader Evo Morales Steps Down], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (10 November 2019).</ref>. This was followed by the resignation of [[Adriana Salvatierra Arriaza]], the president of the [[Bolivian Senate]], who was next in the constitutional line of succession<ref name=\"GuerreroAndone\">Kay Guerrero & Dakin Andone, [https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/10/americas/bolivia-new-election-audit/index.html Bolivian President Evo Morales steps down following accusations of election fraud], CNN (10 November 2019).</ref>\u2014leading to a situation where all constitutional successors were exhausted. The role of acting President of the Senate would normally fall to the vice-president of the Senate, Rub\u00e9n Medinaceli, but since he also had resigned, the position fell to A\u00f1ez as second vice-president of the Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/76278_salvatierra-asume-pide-que-haya-mas-inclusion-de-mujeres-y-jovenes|title=Salvatierra sworn in; Calls for more inclusion of women and young people|website=El Deber|date=18 January 2019|language=es|author=Jes\u00fas Alanoca Paco}}</ref> Thus A\u00f1ez became the highest-ranking official in the line of succession to the presidency of Bolivia and stated an acceptance to fill the role if needed. The succession was not automatic, however, as the Legislative Assembly would need to hold emergency meetings to accept the abdications of the President and Vice-President and determine who was next in line due to the lack of constitutional guidance.<ref name=\"vicepresidente1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-50370125 |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez en proceso de ratificaci\u00f3n tras renuncia del Presidente, Vicepresidente, Presidente del Senado y Presidente de la C\u00e1mara de Diputados de Bolivia |editor=BBC News Mundo |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez could not attend an emergency assembly until the day after Morales' resignation, as she was in Beni and there were no Sunday flights from there to the capital of [[La Paz]].<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nOn 11 November, A\u00f1ez arrived at [[El Alto International Airport|La Paz-El Alto airport]] and was taken in a military helicopter to a nearby Air Force base. From there, she traveled to the Bolivian Senate. At 4pm, an emergency vote took place to formally accept the resignations of the previous day. <ref name=\"Huff-Post\">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.fr/entry/apres-la-demission-devo-morales-les-insoumis-denoncent-un-coup-detat_fr_5dc91fa7e4b00927b236112e |title=Apr\u00e8s la d\u00e9mission d'Evo Morales, les insoumis d\u00e9noncent un \"coup d'\u00c9tat\" |date=11 November 2019 |website=Le Huffington Post}}</ref> Morales' MAS party, which still held a majority in the upper chamber, boycotted this vote. Constitutional experts Paul Coca and Israel Alanoca stated that, while the normal quorum would have been desirable for purpose of quelling accusations of a coup d'etat, there was no specific regulation to deal with the resignation of leaders and an emergency vote on the grounds of human rights concerns and establishing social peace would be legally valid.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/11/si-no-hay-quorum-en-la-alp-se-puede-apelar-al-voto-de-urgencia-237110.html|title=If there is no quorum in the ALP, an emergency vote can be applied|language=es|date=11 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn the evening of 12 November, per article 169 of the [[Constitution of Bolivia]], \u00c1\u00f1ez was declared acting [[president of Bolivia]] in front of a session of the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldeber.com.bo/156411_anez-asume-la-presidencia-de-bolivia-ante-vacancia-y-aplicando-la-sucesion-constitucional|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez asume la Presidencia de Bolivia ante vacancia y aplicando la sucesi\u00f3n constitucional|trans-title=\u00c1\u00f1ez assumes the Presidency of Bolivia due to vacancy and applying the constitutional succession|website=El Deber|language=es|access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> This vote was also boycotted by MAS, who dubbed the vote \"illegal\". <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/12/anez-asume-la-presidencia-para-pacificar-el-pais-237195.html|title=Anez assumes the presidency to pacify the country|language=es|date=12 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/12/evo-morales-arrives-mexico-bolivia-power-vacuum |title=Bolivia: Jeanine A\u00f1ez claims presidency after ousting of Evo Morales |location=La Paz |first1=Jo |last1=Tuckman |first2=Dan |last2=Collyns |date=13 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 November 2019 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 }}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/13/americas/bolivia-political-unrest-intl-hnk/index.html |title=Bolivian senator declares herself acting president -- but she may be on shaky ground |first1=Joshua |last1=Berlinger |first2=Gustavo |last2=Vald\u00e9s |website=CNN |access-date=13 November 2019 }}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez obtained the favorable vote of the remaining parties, a third part of the parliament. <ref>{{cite news |title=La senadora Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez se proclama presidenta de Bolivia sin qu\u00f3rum en el Parlamento |url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/11/12/america/1573566340_453048.html |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=13 November 2019 |accessdate=13 November 2019|issn=1134-6582|language=es|first=Francesco|last=Manetto}}</ref> The move was later upheld by the [[Plurinational Constitutional Court]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/156414_tcp-avala-sucesion-constitucional-en-la-presidencia|title=TCP avala sucesi\u00f3n constitucional en la Presidencia |trans-title=TCP uphelds constitutional succession in the Presidency |website=El Deber |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019 }}</ref> \n\nOn 13 November Salvatierra contended that her resignation was not valid since it had not been accepted by the Senate, and therefore, \u00c1\u00f1ez should not be able to assume the Presidency via becoming President of the Senate.<ref name=\"dispute\">{{cite news |title=Presidenta de Senado boliviano denuncia presi\u00f3n a dirigentes |url=https://www.telesurtv.net/news/bolivia-presidenta-senado-denuncia-presion-dirigentes-20191113-0021.html |accessdate=14 November 2019 |work=www.telesurtv.net |agency=teleSUR |date=13 November 2019 |language=es}}</ref> This prompted a further session on the Senate on 14 November, this time with the involvement of MAS, that reaffirmed Salvatierra's resignation more formally and elected M\u00f3nica Eva Copa from the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]] as the new president.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atb.com.bo/pol%C3%ADtica/eva-copa-es-la-nueva-presidenta-del-senado|language=es|title=Eva Copa is the new president of the Senate|date=15 November 2019|website=www.atb.com.bo}}</ref>\n\nAmid a pledge to \"rebuild democracy\", A\u00f1ez unveiled her new [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]]. Her senior ministers included prominent businesspeople from [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]]. The first eleven members of her cabinet did not include any members of the [[indigenous peoples in Bolivia]], which ''[[The Guardian]]'' described as a sign that she did \"not intend to reach across the country's deep political and ethnic divide\". Later appointments of the remaining positions would include two indigenous members. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Anez-completa-gabinete-ministra-Alto_0_3257674272.html|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez posesiona cinco nuevos ministros; Yujra besa la wiphala y va por di\u00e1logo con El Alto - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/ministros-posesion-bolivia-anez_0_3260074003.html|title=A\u00f1ez posesiona a Carlos Huallpa en Miner\u00eda y a Virginia Patty Torres en Educaci\u00f3n - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref> While Morales's first cabinet was majority indigenous (14 out of 16 positions), this number steadily decreased since 2009 and by 2017 contained only three indigenous members. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2006/01/23/actualidad/1137970802_850215.html|title=Morales toma juramento a los 16 ministros que integran el \"nuevo Gabinete del pueblo\"|work=El Pais|language=es|accessdate=13 April 2020|date=23 January 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/especial01/2017/1/22/gabinete-tuvo-rostros-indigenas-pero-pocos-ministros-poder-124588.html|title=Gabinete tuvo rostros ind\u00edgenas, pero pocos ministros con poder - Diario Pagina Siete|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Decree 4078 and repercussions ====\n\nOn 15 November, amid [[2019 Bolivian protests|continuing protests]], violence and [[2019 shortages in Bolivia|shortages]] in several main cities, A\u00f1ez issued Decree 4078 to enlist the police and army to pacify the country. Article 3 of the decree reads \"The personnel of the Armed Forces who participate in operations to restore internal order and public stability will be exempt from criminal liability when, in compliance with their constitutional functions, they acted in legitimate defense or state of necessity, in observance of the principles of legality, absolute necessity and proportionality.\u201d <ref name=HRO>{{cite web|url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/11/17/america/1574014107_965320.html|website=El Pais|language=es|date=17 November 2019|title=Alarm in Bolivia for impunity for the military who repress the protests|author=Francesco Manetto}}</ref> The same day, there was a confrontation close to [[Sacaba]] with pro-Morales supporters, mainly coca growers, while they were attempting to cross a bridge on which a police cordon has been set up. 9 people were killed and 17 injured, 11 of which showing wounds from projectiles. <ref name=sacaba>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/17/gobierno-niega-uso-de-armas-en-sacaba-suman-los-muertos-237622.html|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|date=17 November 2019|title=Government deny use of arms in Sacaba. The dead increase.}}</ref> Protesters say that they were fired upon without warning while the police report states that 201 people were involved in \"violent acts\" and 10 men were arrested for the \"crimes of armed uprising, possession and carrying of firearms, and manufacture and trade of explosive and suffocating substances\". Several human rights groups, including the [[Inter-American Commission on Human Rights|IACHR]], [[Amnesty International]], [[Human Rights Watch]] and the UN Human Rights Commission, called for the immediate revocation of Decree 4078.<ref name=HRO></ref> Amnesty International described it as a \"carte blanche\" for human rights abuses. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2019/11/bolivia-derogar-norma-impunidad-fuerzas-armadas/|date=18 November 2019|title=Bolivia: Jeanine A\u00f1ez must immediately repeal decree giving impunity to Armed Forces personnel|author=Amnesty International}}</ref> Government sources claimed that the bullets were not of the type used by the police while army garrison commander Alfredo Cu\u00e9llar stated that they were under no orders to shoot and would not be authorised to use lethal force in those circumstances. <ref name=sacaba></ref>.\n\nOn 28 November, the controversial decree was repealed by President A\u00f1ez, but not before a further massacre occurred in the [[Senkata]] district of [[El Alto]] in which another 9 people were killed and more injured.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/29/anez-abroga-polemico-decreto-luego-de-la-pacificacion-del-pais-238933.html|language=es|title=A\u00f1ez abrogates controversial decree in order to pacify country|date=29 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=IACHR></ref> The Senkata gas refinery plant had been attacked in previous days and a military escort was provided for a convoy of fuel trucks needed to relieve shortages in the cities of El Alto and LA Paz. While en route, a violent clash occurred.<ref name=IACHR></ref>The official government response was, again, that they had not fired shots and that they had been under attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20191121/fiscalia-confirma-ocho-fallecidos-por-enfrentamientos-en-senkata|title=Prosecutors office confirm 8 deaths due to clash in Senkata|date=21 November 2019|website=El Alteno|language=es}}</ref> Concerning the deaths, President \u00c1\u00f1ez said \"We deeply regret the deaths of our brothers in El Alto, it hurts us because we are a government of peace\" and called for dialogue to listen to the demands of the protesters. In addition, she asked international organizations and the church to accompany this process in order to stop the violence. \"Let's unite to reconcile, to build the Bolivia for which we are all fighting and so that one Bolivian is never above the other,\" said \u00c1\u00f1ez.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/157419_la-presidenta-jeanine-anez-lamenta-las-muertes-de-el-alto-y-pide-dialogo-para-pacificar-el-pais|website=El Deber|date=December 2019|language=es|title=President Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez mourns the deaths of El Alto and calls for dialogue to pacify the country}}</ref>\n\nOn invitation by the state, the IACHR conducted an investigation into the deaths and injuries that occurred during this period of violence. On 10 December they published their preliminary observations, based on interviews conducted with eyewitnesses. The stated that \"it is appropriate to describe these events as massacres, given the number of people who lost their lives in the same way and at the same time and place, and because the acts in question were committed against a specific group of people. Furthermore, the patterns of injuries that have been recorded point strongly to extrajudicial killing practices.\"<ref name=IACHR>{{cite web|url=http://www.oas.org/en/iachr/media_center/PReleases/2019/321.asp|date=10 December 2019|website=www.oas.org|title=IACHR Preliminary Findings}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/12/10/cidh-califica-hechos-de-sacaba-senakta-de-masacre-pide-investigacion-internacional-240095.html|date=10 December 2019|language=es|title=IACHR calls acts at Sacaba and Senkata massacres and asks for international investigation|website=P\u00e1gina Siete}}</ref> In ongoing talks with families of victims, proposed compensation relating to Decree 4100 includes 100000 Bolivianos ($15000) for families of those killed and from 12500 to 50000 Bolivianos for those injured, the amount depending on severity. By request of the families, the amount is to be given in humanitarian aid (including 12 months of food) rather than a single payment. It also allows the victims to seek help from international organisations. A final agreement has not been reached as there is general mistrust in the government to follow through on their promises. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2020/2/6/victimas-de-senkata-gobierno-negocian-acuerdo-de-seis-puntos-245777.html|date=6 February 2020|title=Victims of Senkata and government negotiate agreement on 6 points.|language=es|website=P\u00e1gina Siete}}</ref>\n\nAfter taking office, the governments of [[Canada]], [[Brazil]], the [[European Union]], [[Russia]] and the [[United States]] recognized \u00c1\u00f1ez as the acting president of Bolivia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Canada will 'support' Bolivian opposition government |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/bolivia-canada-anez-government-1.5360138 |work=CBC News |date=14 November 2019}}</ref>{{when|date=December 2019}}<!-- the timing of this recognition should be included in the prose -->\n\n====Later activity====\n\nEarly on, \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that Morales would not be permitted to run in an upcoming election for a fourth term, should he return to Bolivia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-bolivias-interim-leader-says-evo-morales-cant-run-in-new-election/ |title=Bolivia's interim leader says Evo Morales can't run in new election |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bolivia-interim-president-bars-morales-from-new-elections/a-51259511 |title=Bolivia: Interim president bars Morales from new elections |date=15 November 2019  |website=www.dw.com |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> This was verified by the Constitutional Court, who reversed their decision to overturn the [[2016 Bolivian constitutional referendum]] which permitted all public figures to have an unlimited number of terms. This also prevented the vice-president from running for a fourth term. The decision was further ratified on 23 November when a bill was first approved by the Senate and then later in the day by the lower house, both of which are dominated by Morales' Movement Toward Socialism party.<ref name=bills>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bolivian-election-lawmakers-approve-new-elections-with-rules-barring-ex-president-evo-morales-from-running/|title=Bolivian lawmakers approve new election rules barring ex-President Morales from running|date=23 November 2019|website=cbsnews}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 November, \u00c1\u00f1ez rejected a bill presented by Morales' party that would have prevented the ousted president, and all others in his party, from being tried for alleged crimes committed during the exercise of their functions to date. \"With respect to approving this bill in favor of those who have committed crimes and who now seek impunity, my decision is clear and firm: I will not promulgate this law,\" \u00c1\u00f1ez said. The bill did not have full support within MAS with one member of the Chamber of Deputies stating \"I ask the president [Morales] to reflect and really listen to the Bolivian people,\" and claimed that for years the \"oppressed wing\" of MAS suffered discrimination from within the party.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/12/28/ortiz-pide-morales-reflexionar-pensar-en-el-pueblo-241794.html|title=Ortiz asks Morales to reflect and think about the people.|date=28 December 2019|language=es|website=www.paginasiete.bo}}</ref>\n\nSince then, the \u00c1\u00f1ez government has led numerous investigations and charges of corruption against members of previous administration and those linked to them. The majority involve embezzlement or misappropriation of state owned companies and awarding of state contracts where there was a conflict of interest. These include Entel, a state communications company that saw losses of $250 million and was described as the \"petty cash\" of MAS, the Neurona case, the Bolivian Highway Administrator that saw $310 million dollars disappear into uncompleted or unobserved projects, investments in state owned petroleum projects that were not developed and the multimillion diversion of money from the Indigenous Fund. All of the previous cases involved government ministers and several were subject to complaints from members of the opposition in the past.<ref name=corrupcion></ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/ciudad/20171021/opositores-afirman-que-el-mas-se-dana-en-corrupcion|website=www.elalteno.com|language=es|date=22 October 2017|title=Opposition agree that MAS damages itself through corruption}}</ref> Corruption watchdogs have observed that corruption was common under the MAS government and continues to be a problem in the interim government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20190130/informe-de-corrupcion-pone-al-pais-nivel-de-un-regimen-autoritario|website=www.elalteno.com|language=es|title=Corruption report puts the country at the level of an authoritarian regime|date=30 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=casos>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20200108/gobierno-investiga-592-exautoridades-de-la-gestion-de-morales-y-familiares-por|website=www.elalteno.com.bo|date=8 January 2020|language=es|title=Government investigates 592 ex-authorities of the Morales era}}</ref> The level of prosecutions have led to accusations of political persecution from human rights groups.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/2/29/cuatro-organismos-internacionales-se-pronunciaron-advirtiendo-violacion-derechos-en-bolivia-248178.html|website=www.paginasiete.bo|title=Four human rights organisations spoke out against human rights violations in Bolivia|language=es|date=29 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=casos></ref> Similar observations were also made during the Morales era.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2016/country-chapters/bolivia|website=www.hrw.org|title=2016 Human Rights Report (Bolivia)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2019/country-chapters/bolivia|website=www.hrw.org|title=2019 Human Rights Report (Bolivia)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/andes-to-the-amazon/2017/apr/08/top-bolivian-ngo-faces-forced-eviction|website=www.guardian.com|title=Top Bolivian NGO faces forced eviction|date=8 April 2018}}</ref> In response to prosecutions, the government claim that \"It must be remembered that the current Judicial Branch, be it the Supreme Court of Justice, the Constitutional Court, the Council of the Magistracy, all have been appointed by MAS and in other cases have been preselected by MAS.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/3/8/reportaje-de-washington-post-ve-ola-de-persecucion-en-bolivia-248951.html|title=Washington Post see wave of persecution in Bolivia.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/04/29/bolivia-dozens-judges-arbitrarily-dismissed|website=www.hrw.org|title=Bolivia: Dozens of judges arbitrarily dismissed|date=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Straits Times]], the new interim government of president Jeanine A\u00f1ez has \"denounced foreign influence in the country since taking power, naming Colombians, Peruvians, Cubans and Venezuelans at different times... blaming foreigners for provoking violent clashes during post-election violence.\"<ref name=GAT>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/americas/bolivia-unveils-anti-terror-unit-to-fight-threatening-foreign-groups |title=Bolivia unveils anti-terror unit to fight 'threatening' foreign groups |date=4 December 2019 |website=The Straits Times}}</ref> Bolivia has had long-standing problems with foreign groups involved in organised crime, largely the drug trade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20171025/denuncian-presencia-de-narcotraficantes-colombianos-peruanos-y-brasilenos-en-el|title=They denounce presence of Colombian, Peruvian and Brazilian drug traffickers in Beni|language=es|date=25 October 2017|website=www.elalteno.com.bo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20180523/policia-desbarata-banda-de-colombianos-vinculada-al-prestamo-gota-gota|date=23 May 2018|title=Police disrupt Colombian gang linked to the 'drop by drop' loan|language=es|website=www.elalteno.com.bo}}</ref> Police arrested an Argentine national and fugitive since 2017, 44-year-old Facundo Morales Schoenfeld, in the eastern province of Santa Cruz. He was previously a member of the [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia]] (FARC) and was participating among the protesters in [[Yapacan\u00ed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eltiempo.com/justicia/conflicto-y-narcotrafico/en-bolivia-fue-capturado-alias-camilo-exguerrillero-de-las-farc-433296|website=www.eltiempo.com|language=es|date=14 November 2019|title=Who is the 'Argentine', ex-Farc captured after protests in Bolivia?}}</ref> Around the same time, four Cubans were discovered in El Alto with 90000 Bs ($13000) contained in two backpacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/156665_la-policia-investiga-y-detiene-a-nueve-subditos-extranjeros|date=15 November 2019|title=Police investigate and detain 9 foreign subjects|language=es}}</ref> Venezuelan migrants, many fleeing the current unrest in their country, had been subject to accusations of \"political activity\" and involvement in criminal activities under the Morales government, with human rights groups expressing concern about persecution of Venezuelans in Bolivia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20190403/canciller-advierte-que-venezolanos-no-pueden-hacer-politica-en-el-pais|title=Chancellor warns that Venezuelans cannot do politics in Bolivia|language=es|date=4 March 2019|website=www.elalteno.com.bo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Amnesty International demands that Bolivia stop the persecution and expulsion of Venezuelans|language=es|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20190328/amnistia-internacional-exige-bolivia-que-pare-la-persecucion-y-expulsion-de|website=www.elalteno.com.bo}}</ref> While police and interim government ministers have cited involvement of armed and politically aligned Venezuelans in pro-Morales protests<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/21/hay-16-carreteras-bloqueadas-amenazan-con-cerrar-aeropuerto-238015.html|title=16 roads are blocked and threaten to close airport|language=es|date=21 November 2019|website=www.paginasiete.bo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/16/detienen-venezolanos-con-armas-en-beni-continuan-los-ataques-terroristas-237545.html|title=9 Venezuelans detained with weapons in Beni and terrorist attacks continue|language=es|date=16 November 2019}}</ref>, they have also granted amnesty to Venezuelan refugees, extended permanence and transit of Venezualan citizens and approved a resolution to help Venezuelan children and adolescents. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/2/12/el-gobierno-otorgo-refugio-54-venezolanos-246424.html|title=The government granted refuge to 54 Venezuelans|date=12 February 2020|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/2/3/bolivia-legalizara-permanencia-transito-de-ciudadanos-venezolanos-245466.html|title=Bolivia will legalise permanence and transit of Venezuelan citizenz|date=3 February 2020|language=es|website=www.paginasiete.bo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2020/1/30/aprueban-resolucion-que-favorece-ninos-venezolanos-245030.html|title=Resolution approved which favours Venezuelan children}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 November, 700 Cuban doctors were expelled from Bolivia. The Cuban doctor program had been a subject of controversy in Bolivia in previous years with the Bolivian medical workers union (FESIMRAS) complaining that Cubans needed only a simple photocopy to practice medicine whereas the requirements for Bolivians were much more stringent and many medical professionals were unemployed.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2019/5/23/medicos-cubanos-pueden-ejercer-en-bolivia-solo-con-fotocopia-simple-denuncia-fesimras-218913.html|title=Cuban doctors can practice in Bolivia with only a simple photocopy, FESIMRAS denounce|language=es|date=23 May 2019|website=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20190316/denuncian-que-el-estado-gasta-bs-14-mil-al-mes-por-cada-medico-cubano|title=They denounce that the state wastes 14000 Bs per month on each Cuban doctor.|date=16 March 2019|website=www.elalteno.com.bo|language=es}}</ref><ref name=Larrea></ref>The interim government stated that the Cuban embassy was paid $147 million over the course of 13 years for the Cuban doctors program and the president of the Medical College of La Paz, Luis Larrea, claimed that there was \"indiscriminate use of state assets, the waste of state money deposited in private accounts to, supposedly, pay Cubans, when these resources should be in a fiscal account,\" and that the Bolivian doctor felt \"belittled\".<ref name=Larrea>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20200123/anez-destapa-la-corrupcion-del-mas-y-dice-labor-cumplida|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez uncovers the corruption of the MAS and says \"work accomplished\"|language=es|website=www.elalteno.com.bo|date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2019/12/9/larrea-dice-que-el-gobierno-de-morales-despilfarro-dinero-menosprecio-al-medico-boliviano-239903.html|title=Larrea says the Morales government wasted money and belittled the Bolivian doctor|language=es|date=9 December 2019|website=www.elalteno.com.bo}}</ref> There have also been suggestions that only 205 out of 702 were doctors with the remaining working as drivers, technicians and in other areas that had nothing to do with medicine \"but were assigned salaries of 1,032, dollars\" as if they were doctors and that documents for these workers were falsified.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20191129/de-los-702-cubanos-solo-205-eran-medicos-pero-ganaban-buen-sueldo|title=Of the 702 Cubans, only 205 were doctors but they earned good salaries|language=es|website=www.elalteno.com.bo|date=29 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://eldeber.com.bo/162196_gobierno-de-evo-gasto-us-147-millones-en-medicos-cubanos|title=Evo's govenmnet wasted $147 million on Cuban doctors|date=January 2020</ref> The former head of the Cuban doctors program in Bolvia, Carlos de la Rocha, is facing charges of breach of duties, destruction of documents and theft, among other crimes. De la Rocha maintains his innocence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/161953_aprehenden-a-exfuncionario-responsable-del-programa-de-medicos-cubanos-en-bolivia|title=Former official responsible for the Cuban doctors program in Bolivia apprehended|language=es|date=January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/1/7/de-la-rocha-asegura-ser-inocente-que-manejo-todo-transparentemente-242714.html|title=De la Rocha claims to be innocent and that he handled everything transparently|language=es|website=www.paginasiete.bo|date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe interim government and President have explicitly signaled an attempt to disassociate themselves with countries that were political allies of Morales and \"anti imperialist ideology\". Chancellor [[Karen Longaric]] stated \"The relationship with Venezuela, Nicaragua and Cuba was aimed at consolidating an ideological current that had a geopolitical project. Bolivia did not benefit at all. It has always contributed more than it received and we are a developing country that cannot afford to make contributions or invest outside the country and sustaining other economies\" and that \"Bolivia did not want to participate in the association agreements with the EU, unlike Peru, Ecuador and Colombia, which did and that benefited, for example, with the elimination of visas to travel to Europe. Bolivia at the time moved away demonizing free trade agreements and treaties.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/1/6/gobierno-da-un-giro-las-relaciones-diplomaticas-bolivianas-con-decisiones-242520.html|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es|date=6 January 2020|title=Government reverses Bolivian diplomatic relations with 4 decisions}}</ref> This direction was further highlighted in the closure and replacement of the General [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Torres]] Anti-Imperialist Command School<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-37114191|website=www.bbc.com|date=18 August 2016|title=Bolivia opens 'anti-imperialist' school to counter US}}</ref><ref name=anti-imp>{{cite web|website=www.lostiempos.com|language=es|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20200116/sustituyen-escuela-antiimperialista-heroes-nancahuazu|title=The anti-imperialist school is replaced by H\u00e9roes de \u00d1ancahuaz\u00fa}}</ref>, an institution that made many military and political opponents uneasy as it was viewed as an attempt to align the military to a political ideology more sympathetic to that of Morales' MAS party. A ministry of defense press release stated that \"The core of the teaching focuses on anti-imperialist content with different components for the benefit of sergeants, second lieutenants, lieutenants, captains and above\". Taking and passing these courses was compulsory in order to achieve promotion to all ranks for captain and below.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindef.gob.bo/mindef/node/3257|title=Anti-imperialist School reinterprets history through the logic of the South|website=www.mindef.gob.bo|date=29 November 2018|language=es}}</ref><ref name=anti-imp></ref> In 2016, its opening was attended by the ministers of Defense of Nicaragua, Martha Ruiz Sevilla, and of Venezuela, the controversial [[Vladimir Padrino L\u00f3pez]].<ref>{{cite web|website=www.theguardian.com|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/aug/17/bolivia-anti-imperialist-military-school-evo-morales-us|title=Bolivia opens 'anti-imperialist' military school to counter US foreign policies|date=16 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=anti-imp></ref> The interim government had previously made it no longer compulsory to shout the phrase \"Patria o muerte\" (\"Fatherland or death\") during military activities. The phrase, popularised by [[Fidel Castro]] in a 1960 speech, was integrated into the military in 2010 by Morales, replacing the traditional \"subordinaci\u00f3n y constancia, viva Bolivia hacia el mar\" (\"subordination and constancy, long live Bolivia towards the sea\").<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/america-latina/2019/12/05/el-grito-de-patria-o-muerte-fue-eliminado-de-los-actos-militares-en-bolivia/|title=The cry of \"fatherland or death\" has been eliminated from military acts in Bolivia.|date=5 December 2019|language=es|webside=www.infobae.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 December, the formation of a new anti-terrorist group, Grupo Anti-Terrorista (GAT), was announced to combat terrorist groups and narcotics traffickers.<ref name=GAT></ref> \n\nOn 10 December, \u00c1\u00f1ez created a committee to facilitate the return of an estimated 1300 political exiles created during the government of former President Evo Morales. She stated that \"The committee will not help people who are prosecuted for crimes against humanity or for drug trafficking.\" These exiles would include Manfred Reyes Villa, Mario Coss\u00edo, Branko Marinkovic and Elsner Larraz\u00e1bal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elalteno.com.bo/bolivia/20191205/gobierno-crea-comite-para-el-retorno-de-los-perseguidos-politicos|title=Government creates committee for the return of persecuted politicians|date=10 December 2019|website=www.elalteno.com.bo|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/america-latina/2019/12/04/un-comite-investigara-las-denuncias-de-persecucion-politica-durante-los-anos-de-gobierno-de-evo-morales/|title=A committee will investigate allegations of political persecution during the years of Evo Morales' government|date=10 December 2019|language=es|website=www.infobae.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/nacional/20160528/periodistas-politicos-denuncian-persecucion|website=Los Tiempos|date=28 May 2016|language=es|title=Journalists and politicians denounce persecution}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 December 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez sent a bill to the Plurinational Legislative Assembly in which it would be mandatory for candidates to take part in debates. She stated of electoral debate that \"it is an obligation. Democracy thrives on freedom and the freedom to be responsible requires information\". During the almost 14 years that Morales ruled Bolivia, he never agreed to debate with any candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20191231/anez-envia-alp-proyecto-ley-que-plantea-debate-obligatorio-candidatos|website=www.lostiempos.com|language=es|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez submits a bill to assembly that raises mandatory debate between candidates}}</ref> This bill was rejected by the opposition ruled Assembly and \u00c1\u00f1ez appealed to them to reconsider on the grounds of \"making democracy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20200117/anez-apela-alp-aprobar-ley-debate-obligatorio-rumbo-elecciones|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez appeals to ALP to approve bill on obligatory electoral debates|date=13 January 2020|language=es|website=www.lostiempos.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 January 2020, the government decided to ratify the 22 January public holiday created by Morales to celebrate the founding of the [[Plurinational State of Bolivia]] via the 2009 constitution. On this day, the President of Bolivia normally addresses the nation, but doubt had been expressed whether this holiday would go ahead due to its strong political connection with Morales and MAS. In a public statement, however, minister for the Presidency [[Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], said \"January 22 is a holiday by presidential decree, we are going to respect that decree and our president is evaluating if she is going to make a report about the pillars of this government, which are transition, pacification and management.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/1/7/gobierno-ratifica-feriado-del-22-de-enero-anez-evalua-informe-de-gestion-242710.html | title=Government ratifies 22 January holiday and A\u00f1ez considers management address|language=es}}</ref> In this speech, she thanked the indigenous people of Bolivia for \"having accompanied the process with wisdom and firm decision\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theworldnews.net/bo-news/somos-un-pueblo-que-no-se-rinde|website=www.theworldnews.net|title=Plurinational State Day Presidential Speech|date=23 January 2020|language=es}}</ref>\n\nSince early March 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez has implemented numerous controls concerning the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bolivia|coronavirus pandemic]] including closing all borders, prohibiting all international and interdepartmental flights, a strict nationwide curfew and restricting driving to those transporting foods and supplies and those carrying out essential services. This crisis has also resulted in the postponement of the upcoming [[2020 Bolivian general election]], the delay having been agreed upon by all parties involved.\n\nOn 21 April 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez and her cabinet pledged to donate 50% of their monthly salary towards a fund to help those affected by the coronavirus pandemic and encouraged other parliamentarians to do the same. The President's monthly salary is currently Bs 24,251 ($3,520); that of a Minister of State of Bs 21,556 ($3,130); and that of a Vice Minister of Bs 20,210 ($2,930). The initial sum is Bs 250,000 ($36,290) per month. There is also an account managed by the ministry of health that anyone can donate to.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.la-razon.com/nacional/2020/04/21/anez-y-ministros-aportan-50-de-sus-sueldos-a-un-fondo-para-afectados-por-la-cuarentena/|website=www.la-razon.com|date=21 April 2020|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez and ministers donate 50% of earnings to fund for those affected by coronavirus|language=es}}</ref>\n\n===2020 Presidential Candidacy===\n\nOn 5 December, \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that she would not be a candidate or support any candidate in the upcoming presidential election.<ref>[https://rpp.pe/mundo/latinoamerica/bolivia-jeanine-anez-no-postulara-a-la-presidencia-segun-el-gobierno-interino-noticia-1233337 Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez no postular\u00e1 a la Presidencia de Bolivia, seg\u00fan el Gobierno interino.] Publicado el 5 de diciembre de 2019. Consultado el 8 de diciembre de 2019.</ref> This was further reiterated on 15 January 2020 by Minister for the Presidency [[:w:es:Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez|Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], who said that \"[\u00c1\u00f1ez] will not be a candidate. The President has stated on several occasions, she will not be a candidate, this is a government of peace, transition, and management because you can not stop the state apparatus.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/jeanine-anez-presidencia-gobierno-elecciones-bolivia_0_3294870527.html| language=es|title=Government clarifies that Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez will not be a candidate for the Presidency}}</ref>\n\nDespite her previous statements, \u00c1\u00f1ez announced her candidacy on 24 January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atb.com.bo/pol\u00edtica/jeanine-\u00e1\u00f1ez-confirma-candidatura-presidencial-para-las-elecciones-generales|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez confirma candidatura presidencial para las elecciones generales|date=24 January 2020|access-date=24 January 2020|website=ATBDigital|language=es-ES}}</ref> A survey reported in the Bolivian newspaper ''[[Los Tiempos]]'' indicated that, while 43% of respondents considered her to have done a \"good or very good\" job as interim president (compared to 27% bad or very bad), only 24% of respondents believed that she should stand as a candidate in the upcoming elections. In the same poll, 63% of respondents agreed with the statement that \"as interim president, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez should call elections and not take advantage of her power to become a presidential candidate.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20200126/encuesta-aprueban-gestion-anez-pero-rechazan-candidatura| title=Survey approves of \u00c1\u00f1ez's term as president, but rejects her candidacy.|language=es|date=26 January 2020}}</ref> Her running mate who was previously critical of her decision to stand as a presidential candidate is [[Samuel Doria Medina]], a former presidential candidate and leader of the center-right [[National Unity Front]] party.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/03/05/bolivia-after-the-ouster-of-evo-morales-a-leftist-strongman| title=Bolivia after the ouster of Evo Morales, a leftist strongman|date= 7 March 2020}}</ref>. They are standing under the newly formed [[Juntos (Bolivian political party)|Juntos]] alliance. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Unidad-Nacional-Sole-Vicepresidencia-Juntos_0_3304469555.html|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez and Doria Medina seal alliance and become presidential running mates| language=es|date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nA\u00f1ez is described as a [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-idUSKBN1XM1NV |title=Bolivian Senate head assumes interim presidency; Morales' loyalists object |date=13 November 2019 |work=Reuters |access-date=15 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191113-bolivian-senator-declares-herself-president-morales-denounces-coup |title=Bolivian senator declares herself interim president, Morales slams 'coup' |date=13 November 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> [[Religious conservatism|religious conservative]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/bolivia-s-new-leader-religious-conservative-jeanine-ez-chavez-faces-n1082426 |title=Bolivia's new leader, religious conservative Jeanine A\u00f1ez Chavez, faces daunting challenges |website=NBC News |language=en |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/14/bolivia-interim-leader-recognises-guaido-legitimate-venezuelan/ |title=Bolivia interim leader recognises Guaido as legitimate Venezuelan leader as balance shifts |last=Staff |first=Our Foreign |date=14 November 2019 |work=The Telegraph |access-date=15 November 2019 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> and has been a critic of Evo Morales.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bolivia-senator-jeanine-anez-declares-herself-interim-president/a-51218963 |title=Bolivia: Senator Jeanine Anez declares herself interim president {{!}} DW {{!}} 12 November 2019 |last= |first= |date= |website=Deutsche Welle |language=en-GB |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Drugs===\n\u00c1\u00f1ez has spoken out against the proliferation of drug trafficking in South America.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2017/10/20/narcotrafico-anez-llama-canalla-romero-dice-sobrino-responsable-actos-156480.html |title=Narcotr\u00e1fico: A\u00f1ez llama \"canalla\" a Romero y dice que su sobrino es responsable de sus actos |last= |first= |date= |website=Diario Pagina Siete |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, her nephew was arrested in Brazil for smuggling 480 kilos of drugs. The security minister [[Carlos Romero (Bolivian politician)|Carlos Romero]] criticized \u00c1\u00f1ez and said that her position in the senate was \"rogue\" because of the relationship; \u00c1\u00f1ez responded by saying that she is not responsible for her nephew's actions, and criticized Romero because of his position in the government by saying that he is \"responsible for the growth of drug trafficking\". It was later revealed that another Bolivian arrested with drugs at the same time was the nephew of another politician, this time belonging to the MAS ruling party.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===Prison services===\nIn early 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez called for an investigation into prison wardens in Beni after speaking to victims of rape and abuse on the part of guards. She aimed to set a precedent to bring in new legislation that can be upheld.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eju.tv/2019/03/senadora-jeanine-anez-pide-al-gobierno-investigar-todas-carceletas-del-beni/ |title=Senadora Jeanine A\u00f1ez pide al Gobierno investigar todas carceletas del Beni |website=eju.tv |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nShe describes herself as a [[Christianity|Christian]] and held up a large Bible while declaring herself the interim president; this was described by ''The Guardian'' as an \"explicit rebuke\" of Morales, who has a strained [[Evo Morales and the Roman Catholic Church|history with the Catholic Church]] and has expressed support for indigenous religious traditions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191113-jeanine-anez-stand-in-president-vowing-to-pacify-bolivia |title=Jeanine Anez: stand-in president vowing to 'pacify' Bolivia |date=13 November 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/13/jeanine-anez-bolivia-president-promises-new-elections |title=Bolivia's interim president Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez promises new elections |last=Collyns |first=Dan |date=13 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 November 2019 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Under Morales, a new [[Constitution of Bolivia|Constitution]] was [[2009 Bolivian constitutional referendum|approved by referendum]] that gave Christianity equal status to other religions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-11/bolivia-faces-power-vacuum-and-more-chaos-after-morales-quits |title=Senator Brandishing Giant Bible Takes Over Bolivia Presidency |date=11 November 2019 |website=Bloomberg |language=en |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> A 2018 survey found that 70% of Bolivians identified as Catholic and 17.2% as Protestant of some form. 9.3% were non-religious.<ref>[https://www.statista.com/statistics/1066911/religious-affiliation-in-bolivia/ \u2022 Religion affiliations in Bolivia 2018 | Statista<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Political analyst Carlos Cordero states that \u201cShe is a believer, but she does not use her religiosity politically, she expresses it, she lives it.\u201d<ref>https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/12/30/las-quince-diferencias-en-el-estilo-de-gobernar-de-jeanine-anez-morales-241950.html</ref>\n\n===Venezuela===\n\u00c1\u00f1ez recognized [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]] as acting president of Venezuela in the [[2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis]], 24 hours after taking office.<ref name=\"Alberto\">{{cite web |url=https://albertonews.com/principales/ultima-hora-bolivia-reconoce-a-juan-guaido-como-presidente-e-de-venezuela/ |title=Bolivia reconoce a Juan Guaid\u00f3 como presidente (E) de Venezuela |date=13 November 2019 |website=Albertonews.com |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> Her interim government also severed diplomatic relations with Venezuela's Maduro government, giving its diplomats 72 hours to leave the country.<ref name=\"lapiensa\">{{cite web |url=https://latinoamericapiensa.com/la-politica-internacional-de-anez-anuncio-la-salida-de-bolivia-del-alba-de-la-unasur-y-rompio-relaciones-con-venezuela/21065/ |title=La pol\u00edtica internacional de A\u00f1ez: anunci\u00f3 la salida de Bolivia del Alba, de la Unasur y rompi\u00f3 relaciones con Venezuela |language=es |website=Latinomerica Piensa |date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-bolivia-election-venezuela/bolivas-interim-government-to-ask-venezuelan-diplomats-to-leave-the-country-idUKKBN1XP23U |title=Boliva's interim government to ask Venezuelan diplomats to leave the country |website=Reuters |date=15 November 2019}}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez has also called on Guaid\u00f3 to appoint the new Venezuelan Ambassador to Bolivia, \"who will be recognized immediately by our government.\"<ref name=\"Alberto\"/>\n\nA month later, her government announced Bolivia's entry into the [[Lima Group]], a regional bloc established in 2017 with the purpose of finding a way out of the [[Crisis in Venezuela|Venezuelan crisis]]. The Bolivian foreign ministry said in a statement that it hoped to \u201ccontribute to a peaceful, democratic and constitutional solution to the crisis in Venezuela, which must be guided by the Venezuelan people.\u201d<ref>{{cite web | last1=Sigal | first1=Lucila | title=Bolivia announces entry into Lima Group to resolve Venezuelan crisis | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-politics/bolivia-announces-entry-into-lima-group-to-resolve-venezuelan-crisis-idUSKBN1YQ0JM | date=22 December 2019 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> On the same month, the interim government announced that they would give refuge to 200 Venezuelans \"who have fled their country for reasons of political order, of political persecution promoted by the [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] government.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/es/bolivia-dar%C3%A1-refugio-a-200-venezolanos-que-huyeron-por-persecuci%C3%B3n-pol%C3%ADtica/a-51665845|title=Bolivia will shelter 200 Venezuelans who fled for \"political persecution\"|last=|first=|date=13 December 2019|work=[[Deutsch Welle]]|access-date=4 January 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n===Violence against women and children===\nDuring her second senatorial term, \u00c1\u00f1ez was associated with legislative works to combat feminicides and violence against women which has become a continuing theme for her politically.<ref name=CIDOB></ref>\n\nOn 6 February 2020, she invited the people of Bolivia to attend a march in Santa Cruz in support of the fight against violence against women and children, an issue increasingly highlighted by the Bolivian press. <ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/rascacielos/2020/3/8/feminicidios-en-bolivia-suenos-robados-248613.html|language=es|date=8 March 2020|title=Feminicides in Bolivia: Stolen Dreams}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/2/6/anez-pide-denunciar-la-violencia-contra-mujeres-ninos-en-una-marcha-245817.html|date=6 February 2020| title=A\u00f1ez asks to denounce violence against women and children in a march|language=es}}</ref>\n\nOn [[International Women's Day]], 8 March 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez announced a $100 million investment in the fight against violence against women, She declared 2020 as the  Year of the Fight Against Feminicide and Infanticide in Bolivia, saying \"I am the worst news for all those murderers of women, users of violence, abusers, stalkers and rapists, because I will not get tired of closing against these aggressors\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.la-razon.com/sociedad/mujer-bolivia-anez-presidenta-violencia-genero_0_3326667313.html| title=\u00c1\u00f1ez: 'I will give everything to end gender violence'|language=es|date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2020/3/10/violencia-anez-lanza-plan-con-una-inversion-de-us-100-millones-249125.html|title=Violence: A\u00f1ez launches plan with an investment of $ us 100 million|language=es|date=8 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Racism controversy==\nAround 41% of the population of Bolivia identifies itself as [[Indigenous peoples in Bolivia|indigenous]]<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/15/world/americas/morales-bolivia-Indigenous-racism.html |title=Ethnic Rifts in Bolivia Burst Into View With Fall of Evo Morales |date=15 November 2019 |agency=The New York Times}}</ref> and the population often encounters discrimination regarding their social status in Bolivia, mainly related to poverty and ethnic background.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/could-bolivias-current-politics-be-fueling-indigenous-discrimination |title=Could Bolivia's current politics be fueling indigenous discrimination? |last= |first= |date=25 November 2019 |website=[[PBS NewsHour]] |language=en-us |access-date=3 December 2019}}</ref> Following the 2006 election of Evo Morales, the first indigenous president of Bolivia, polarization between the indigenous peoples and others increased<ref name=\":5\" /> as Bolivia's political system shifted from left-right politics to indigenous-urbanist politics.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Faguet |first=Jean-Paul |date=June 2019 |title=Revolution from Below: Cleavage Displacement and the Collapse of Elite Politics in Bolivia |url= http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/100505/1/Revolution_from_Below_in_Bolivia_2_Theory_v4_Full.docx|journal=[[Politics & Society]] |volume=47 |issue=2 |pages=205\u2013250 |doi=10.1177/0032329219845944 |quote=Politics shifted from a conventional left-right axis of competition, unsuited to Bolivian society, to an ethnic/rural\u2013cosmopolitan/urban axis closely aligned with its major social cleavage.|via= }}</ref>\n\nShortly after her inauguration, opponents of \u00c1\u00f1ez circulated [[Twitter#Tweets|tweets]] dating back to 2013 <ref name=\"elcomercio\">{{cite news |url=https://elcomercio.pe/mundo/latinoamerica/jeanine-anez-estos-son-los-agresivos-tuits-contra-originarios-e-indigenas-que-borro-la-presidenta-interina-de-bolivia-noticia/ |title=Estos son los agresivos tuits contra \"originarios\" e \"ind\u00edgenas\" que borr\u00f3 Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez, la presidenta de Bolivia |date=15 November 2019 |agency=Redaccion El Comercio}}</ref>. These tweets, directed towards indigenous peoples, have been described as \"racist\" by ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref name=\"guardian\" /> \"anti-indigenous\" by [[Agence France-Press]],<ref name=\"afp\">{{cite news |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/these-are-anti-indigenous-tweets-bolivias-interim-president-deleted |title=These are the anti-indigenous tweets that Bolivia's interim president deleted |date=16 November 2019 |agency=Agence France-Presse (AFP)}}</ref> and \"provocative\" by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> On [[Twitter]], \u00c1\u00f1ez called the [[Aymara people]]'s [[Willkakuti|New Year celebration]] \"satanic\" and said that \"nobody can replace God\", and has implied that indigenous people were not genuine for wearing shoes.<ref name=\"afp\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> She would later state \"I\u2019ve seen a couple of tweets that I never wrote and that we already stated were false\" and that she never made \"ill-intentioned\" comments.<ref name=\":5\" /> In the opening days of her presidency, [[Mar\u00eda Galindo]], an outspoken critic of Morales and an anarcha-feminist and psychologist, described the government of \u00c1\u00f1ez as \"anti-indigenous.\"<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |newspaper=The Guardian |date=14 November 2019}}</ref> About \u00c1\u00f1ez, she would later state that \"her hatred of the Indian is of all hatreds the most painful, because it is a hatred of herself\", referring to \u00c1\u00f1ez' own mestizo background. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/opinion/maria-galindo/2019/12/18/jeanine-usurpadora-sustituta-subalterna-240715.html|title=Jeanine: Usurper, substitute, subordinate?|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|author=Mar\u00eda  Galindo|date=18 December 2019|language=es}}</ref>\n\nAs acting president, \u00c1\u00f1ez has kept [[wiphala]], the flag of indigenous Bolivian communities, as a co-official [[flag of Bolivia]], as it had been under Morales, declaring that she was committed to the fundamental task of \"highlighting the unity [of the] plural and diverse\" nation of Bolivia.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://eju.tv/2019/11/jeanine-anez-instruye-que-junto-a-la-sagrada-tricolor-se-mantenga-la-wiphala/ |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez instruye que junto a la sagrada tricolor se mantenga la wiphala |website=eju.tv |date=12 November 2019}}</ref> In addition to the whipala, the [[patuj\u00fa]] is displayed prominently.<ref>[https://www.eldeber.com.bo/156526_colocan-la-bandera-de-la-flor-del-patuju-junto-a-la-wiphala-y-la-tricolor-en-palacio-quemado Colocan la bandera de la Flor del Patuj\u00fa junto a la wiphala y la tricolor en Palacio Quemado | EL DEBER<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The patuj\u00fa is a symbol of the Eastern indigenous peoples of Bolivia and of [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]], Bolivia's largest city. This flag was also adopted by indigenous opposition to Morales during the [[Isiboro_S%C3%A9cure_National_Park_and_Indigenous_Territory|TIPNIS]] protests.<ref>[https://radiopatuju.blogspot.com/2012/05/imagenes-por-el-tipnis-no.html Radio Patuj\u00fa 95.2 FM: IM\u00c1GENES \"POR EL TIPNIS NO\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> On 26 November 2019, she was presented with and wore a red poncho (a traditional Andean garment worn by community leaders) by representatives of the indigenous community on the inauguration of [[Rafael Quispe]] as director of the Fund for Indigenous Development.<ref>[https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20191126/anez-viste-poncho-andino-obsequiado-comunarios A\u00f1ez viste poncho andino obsequiado por comunarios | Los Tiempos<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On 28 January 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez signed a proposed bill to provide cultural recognition to the seven different identities of the country's indigenous women. After signing she stated \"This bill is a demonstration of the value of the [[pollera]] woman as the main character in the fight for the equality of indigenous, rural, migrant and mestizo women\" and that \"the principle of equality must transcend laws and transform society and create more opportunities for indigenous and rural women.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bolivia.com/actualidad/nacionales/cholas-bolivianas-patrimonio-cultural-e-inmaterial-bolivia-jeanine-anez-258189|website=www.bolivia.com|language=es|date=28 January 2020|title=Government will seek to declare the Cholas cultural heritage of Bolivia}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez was married in Santa Cruz at the age of 23 to Tadeo Ribera Bruckner, a lawyer and a former mayor of [[Trinidad, Bolivia|Trinidad]], the capital of [[Beni Department|Beni]], representing the Uni\u00f3n C\u00edvica Solidaridad (UCS) party. They had two children together, Carolina (born 1990) and Jos\u00e9 Armando (born 1995). Ribera died in [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]] on 29 January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/164289_fallece-el-exesposo-de-la-presidenta-jeanine-anez|website=El Deber|title=Ex-husband of President Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez dies|date=29 January 2020|language=es}}</ref><ref name=biografias></ref>\n\n\u00c1\u00f1ez's second husband is H\u00e9ctor Hernando Hincapi\u00e9 Carvajal, a Colombian from [[Tolima Department|Tolima]]. He is a politician in the [[Colombian Conservative Party]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=RESULTADO CORPORACI\u00d3N |url=https://elecciones.caracol.com.co/candidatos/senado/partido-conservador-colombiano |website=Caracol Radio |accessdate=14 November 2019|date=26 October 2019}}</ref> Hincapi\u00e9 ran, unsuccessfully, for a seat in the Colombian Senate in 2018, and as a member of the Tolima regional assembly and House of Representatives in 2010 and 2014 respectively. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lafm.com.co/internacional/el-colombiano-que-se-robo-el-corazon-de-la-presidenta-e-de-bolivia|title=The Colombian that stole he heart of the President of Bolivia|language=es|website=www.lafm.com.co|date=13 November 2019}}</ref> Until recently, they travelled between Bolivia and Colombia to see one another, although this has become easier since failure to win a seat in 2018.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=https://www.opinion.com.bo/content/print/jeanine-anez-chavez-mujer-dirige-bolivia-afronta-desafios/20191122104634737958|website=www.opinion.com.bo|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, the woman who heads Bolivia and faces challenges|language=es|date=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links\n|wikt=no|commonscat=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez|n=no|q=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez|s=no|author=no|b=no|v=no\n|voy=no|d=Q16581287|m=no|mw=no|species=no|species_author=no\n}}\n*[http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/spip.php?page=parlamentario&id_parlamentario=159 Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez]\n*[https://www.cidob.org/biografias_lideres_politicos/america_del_sur/bolivia/jeanine_anez_chavez Biography by CIDOB] \n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Evo Morales]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Bolivia]]|order=Interim|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of Bolivia}}\n{{Heads of State of the South America}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anez, Jeanine}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Bolivian politicians]]\n[[Category:Bolivian Christians]]\n[[Category:Female heads of government]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:People from Beni Department]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Senate of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Women presidents]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeanine_%C3%81%C3%B1ez"}
{"title_page": "L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n|name=L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n<br />[[wikt:\u8c89|\u8c89]][[wikt:\u9f8d|\u9f8d]][[wikt:\u541b|\u541b]]\n|image=\u0110\u1ec1n th\u1edd L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n.jpg\n|caption=Temple of L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n\n|title=[[ H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng| H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng of  V\u0103n Lang ]]\n|father= [[Kinh D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng]]\n|mother= [[Long M\u1eabu Th\u1ea7n Long]]\n|spouse=[[\u00c2u C\u01a1]]\n|issue= 100 sons and daughters\n|birth_date=?\n|birth_place = ?\n|death_date=?\n|death_place =\n|place of burial = \n|full name= S\u00f9ng L\u00e3m\n|succession=[[ H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng| H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng of V\u0103n Lang ]]\n|reign=2793 BC&ndash;2524 BC\n|predecessor=[[Kinh D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng| H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng II]]\n|successor=[[H\u00f9ng Qu\u1ed1c V\u01b0\u01a1ng| H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng III]]\n|succession1=\n|reign1=\n|predecessor1=\n|successor1=\n|house=\n|era dates= \n|temple name=\n|posthumous name=\n|religion = \n}}\n{{Contains Vietnamese text}}\n\n'''L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n''' (literally \"Dragon Lord of L\u1ea1c\"; also called '''H\u00f9ng Hi\u1ec1n V\u01b0\u01a1ng''') as known as  '''H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng II''', is considered the second [[H\u00f9ng king]] of the semi-mythical [[H\u1ed3ng B\u00e0ng Dynasty]] of ancient [[Vietnam]] (known then as V\u0103n Lang and before that as X\u00edch Qu\u1ef7). Qu\u00e2n was the son and sole successor of [[Kinh D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng]] (the first Hung king), who ruled over X\u00edch Qu\u1ef7. He is thought to have become king in 2793 BC. He is also a significant figure in Vietnamese legend.\n\nIn modern day, his life is mixed with many legends. Qu\u00e2n's wife, [[\u00c2u C\u01a1]], gave birth to a sac containing 100 eggs from which 100 children were born; this is the origin of the story of the [[Hundred Family Surnames|100]] [[Vietnamese name|Vietnamese family names]], later the [[B\u00e1ch Vi\u1ec7t]] tribes. One day L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n told \u00c2u C\u01a1: \"I am descended from dragons, you from [[Fairy|fairies]]. We are as incompatible as water is with fire. So we cannot continue in harmony.\" This said, the husband and wife parted. The man went to the seawards with 50 of their children, while his wife went to the mountainous region with the other half of the clan. The eldest son, who followed his mother,<ref>Ng\u00f4 Th\u00ec S\u0129, Vi\u1ec7t s\u1eed Ti\u00eau \u00e1n]</ref> later installed himself as Qu\u00e2n's successor.<ref>Roseane M Santos ''An Unashamed Defense of Coffee'' - Page 268 2009 \"A Vietnamese myth claims that the Vietnamese people of various tribes were born outside the womb following the marriage of L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n (Dragon Chief) and \u00c2u C\u01a1 (the Fairy), but Vietnamese historians consider the Dong Son civilization ...\"</ref><ref>Nghia M. Vo ''Saigon: A History'' 2011 -- Page 285 \"According to legend, King L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n wed fairy \u00c2u C\u01a1 who gave him 100 children. Both considered to be the ancestors of the Vietnamese nation, they later split up; taking 50 children, he settled along the coastal area and founded the ...\"</ref>\n\n==Genealogy==\nL\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n's father was [[Kinh D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng]] and L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n's mother is [[Long M\u1eabu Th\u1ea7n Long]] (Divine Mother Goddess of Dragons).<ref>Keith Weller Taylor: ''The Birth of Vietnam''. Revision of thesis (Ph.D), Appendix A, pg. 304. University of California Press (1991). {{ISBN|0-520-07417-3}}</ref>\n\n==In Vietnamese literature==\nThe books [[\u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t s\u1eed k\u00fd to\u00e0n th\u01b0]] (from the 15th century) and [[L\u0129nh Nam ch\u00edch qu\u00e1i]] (\"Wonders plucked from the dust of Linh-nam\", from the 14th century) mention the legend with \u00c2u C\u01a1.<ref>Keith Weller Taylor: ''The Birth of Vietnam''. Revision of thesis (Ph.D.). Appendix A, page 303. [[University of California Press]] (1991). {{ISBN|0-520-07417-3}}</ref>\n\n==Mythology==\n'''Slaying of NG\u01af TINH'''\n\nDuring L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n's time, the people of Van Lang was still undeveloped and isolated. In the Eastern sea, there appears a giant Fish called Ng\u01b0 Tinh  (Vietnamese for \"fish monster\" or \"fish spirit\"). This fish has lived for centuries, with the size of its mouth, it can consume a ship with 10 fisherman at the same time. Whenever the Fish swim, waves can reach the sky, drown multiple ships, all the people passing through the area were all eaten by the fish. Ng\u01b0 Tinh  lives in a big cave under the sea, above the cave is a huge mountain which divide the sea into two areas.\n\nL\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n decided to slay the beast to help the people. He built a huge ship, made a burning human-shaped piece of metal, then sailed straight to Ng\u01b0 Tinh nest. There he held the human-shaped piece of metal up to trick Ng\u01b0 Tinh. Ng\u01b0 Tinh thought it was a human than opened its mouth and tried to swallow to burning metal. Qu\u00e2n threw the burning metal into Ng\u01b0 Tinh's mouth. Ng\u01b0 Tinh 's throat was burning, it struggled but tried to sink Qu\u00e2n's ship. Qu\u00e2n then took his sword out and slew the beast, slicing it into three pieces.\n\n'''Slaying of the nine-tailed fox '''\n\nAfter slaying Ng\u01b0 Tinh, Qu\u00e2n went down to Long Bi\u00ean. There appears a [[nine-tailed fox]] that live for thousand years, called H\u1ed3 Tinh (Vietnamese for \"fox monster\" or \"fox spirit\"). The fox lived in a deep cave, under a rock mountain in the West Long Bi\u00ean. This fox often disguised into human shape, lure the women, then bring them to the cave and feed on them. This fox has been harassing people from Long Bi\u00ean to T\u1ea3n Vi\u00ean mountain. The innocents were so afraid of the fox that they have to leave their homes, farms to other places in order to live peacefully. Qu\u00e2n brought his sword to the beast's nest and tried to slay the beast. When Qu\u00e2n reached the cave, the fox smelled human, then suddenly attacked, Qu\u00e2n then used magic to call the elements of wind and thunders to trap the beast. After 3 days, the beast has weakened, tried to find a way to run away. Qu\u00e2n caught the beast and sliced its head off. The beast revealed itself as a huge nine-tailed fox. Qu\u00e2n got into the cave and rescued everybody that was alive and tortured by the fox.\n\n'''Descendant of Dragon and Fairy'''\n\nL\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n is a son of [[Long M\u1eabu Th\u1ea7n Long]], the dragon goddess that rules the sky and the ocean. \n\nL\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n was married to \u0110\u1ebf Lai's daughter, \u00c2u C\u01a1. She gave birth to a sac of a hundred eggs, which were hatched into a hundred boys. One day, Qu\u00e2n confessed to her: \"I am a descendant of the Dragon, you are descendant of the Fairy, fire and water cannot live together in harmony.\" The two of them then divided their children. Fifty sons followed their mother to the mountainous north, the other fifty followed their father to live in the south; these children are ancestor of B\u00e1ch Vi\u1ec7t. The oldest brother followed \u00c2u C\u01a1 to Phong Ch\u00e2u (Ph\u00fa Th\u1ecd), became Qu\u00e2n's successor and ruled as Hung King.<ref>http://myvietnamhandbook.com/vietnamese-culture/{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Linh Nam Chich Quai, Dai Viet Su Ky Toan Thu</ref>\n[[File:\u0110\u1ec1n th\u1edd L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n.jpg|thumb|250px|right|L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n's temple at Sim Hill (Ph\u00fa Th\u1ecd)]]\n[[image:\u0110\u1ec1n th\u1edd ch\u00ednh th\u1edd L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n.jpg|Small|250px|right|thumb| L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n 's temple at Sim hill.]]\n\n==Legacy==\nMost cities in Vietnam have named major streets after him.<ref>{{cite book| title=Vietnam Country Map |publisher=Periplus Travel Maps |year=2002\u20132003 |isbn=0-7946-0070-0}}</ref> He features both in primary education,<ref>Marie-Carine Lall, Edward Vickers - ''Education As a Political Tool in Asia'' - Page 143 2009 \"'Vietnamese-ness'. The history of the country really started around 800 bc with the V\u0103n Lang kingship. Children learn about the legends of the nation's birth, which feature heroic figures such as [[Kinh D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng]], [[\u00c2u C\u01a1]] \u2013 L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n ...\"</ref> and in some forms of popular religious belief as a god.<ref>Andrea Lauser, Kirsten W. Endres - ''Engaging the Spirit World: Popular Beliefs and Practices in Modern Vietnam'' 2012 - Page 93  \"of the Water Palace are linked to the mythical foundation of the country and they are considered to be descendants of the Dragon King of [[\u0110\u1ed9ng \u0110\u00ecnh]], father of the mythic founder of the country, L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n. Images from this past are enacted ...\"</ref><ref>Philip Taylor  ''Modernity and Re-Enchantment: Religion in Post-Revolutionary Vietnam'' Page 68  2007 \"According to legend, all Vietnamese people can trace their ancestry back to the marriage of the dragon father L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n and the fairy mother \u00c2u C\u01a1. This magical union produced an egg sac from which hatched one hundred human ...\"</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Vietnam|Mythology}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=rCl_02LnNVIC&pg=PA1&dq=%22lac+long+quan%22&sig=ACfU3U0mKRwsh2QROLWiZWFzktnledCrEg Google Books search]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=hDV-LJbKS_AC&pg=PA232&dq=%22lac+long+quan%22&sig=ACfU3U2YQr2ZM2O_SkfVjxyOskSXHB5Nkw  Google Books search]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=YgA1kBqOZYgC&pg=PA71&dq=%22lac+long+quan%22&sig=ACfU3U3_Ycg6qs4yuX6N-KnIisDX3uL-5A#PPA72,M1 Google Books search]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of monarchs of Vietnam]]\n*[[H\u1ed3ng B\u00e0ng Dynasty]]\n*[[Yue (state)]]\n*[[Goujian]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|H\u1ed3ng B\u00e0ng Dynasty||||}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kinh D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Vietnamese monarchs|King of V\u0103n Lang]]|years= 2793 BC \u2013 ? }}\n{{s-aft|after=H\u00f9ng Qu\u1ed1c V\u01b0\u01a1ng}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quan, Lac Long}}\n[[Category:28th-century BC rulers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Vietnam]]\n[[Category:H\u1ed3ng B\u00e0ng dynasty]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese culture]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n|name=L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n<br />[[wikt:\u8c89|\u8c89]][[wikt:\u9f8d|\u9f8d]][[wikt:\u541b|\u541b]]\n|image=\u0110\u1ec1n th\u1edd L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n.jpg\n|caption=Temple of L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n\n|title=[[ H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng| H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng of  V\u0103n Lang ]]\n|father= [[Kinh D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng]]\n|mother= [[Long M\u1eabu Th\u1ea7n Long]]\n|spouse=[[\u00c2u C\u01a1]]\n|issue= 100 sons and daughters\n|birth_date=?\n|birth_place = ?\n|death_date=?\n|death_place =\n|place of burial = \n|full name= S\u00f9ng L\u00e3m\n|succession=[[ H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng| H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng of V\u0103n Lang ]]\n|reign=2793 BC&ndash;2524 BC\n|predecessor=[[Kinh D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng| H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng II]]\n|successor=[[H\u00f9ng Qu\u1ed1c V\u01b0\u01a1ng| H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng III]]\n|succession1=\n|reign1=\n|predecessor1=\n|successor1=\n|house=\n|era dates= \n|temple name=\n|posthumous name=\n|religion = \n}}\n{{Contains Vietnamese text}}\n\n'''L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n''' (literally \"Dragon Lord of L\u1ea1c\"; also called '''H\u00f9ng Hi\u1ec1n V\u01b0\u01a1ng''') as known as  '''H\u00f9ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng II''', is considered the second [[H\u00f9ng king]] of the semi-mythical [[H\u1ed3ng B\u00e0ng Dynasty]] of ancient [[Vietnam]] (known then as V\u0103n Lang and before that as X\u00edch Qu\u1ef7). Qu\u00e2n was the son and sole successor of [[Kinh D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng]] (the first Hung king), who ruled over X\u00edch Qu\u1ef7. He is thought to have become king in 2793 BC. He is also a significant figure in Vietnamese legend.\n\nIn modern day, his life is mixed with many legends. Qu\u00e2n's wife, [[\u00c2u C\u01a1]], gave birth to a sac containing 100 eggs from which 100 children were born; this is the origin of the story of the [[Hundred Family Surnames|100]] [[Vietnamese name|Vietnamese family names]], later the [[B\u00e1ch Vi\u1ec7t]] tribes. One day L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n told \u00c2u C\u01a1: \"I am descended from dragons, you from [[Fairy|fairies]]. We are as incompatible as water is with fire. So we cannot continue in harmony.\" This said, the husband and wife parted. The man went to the seawards with 50 of their children, while his wife went to the mountainous region with the other half of the clan. The eldest son, who followed his mother,<ref>Ng\u00f4 Th\u00ec S\u0129, Vi\u1ec7t s\u1eed Ti\u00eau \u00e1n]</ref> later installed himself as Qu\u00e2n's successor.<ref>Roseane M Santos ''An Unashamed Defense of Coffee'' - Page 268 2009 \"A Vietnamese myth claims that the Vietnamese people of various tribes were born outside the womb following the marriage of L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n (Dragon Chief) and \u00c2u C\u01a1 (the Fairy), but Vietnamese historians consider the Dong Son civilization ...\"</ref><ref>Nghia M. Vo ''Saigon: A History'' 2011 -- Page 285 \"According to legend, King L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n wed fairy \u00c2u C\u01a1 who gave him 100 children. Both considered to be the ancestors of the Vietnamese nation, they later split up; taking 50 children, he settled along the coastal area and founded the ...\"</ref>\n\n==Genealogy==\nL\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n's father was [[Kinh D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng]] and L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n's mother is [[Long M\u1eabu Th\u1ea7n Long]] (Divine Mother Goddess of Dragons).<ref>Keith Weller Taylor: ''The Birth of Vietnam''. Revision of thesis (Ph.D), Appendix A, pg. 304. University of California Press (1991). {{ISBN|0-520-07417-3}}</ref>\n\n==In Vietnamese literature==\nThe books [[\u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t s\u1eed k\u00fd to\u00e0n th\u01b0]] (from the 15th century) and [[L\u0129nh Nam ch\u00edch qu\u00e1i]] (\"Wonders plucked from the dust of Linh-nam\", from the 14th century) mention the legend with \u00c2u C\u01a1.<ref>Keith Weller Taylor: ''The Birth of Vietnam''. Revision of thesis (Ph.D.). Appendix A, page 303. [[University of California Press]] (1991). {{ISBN|0-520-07417-3}}</ref>\n\n==Mythology==\n'''Slaying of NG\u01af TINH'''\n\nDuring L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n's time, the people of Van Lang was still undeveloped and isolated. In the Eastern sea, there appears a giant Fish called Ng\u01b0 Tinh  (Vietnamese for \"fish monster\" or \"fish spirit\"). This fish has lived for centuries, with the size of its mouth, it can consume a ship with 10 fisherman at the same time. Whenever the Fish swim, waves can reach the sky, drown multiple ships, all the people passing through the area were all eaten by the fish. Ng\u01b0 Tinh  lives in a big cave under the sea, above the cave is a huge mountain which divide the sea into two areas.\n\nL\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n decided to slay the beast to help the people. He built a huge ship, made a burning human-shaped piece of metal, then sailed straight to Ng\u01b0 Tinh nest. There he held the human-shaped piece of metal up to trick Ng\u01b0 Tinh. Ng\u01b0 Tinh thought it was a human than opened its mouth and tried to swallow to burning metal. Qu\u00e2n threw the burning metal into Ng\u01b0 Tinh's mouth. Ng\u01b0 Tinh 's throat was burning, it struggled but tried to sink Qu\u00e2n's ship. Qu\u00e2n then took his sword out and slew the beast, slicing it into three pieces.\n\n'''Slaying of the nine-tailed fox '''\n\nAfter slaying Ng\u01b0 Tinh, Qu\u00e2n went down to Long Bi\u00ean. There appears a [[nine-tailed fox]] that live for thousand years, called H\u1ed3 Tinh (Vietnamese for \"fox monster\" or \"fox spirit\"). The fox lived in a deep cave, under a rock mountain in the West Long Bi\u00ean. This fox often disguised into human shape, lure the women, then bring them to the cave and feed on them. This fox has been harassing people from Long Bi\u00ean to T\u1ea3n Vi\u00ean mountain. The innocents were so afraid of the fox that they have to leave their homes, farms to other places in order to live peacefully. Qu\u00e2n brought his sword to the beast's nest and tried to slay the beast. When Qu\u00e2n reached the cave, the fox smelled human, then suddenly attacked, Qu\u00e2n then used magic to call the elements of wind and thunders to trap the beast. After 3 days, the beast has weakened, tried to find a way to run away. Qu\u00e2n caught the beast and sliced its head off. The beast revealed itself as a huge nine-tailed fox. Qu\u00e2n got into the cave and rescued everybody that was alive and tortured by the fox\n\n'''Descendant of Dragon and Fairy'''\n\nL\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n is a son of [[Long M\u1eabu Th\u1ea7n Long]], the dragon goddess that rules the sky and the ocean. \n\nL\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n was married to \u0110\u1ebf Lai's daughter, \u00c2u C\u01a1. She gave birth to a sac of a hundred eggs, which were hatched into a hundred boys. One day, Qu\u00e2n confessed to her: \"I am a descendant of the Dragon, you are descendant of the Fairy, fire and water cannot live together in harmony.\" The two of them then divided their children. Fifty sons followed their mother to the mountainous north, the other fifty followed their father to live in the south; these children are ancestor of B\u00e1ch Vi\u1ec7t. The oldest brother followed \u00c2u C\u01a1 to Phong Ch\u00e2u (Ph\u00fa Th\u1ecd), became Qu\u00e2n's successor and ruled as Hung King.<ref>http://myvietnamhandbook.com/vietnamese-culture/{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Linh Nam Chich Quai, Dai Viet Su Ky Toan Thu</ref>\n[[File:\u0110\u1ec1n th\u1edd L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n.jpg|thumb|250px|right|L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n's temple at Sim Hill (Ph\u00fa Th\u1ecd)]]\n[[image:\u0110\u1ec1n th\u1edd ch\u00ednh th\u1edd L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n.jpg|Small|250px|right|thumb| L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n 's temple at Sim hill.]]\n\n==Legacy==\nMost cities in Vietnam have named major streets after him.<ref>{{cite book| title=Vietnam Country Map |publisher=Periplus Travel Maps |year=2002\u20132003 |isbn=0-7946-0070-0}}</ref> He features both in primary education,<ref>Marie-Carine Lall, Edward Vickers - ''Education As a Political Tool in Asia'' - Page 143 2009 \"'Vietnamese-ness'. The history of the country really started around 800 bc with the V\u0103n Lang kingship. Children learn about the legends of the nation's birth, which feature heroic figures such as [[Kinh D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng]], [[\u00c2u C\u01a1]] \u2013 L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n ...\"</ref> and in some forms of popular religious belief as a god.<ref>Andrea Lauser, Kirsten W. Endres - ''Engaging the Spirit World: Popular Beliefs and Practices in Modern Vietnam'' 2012 - Page 93  \"of the Water Palace are linked to the mythical foundation of the country and they are considered to be descendants of the Dragon King of [[\u0110\u1ed9ng \u0110\u00ecnh]], father of the mythic founder of the country, L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n. Images from this past are enacted ...\"</ref><ref>Philip Taylor  ''Modernity and Re-Enchantment: Religion in Post-Revolutionary Vietnam'' Page 68  2007 \"According to legend, all Vietnamese people can trace their ancestry back to the marriage of the dragon father L\u1ea1c Long Qu\u00e2n and the fairy mother \u00c2u C\u01a1. This magical union produced an egg sac from which hatched one hundred human ...\"</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Vietnam|Mythology}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=rCl_02LnNVIC&pg=PA1&dq=%22lac+long+quan%22&sig=ACfU3U0mKRwsh2QROLWiZWFzktnledCrEg Google Books search]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=hDV-LJbKS_AC&pg=PA232&dq=%22lac+long+quan%22&sig=ACfU3U2YQr2ZM2O_SkfVjxyOskSXHB5Nkw  Google Books search]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=YgA1kBqOZYgC&pg=PA71&dq=%22lac+long+quan%22&sig=ACfU3U3_Ycg6qs4yuX6N-KnIisDX3uL-5A#PPA72,M1 Google Books search]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of monarchs of Vietnam]]\n*[[H\u1ed3ng B\u00e0ng Dynasty]]\n*[[Yue (state)]]\n*[[Goujian]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|H\u1ed3ng B\u00e0ng Dynasty||||}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kinh D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Vietnamese monarchs|King of V\u0103n Lang]]|years= 2793 BC \u2013 ? }}\n{{s-aft|after=H\u00f9ng Qu\u1ed1c V\u01b0\u01a1ng}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quan, Lac Long}}\n[[Category:28th-century BC rulers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Vietnam]]\n[[Category:H\u1ed3ng B\u00e0ng dynasty]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese culture]]\n", "name_user": "FriendDewey", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMythology:missing a period after \"Qu\u00e2n got into the cave and rescued everybody that was alive and tortured by the fox\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L%E1%BA%A1c_Long_Qu%C3%A2n"}
